/** Etymology data for lemma IDs in chunk 6 */
export const etymologyChunk6: Record<number, string> = {
  "2875": "فِرَارٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ر, with the root verb فَرَّ meaning \"he fled\" or \"he ran away.\" فِرَارٌ means \"flight,\" \"escape,\" or \"retreat.\" The connection lies in the act of fleeing from danger or adversity, embodying the root's concept of escape. This term highlights the urgency and necessity of withdrawal from threatening situations, highlighting reactions to fear or peril.",
  "2876": "فِرَاشٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ش, with the root verb فَرَشَ meaning \"he spread out\" or \"he laid out.\" فِرَاشٌ means \"bed\" or \"sleeping place.\" The connection lies in the item being spread out for rest, directly relating to the root's concept of laying out. This term emphasizes the provision of comfort and rest, highlighting the essential human need for sleep and the preparation involved in creating a restful space.",
  "2877": "فِرَاقٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ق, with the root verb فَرَقَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he divided.\" فِرَاقٌ means \"separation,\" \"parting,\" or \"departure.\" The connection lies in the act of leaving or parting ways, directly relating to the root's concept of division. This term emphasizes the emotional and physical aspects of separation, highlighting the impact of departure on relationships.",
  "2878": "فِرْدَوْسُ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-د-س, with فَرْدَسَةٌ meaning \"width\" or \"amplitude.\" فِرْدَوْسٌ refers to a beautiful, expansive garden, often described as containing grape-vines and palm trees. الفِرْدَوْسُ represents the highest level of Paradise and also carries the meaning of a walled garden or an enclosed area filled with lush trees and greenery. The connection lies in the concept of a vast, fertile space, symbolizing both the physical beauty and spiritual grandeur of Paradise. It reflects the abundance of rewards and blessings in the loftiest and most honored part of Paradise.",
  "2879": "فِرْعَوْنُ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ع, with the root verb فَرَعَ meaning \"he was high\" or \"he exalted himself.\" In the Qur'an, \"Fir'awn\" refers to a specific Pharaoh, the ruler of Egypt during the time of Prophet Moses (ﷺ). This Pharaoh is known for his arrogance, tyranny, and self-exaltation, defying Allah’s (ﷻ) commands and oppressing the Children of Israel. The connection lies in the root’s meaning of elevation and superiority, reflecting his attitude of self-glorification and dominance over his people and the Children of Israel.",
  "2880": "فِرْقٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ق, with the root verb فَرَقَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he divided.\" فِرْقٌ means \"part,\" \"portion,\" or \"division.\" The connection lies in a segment that has been separated from the whole, reflecting the root's idea of division. This term highlights the existence of distinct parts within a larger entity, emphasizing the importance of each segment in the overall structure.",
  "2881": "فِرْقَةٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ر-ق, with the root verb فَرَقَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he divided.\" فِرْقَةٌ means \"group,\" \"sect,\" or \"faction.\" The connection lies in a subset that has been separated from a larger group, reflecting the root's concept of division. This term emphasizes the formation of distinct factions, highlighting how divisions can lead to separate identities within a community.",
  "2882": "فِسْقٌ and related words stem from the root ف-س-ق, with the root verb فَسَقَ meaning \"he transgressed,\" \"he deviated,\" or \"he committed immorality.\" فِسْقٌ means \"immorality\" or \"sinful deviation,\" specifically referring to the quality or state of moral disobedience. فِسْقٌ emphasizes the inherent condition or nature of deviating from divine or moral commandments. This term highlights the seriousness of such a state, emphasizing the spiritual and ethical consequences of turning away from righteousness.",
  "2883": "فِصَالٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ص-ل, with the root verb فَصَلَ meaning \"he separated\" or \"he divided.\" فِصَالٌ means \"weaning,\" specifically the process of separating a child from breastfeeding. The connection lies in the act of separation between mother and child, reflecting the root's emphasis on division. This term signifies a significant developmental milestone, highlighting the natural progression toward independence.",
  "2884": "فِضَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ض-ض, with the root verb فَضَّ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he scattered,\" or \"he dispersed.\" فِضَّةٌ means \"silver,\" the precious metal known for its purity and value. The root conveys themes of breaking or separating, which connects to silver’s malleability and its ability to be divided into smaller pieces. فِضَّةٌ reflects both material wealth and symbolic purity, tying to the root’s essence of dispersion and refinement, highlighting its versatility and utility in various forms.",
  "2885": "فِطْرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ط-ر, with the root verb فَطَرَ meaning \"he created\" or \"he originated.\" فِطْرَةٌ means \"innate nature,\" \"natural disposition,\" or \"primordial state.\" The connection lies in the original creation or the inherent nature instilled at creation, reflecting the root's emphasis on originating. This term refers to the pure, natural state in which humans are created by Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the inherent inclination toward faith and goodness.",
  "2886": "فِعْلٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ع-ل, with the root verb فَعَلَ meaning \"he did\" or \"he acted.\" فِعْلٌ means \"doing,\" \"action,\" or \"deed,\" referring to the process or act of performing something. The root conveys themes of activity and execution, with فِعْلٌ representing a general or abstract sense of action. Grammatically, فِعْلٌ is also a verbal noun (مَصْدَر), denoting the concept of performing an action.",
  "2887": "The particle فِي means \"in,\" \"inside,\" or \"within\" and is essential for denoting physical location, such as something being contained or situated within a space. For example, it can describe an object physically being in a room or within a boundary. Beyond its physical aspect, فِي also expresses time, condition, or state. In the Qur'anic context, فِي is often used to highlight immersion in specific states, environments, or concepts, such as being in error, in guidance, or in a state of gratitude. Its usage emphasizes depth, inclusiveness, and the encompassing nature of certain realities.",
  "2888": "فِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ف-ي-ل, which refers to \"an elephant.\" The elephant symbolizes great size and strength, reflecting its majestic and formidable characteristics that highlight power and might. In the Qur'an, the story of the People of the Elephant demonstrates Allah's (ﷻ) protection over the Kaaba, illustrating His supreme power over even the strongest creatures.",
  "2889": "قَائِلُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-ي-ل, with the root verb قَالَ meaning \"he slept at midday.\" The root conveys the concept of resting, particularly during the hottest part of the day. قَائِلُونَ means \"ones who sleep at midday\" or \"those resting at noon,\" reflecting the practice of resting to rejuvenate oneself. This term emphasizes the cultural significance of midday rest as a time for physical and mental renewal.",
  "2890": "قائِمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root encompasses concepts of standing upright, rising, maintaining, and supporting. قائِمٌ means \"standing,\" \"one who stands,\" or \"one who maintains.\" It describes someone or something in a state of standing, being upright, or actively maintaining a position. The term embodies the root's essence of uprightness, presence, and stability. Beyond physical standing, it signifies upholding or supporting responsibilities, steadfastness in truth, and oversight, particularly in contexts where maintaining stability and support are essential.",
  "2891": "قائِمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys concepts of standing upright, rising, and establishing, emphasizing notions of firmness, stability, and being upright. قائِمَةٌ means \"standing\" or \"established,\" reflecting the state of being upright or firmly positioned. Derived from the act of standing, it also carries broader implications of being present, enduring, or actively maintaining something. In various contexts, قائِمَةٌ signifies not just physical standing but also the establishment or maintenance of principles, conditions, or entities.",
  "2892": "قَابٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ب, with the root verb قَابَ meaning \"he was, or became near,\" \"he drew near,\" or \"he approached.\" قَابٌ refers to \"a measure\" or \"a distance,\" specifically the length of a bow, symbolizing a defined span or quantifiable space. The root conveys themes of nearness, measurement, and bridging or quantifying spatial separation. قَابٌ illustrates how space and distance, whether physical or metaphorical, can be bridged or reduced, often reflecting closeness in relationships or interactions. The term deeply embodies the root’s essence of bringing what is distant closer, emphasizing nearness, connection, and relational measures.",
  "2893": "قَابِلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قَابِلٌ means \"accepting\" or \"receptive,\" embodying the characteristic of being willing to receive or embrace something. The connection to the root lies in the active quality of openness and readiness, emphasizing a positive attitude toward ideas, guidance, or responsibilities. قَابِلٌ illustrates the root’s themes of intentional engagement and willingness, highlighting the value of being prepared to accept and respond in a constructive and gracious manner.",
  "2894": "قَاتَلَ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, with the root verb قَتَلَ meaning \"he killed.\" قَاتَلَ means \"he fought\" or \"he engaged in battle.\" The connection lies in mutual engagement in killing or combat, extending the root's concept to active fighting. It emphasizes participation in warfare or conflict, highlighting the struggle between opposing forces and the gravity of such confrontations.",
  "2895": "قَادِرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he had power over.\" قَادِرٌ means \"one who is capable\" or \"one who has power,\" reflecting the ability to measure, control, and determine outcomes. ٱلْقَادِرُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The All-Powerful,\" highlighting His absolute authority and limitless capability over all creation. It emphasizes His omnipotence and ability to accomplish all that He wills, reminding us to rely on His unmatched power in all matters and to trust in His ability to overcome any obstacle.",
  "2896": "قَارُونُ refers to Korah, a wealthy man from the people of Prophet Moses (ﷺ) who opposed him. In Hebrew, Korah (קרח) comes from the root קרח (qārach), meaning \"bald\" or \"ice,\" symbolizing both physical baldness and metaphorical barrenness or coldness. This reflects Qārūn's spiritual emptiness and arrogance, as he attributed his wealth to his own knowledge. In the Qur'an, his story highlights the consequences of pride and rebellion, where his cold, defiant nature led to his downfall, with the earth swallowing him and his treasures as punishment.",
  "2897": "قارِعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ع, with the root verb قَرَعَ meaning \"he struck,\" \"he knocked,\" or \"he beat.\" قارِعَةٌ refers to a \"calamity\" or \"striking event,\" capturing the sudden and forceful nature of an impactful occurrence. The term conveys the image of something striking with such intensity that it demands immediate attention and evokes awe or fear. In the Qur'an, \"القارِعَةُ\" refers to the Day of Judgment, highlighting its abrupt, overwhelming nature that will metaphorically \"knock\" on hearts. This term serves as a powerful reminder of accountability, urging reflection and preparation for the certainty of that momentous event, which will leave no heart unmoved.",
  "2898": "قاسَمَ and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided\" or \"he swore an oath.\" قاسَمَ means \"he swore to someone\" or \"he shared with someone,\" emphasizing direct engagement in a solemn promise or shared commitment. The connection lies in the deliberate and reciprocal nature of the act, reflecting mutual understanding and trust. This term highlights themes of shared responsibility, sincerity, and the seriousness of making promises or agreements, highlighting the importance of integrity in interpersonal relationships.",
  "2899": "قَاسِطُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-س-ط, with the root verb قَسَطَ meaning \"he was unjust\" or \"he deviated from fairness.\" قَاسِطُونَ refers to \"unjust persons\" or \"oppressors,\" emphasizing those who actively engage in acts of injustice or deviate from the path of fairness. This term highlights themes of deviation, imbalance, and oppression, symbolizing individuals who disregard principles of equity and fairness. It serves as a reminder of the consequences of straying from just conduct, contrasting with the ideal of fairness and accountability embedded in the broader root.",
  "2900": "قَاسِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-و, with the root verb قَسَا meaning \"he was hard\" or \"he became unfeeling.\" قَاسِيَةٌ refers to something \"hard,\" \"unyielding,\" or \"callous,\" often describing a heart or attitude that is unresponsive or insensitive. The connection lies in the concept of rigidity, where hardness prevents receptiveness or change. This term reflects the danger of becoming detached or indifferent, emphasizing the importance of maintaining softness and openness, particularly in matters of faith and compassion.",
  "2901": "قَاصِدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-د, with the root verb قَصَدَ meaning \"he intended,\" \"he aimed,\" or \"he directed himself.\" قَاصِدٌ refers to \"one who intends,\" \"one who aims,\" or \"one who takes a straightforward path.\" The connection lies in the deliberate and focused nature of the action, emphasizing purpose and direction. This term reflects themes of clarity and determination, where intent is aligned with purposeful action. It can also convey the idea of moderation and taking a middle course, highlighting the importance of balance in pursuit of one’s objectives. The root highlights the significance of intention as the foundation of meaningful and measured effort.",
  "2902": "قَاصِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ر, with the root verb قَصَرَ meaning \"he confined,\" \"he restricted,\" or \"he shortened.\" قَاصِرَةٌ refers to \"a modest or restrained woman,\" often implying one who lowers or restrains her gaze, symbolizing self-control and dignity. The connection lies in the concept of limiting or restricting, whether in physical actions, such as confining one’s gaze, or in behavior, reflecting modesty and restraint. This term highlights themes of self-discipline, refinement, and a deliberate choice to adhere to principles of decorum and virtue, embodying the broader root emphasis on measured actions and boundaries.",
  "2903": "قاصِفٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ف, with the root verb قَصَفَ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he shattered,\" or \"he crushed.\" قاصِفٌ means \"breaking violently\" or \"crushing.\" This term often describes a storm or wind that violently destroys, embodying the root's emphasis on overwhelming force leading to destruction. The connection is evident in the destructive force implied by the root, symbolizing something that breaks or smashes with great power.",
  "2904": "قاضٍ and related words stem from the root ق-ض-ي, with the root verb قَضَىٰ meaning \"he decreed,\" \"he judged,\" or \"he completed.\" قاضٍ refers to a \"judge\" or \"one who decides,\" emphasizing the act of making authoritative decisions or bringing matters to a definitive resolution. The connection lies in the role of determining outcomes, reflecting themes of judgment, authority, and fulfillment. The root highlights the importance of decisiveness, fairness, and the capacity to bring closure, illustrating the weight and responsibility carried by one who judges or decides.",
  "2905": "قاضِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ض-ي, with the root verb قَضَىٰ meaning \"he decreed,\" \"he judged,\" or \"he completed.\" قاضِيَةٌ refers to a \"decisive event,\" highlighting something that brings matters to a final, unavoidable conclusion. The connection lies in the definitive nature of the event, emphasizing themes of finality, resolution, and the profound impact of an unalterable outcome. The root reflects the gravity of decisive occurrences that leave no room for reversal or hesitation, symbolizing the ultimate completion of a matter.",
  "2906": "قاطِعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" قاطِعَةٌ means \"one that cuts off\" or \"decisive,\" highlighting an action or entity that brings something to a clear and definitive end. The connection lies in the deliberate and resolute act of cutting or separating, symbolizing a decisive moment or action. This root emphasizes themes of finality, determination, and separation, whether physical, emotional, or metaphorical. قاطِعَةٌ highlights the power of decisive actions to create distinct divisions or conclusions, reflecting the impact and permanence of such moments in life and relationships.",
  "2907": "قَاعٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ع, with the root verb قَاعَ meaning \"it was low\" or \"it was depressed.\" قَاعٌ refers to a \"level plain\" or \"flat expanse,\" describing open and unobstructed landscapes that are devoid of elevation or barriers. It conveys themes of emptiness and simplicity, symbolizing spaces stripped of adornment or obstruction, leaving behind a stark and clear expanse. The term emphasizes unimpeded flatness, evoking the imagery of complete exposure and an absence of complexity.",
  "2908": "قَاعِدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-د, with the root verb قَعَدَ meaning \"he sat,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" قَاعِدٌ refers to \"one who sits\" or \"one who remains behind,\" highlighting a state of being stationary or refraining from action. The connection lies in the act of sitting, symbolizing inactivity, stillness, or hesitation. Depending on the context, it can reflect neutrality, as in choosing to rest, or reluctance, as in staying behind when action is expected. The root emphasizes the duality of remaining in place, whether as a deliberate and purposeful pause or as a sign of avoidance or inaction.",
  "2909": "قَالِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ي, with the root verb قَلَىٰ meaning \"he hated,\" \"he detested,\" or \"he became estranged from.\" قَالِينَ means \"those who detest\" or \"those who harbor aversion.\" This term embodies the root's concept of intense dislike and emotional distancing from someone or something.",
  "2910": "قَالَ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"he said\" or \"he spoke.\" The root encompasses broader meanings of expressing, declaring, and conveying thoughts or ideas through speech. It emphasizes verbal communication in various forms, whether to inform, command, question, or narrate. The root also conveys intention and deliberation, reflecting how spoken words often stem from thought or purpose. قَالَ highlights the significance of language as a tool for connection, understanding, and influence, emphasizing the power and responsibility of speech to build, guide, or harm, depending on its use and intent.",
  "2911": "قامَ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he stood,\" \"he rose,\" or \"he became upright.\" It describes the action of moving from a lower position to an upright stance. The root conveys themes of uprightness, establishment, maintenance, and readiness, symbolizing stability and strength. قامَ directly reflects the root's emphasis on standing as both a physical act and a metaphor for preparedness, maintaining order, or fulfilling responsibilities. This verb forms the foundation for numerous derivatives, extending its meaning to encompass rising to challenges, upholding justice, and sustaining balance, embodying the root’s essence of steadfastness and alignment.",
  "2912": "قَانِتٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ت, with the root verb قَنَتَ meaning \"he was obedient,\" \"he stood in long prayer,\" or \"he remained steadfast in devotion.\" قَانِتٌ means \"devoutly obedient\" or \"steadfast worshipper,\" describing a person committed to consistent worship and submission to Allah (ﷻ). The root conveys themes of unwavering devotion, humility, and steadfastness, emphasizing prolonged acts of worship and obedience. قَانِتٌ reflects the embodiment of these qualities, symbolizing a life directed toward sincere and continuous submission.",
  "2913": "قَانِتَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ت, with the root verb قَنَتَ meaning \"he was obedient,\" \"he stood in prolonged prayer,\" or \"he remained steadfast in devotion.\" قَانِتَاتٌ means \"devoutly obedient\" or \"steadfast worshippers,\" specifically referring to women committed to acts of prolonged worship and submission to Allah (ﷻ). The root emphasizes devotion, humility, and consistency in worship, and قَانِتَاتٌ embodies these qualities in the context of female piety and steadfastness. This term reflects the broader theme of unwavering obedience and humility as central to acts of worship.",
  "2914": "قَانِطِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ط, with the root verb قَنَطَ meaning \"he despaired\" or \"he lost hope.\" قَانِطِينَ means \"despairing\" or \"hopeless,\" describing individuals overcome by despondency and emotional defeat. The root conveys themes of deep despair, often linked to prolonged hardship or unmet expectations. This term emphasizes the peril of losing trust in Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy, portraying despair as a spiritual weakness that contradicts the Qur'anic ideal of unwavering hope and trust in Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom. It serves as a reminder of the importance of faith and the dangers of allowing hardship to overshadow belief in Allah’s (ﷻ) wisdom and boundless mercy.",
  "2915": "قَانِعٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ع, with the root verb قَنِعَ meaning \"he was content,\" \"he was satisfied,\" or \"he accepted.\" قَانِعٌ means \"content,\" \"satisfied,\" or \"accepting,\" and can also refer to \"a contented poor person who does not beg but is satisfied with what is given voluntarily,\" reflecting both inner contentment and dignity. The root also includes قَنَعَ, meaning \"he raised up\" or \"he held upright,\" indicating dignity alongside acceptance. This duality highlights the balance between gratitude for what one has and humility to accept help. قَانِعٌ emphasizes humility and gratitude as essential for inner peace and balance.",
  "2916": "قَاهِرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ه-ر, with the root verb قَهَرَ meaning \"he subdued\" or \"he overpowered.\" قَاهِرٌ means \"subduer\" or \"conqueror,\" describing one who overcomes or dominates. The root emphasizes themes of power, control, and overcoming opposition. قَاهِرٌ embodies the essence of dominance and mastery, whether in physical, metaphorical, or spiritual contexts, highlighting the ability to prevail over challenges or adversaries.",
  "2917": "قَبَائِلُ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قَبَائِلُ means \"tribes,\" referring to groups of people bound together by common ancestry, culture, or purpose. The connection lies in the root’s theme of meeting or facing, symbolizing how tribes come together in unity and mutual support. قَبَائِلُ highlights the structure and identity of communities, emphasizing their role in fostering collective strength and providing social cohesion. This reflects the root’s broader concept of connection and interaction.",
  "2918": "قَبَسٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-س, with the root verb قَبَسَ meaning \"he took fire\" or \"he borrowed a flame.\" قَبَسٌ means \"a brand,\" \"a torch,\" or \"a borrowed flame.\" The connection lies in the act of taking or borrowing light from another source, reflecting the root's concept of seeking illumination. It symbolizes the quest for knowledge or guidance, as one seeks light to dispel darkness, emphasizing the importance of shared wisdom and enlightenment.",
  "2919": "قَبُولٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قَبُولٌ means \"acceptance\" or \"approval,\" reflecting the act of willingly receiving or agreeing to something. The connection to the root lies in the idea of openness and readiness to acknowledge or embrace what is offered. قَبُولٌ emphasizes the importance of acceptance in building relationships, fostering harmony, and fulfilling obligations, whether in personal, social, or spiritual contexts, reflecting the root’s core idea of intentional and sincere receptiveness.",
  "2920": "قَبِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قَبِيلٌ means \"group\" or \"kind,\" referring to a collection of individuals who come together or share common traits. The connection to the root verb lies in the idea of willingly receiving or admitting others into an association or gathering, while the broader root meaning reflects meeting and mutual engagement. قَبِيلٌ highlights unity and shared purpose, illustrating how individuals or entities are connected through commonalities.",
  "2921": "قَبْرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ر, with the root verb قَبَرَ meaning \"he buried.\" قَبْرٌ means \"grave\" or \"tomb.\" The connection is direct, as the grave is where one is buried, embodying the root's meaning. It symbolizes the final resting place and serves as a reminder of mortality and the transient nature of life, encouraging reflection on one's deeds and the hereafter.",
  "2922": "قَبْضٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ض, with the root verb قَبَضَ meaning \"he grasped.\" قَبْضٌ means \"grasping\" or \"seizing.\" The connection is direct, representing the act of grasping, embodying the root's concept. It symbolizes control and possession, highlighting the dynamics of giving and withholding.",
  "2923": "قَبْضَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ض, with the root verb قَبَضَ meaning \"he grasped.\" قَبْضَةٌ means \"a handful\" or \"a grasp.\" The connection lies in the amount that can be held in a closed hand, directly relating to the root's concept of grasping. It represents a measure of quantity under control, symbolizing possession and the limited nature of one's hold over material things.",
  "2924": "قَبْلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قَبْلٌ means \"before\" or \"in front of,\" denoting precedence in time or position. The connection lies in the idea of being ahead, either temporally or spatially, directly reflecting the root’s concept of facing or being at the forefront. قَبْلٌ highlights the themes of priority, anteriority, and readiness, illustrating the root’s broader application in expressing forwardness, precedence, and intentional positioning.",
  "2925": "قَتَرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ر, with the root verb قَتَرَ meaning \"he was stingy.\" قَتَرٌ means \"dust,\" symbolizing a state of barrenness, dryness, or lack of abundance. The connection lies in the notion of constriction and limitation, as dust represents the absence of fertility or growth, much like stinginess reflects a withholding nature that prevents generosity or flourishing. Dust also symbolizes darkness, gloom, and distress, evoking a sense of sorrow or humiliation, further emphasizing the theme of deprivation and scarcity, both physically and metaphorically, highlighting the consequences of withholding or restricting.",
  "2926": "قَتَرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ر, with the root verb قَتَرَ meaning \"he was stingy.\" قَتَرَةٌ means \"smoke,\" \"gloom,\" or \"darkness,\" reflecting an obscured or oppressive state. The connection to stinginess lies in the idea of withholding light or clarity, akin to the figurative darkness brought about by a miserly or constricted spirit. Just as smoke clouds vision or creates a sense of heaviness, stinginess limits opportunities for illumination and ease, emphasizing the broader impact of such traits on individuals and their surroundings.",
  "2927": "قَتَلَ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, and as the root verb, it means \"he killed.\" The essence of this root lies in the act of taking life, emphasizing deliberate action and its consequences. The word قَتَلَ conveys the finality and gravity of killing, whether in the context of personal acts or broader circumstances such as conflict or punishment. Rooted in the themes of termination and destruction, قَتَلَ highlights the profound impact of such actions on individuals and communities, highlighting the weight and seriousness associated with this act.",
  "2928": "قَتُورٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ر, with the root verb قَتَرَ meaning \"he was stingy.\" قَتُورٌ specifically means \"stingy\" or \"miserly,\" directly embodying the essence of the root. This word captures the behavior of withholding and restricting resources, emphasizing the constricted and ungenerous nature of such actions. The root's theme of limitation is fully realized in قَتُورٌ, reflecting the impact of stinginess in preventing abundance and creating an atmosphere of deprivation, whether material, emotional, or social.",
  "2929": "قَتْلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, with the root verb قَتَلَ meaning \"he killed.\" قَتْلٌ means \"killing\" or \"slaying.\" The connection is direct, representing the act or process of killing, embodying the root's concept. It emphasizes the seriousness of taking life, highlighting the consequences and ethical considerations surrounding violence.",
  "2930": "قَتْلَىٰ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, with the root verb قَتَلَ meaning \"he killed.\" قَتْلَىٰ (plural of قَتِيلٌ) means \"the slain\" or \"those killed.\" The word signifies those who have lost their lives as a direct result of violence or conflict. The root carries the theme of ending life, and قَتْلَىٰ embodies this concept in its application to groups of individuals. This highlights the profound loss and devastation caused by killing, with a focus on its effects not only on individuals but also on the larger community, highlighting the human cost of violence and its lasting impact.",
  "2931": "قَدَرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" قَدَرٌ means \"destiny,\" \"fate,\" or \"divine decree.\" The connection lies in the concept of measured determination and precise ordainment of events, reflecting the root's emphasis on measurement and determination. This term encapsulates the idea that all occurrences are determined and measured by a higher authority, highlighting the meticulousness of divine planning and the unfolding of predetermined events.",
  "2932": "قَدَرَ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" This verb encapsulates the act of assigning precise measures, limits, or determinations, reflecting themes of control, precision, and intentionality. The root conveys the concept of defining or apportioning with accuracy, whether in physical measurements, the establishment of decrees, or the determination of destinies. It highlights the importance of balance, order, and divine wisdom in the arrangement of all matters, emphasizing both human actions of measurement and Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme authority in decreeing outcomes with perfect justice and precision.",
  "2933": "قَدَمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-م, with the root verb قَدُمَ meaning \"he was ancient\" or \"he preceded.\" قَدَمٌ means \"foot\" or \"footstep,\" emphasizing the role of the foot in facilitating movement and advancement. The connection lies in the foot being a foundational means of progressing forward, directly reflecting the root's concept of proceeding or being at the forefront. This term symbolizes advancement, stability, or the act of stepping ahead, highlighting themes of progress and foundation. In the context of the expression قَدَمَ صِدْقٍ, it denotes a position of honor and integrity earned through one’s actions, signifying a foundation of sincerity and integrity that leads to positive outcomes.",
  "2934": "قَدِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he had power over.\" قَدِيرٌ is an intensive form meaning \"All-Powerful,\" \"Omnipotent,\" or \"Most Capable,\" denoting absolute authority and control. The term reflects the ability to measure, determine, and execute with precision, aligning with the root’s emphasis on power and mastery. قَدِيرٌ is exclusively attributed to Allah (ﷻ) in the Qur'an, highlighting His limitless control, unmatched perfection, and ultimate power over all matters. It signifies complete reliance on His supreme authority and the submission owed to His will.",
  "2935": "قَدِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-م, with the root verb قَدُمَ meaning \"he was ancient\" or \"he preceded.\" قَدِيمٌ means \"old,\" \"ancient,\" or \"eternal.\" The connection lies in the concept of existing from earlier times or being timeless, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on precedence and antiquity. This term highlights the notion of age, enduring existence, or timelessness, emphasizing the attribute of having existed long before.",
  "2936": "قَدَّرَ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" قَدَّرَ means \"he predetermined,\" \"he ordained,\" or \"he destined,\" emphasizing a deliberate and intensified act of measuring or determining. This form signifies precise and purposeful planning, reflecting the root’s themes of measurement, determination, and setting limits. The term highlights the concept of predestination and the meticulous establishment of measures or outcomes, whether in physical, temporal, or spiritual contexts. It conveys the idea of intentionality and divine wisdom in the establishment of order, balance, and destiny.",
  "2937": "قَدَّمَ and related words stem from the root ق-د-م, with the root verb قَدُمَ meaning \"he was ancient\" or \"he preceded.\" قَدَّمَ means \"he put forward,\" \"he advanced,\" or \"he presented,\" emphasizing the act of prioritizing or bringing something to the forefront. ٱلْمُقَدِّمُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Advancer\" or \"The One Who Brings Forward,\" reflecting His authority to advance, promote, or prioritize whomever or whatever He wills. This name highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect control over the sequence, timing, and order of all events, reminding us to trust in His divine wisdom and rely on His guidance in seeking advancement or success in all matters.",
  "2938": "قَدْحٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ح, with the root verb قَدَحَ meaning \"he kindled,\" \"he struck fire by friction,\" \"he criticized,\" or \"he wounded.\" قَدْحٌ refers to \"the act of striking,\" \"shooting arrows,\" or \"sharp critique.\" The root conveys themes of ignition, sharpness, and precision, whether through physical actions like kindling fire or metaphorical actions like wounding with words or arrows. The connection lies in the forceful and intentional nature of these acts, emphasizing the initiation of effects, whether by generating sparks, launching arrows, or delivering sharp critique.",
  "2939": "قَدْرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" قَدْرٌ means \"measure,\" \"amount,\" \"value,\" or \"degree,\" emphasizing precision in assigning worth or extent. In the context of لَيْلَةُ الْقَدْرِ (the Night of Decree), it reflects the immense significance of this night, when Allah (ﷻ) decrees matters for the year. It signifies divine wisdom, precise determination, and the unparalleled value of worship and devotion during this sacred time, highlighting themes of measurement, worth, and spiritual elevation.",
  "2940": "قَذَفَ and related words stem from the root ق-ذ-ف, and as the root verb, it means \"he threw,\" \"he hurled,\" or \"he cast.\" This includes both physical actions, such as throwing an object, and metaphorical casting, such as instilling something into the heart or mind. The term reflects the deliberate projection of something with force or intention, whether it involves a false accusation, an emotion like fear or awe, or a physical act. The root emphasizes impactful actions or expressions, highlighting both tangible and intangible ways something can be forcefully imparted. It highlights themes of influence and consequence, revealing how deliberate actions can deeply affect individuals and communities.",
  "2941": "قَرَارٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ر, with the root verb قَرَّ meaning \"he settled,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he became cool.\" قَرَارٌ means \"settlement,\" \"stability,\" or \"resting place,\" and can also denote \"depth\" or \"foundation.\" The connection lies in embodying the root's concept of settling and stability, representing a place or state of permanence and security. This term highlights the importance of having a firm foundation and the comfort found in stability, whether physical or spiritual.",
  "2942": "قَرَأَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-أ, meaning \"he read,\" \"he recited,\" or \"he gathered.\" قَرَأَ means \"he recited\" or \"he read aloud.\" The connection lies in the act of bringing together letters and words to convey meaning, directly reflecting the root's concepts of gathering and recitation. This term emphasizes the importance of conveying knowledge, sharing messages, and the oral tradition of transmitting texts.",
  "2943": "قَرِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" قَرِيبٌ means \"near,\" \"close,\" or \"a relative,\" reflecting nearness in physical proximity, time, or relationships. Broader root meanings emphasize closeness and connection, whether spatial, temporal, or familial. The connection lies in the embodiment of nearness, symbolizing intimacy, kinship, or immediacy. This term highlights the root’s focus on reducing barriers and fostering closeness, whether in human relationships, spiritual connections, or the proximity of events.",
  "2944": "قَرِينٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ن, with the root verb قَرَنَ meaning \"he coupled,\" \"he joined,\" or \"he connected.\" قَرِينٌ means \"companion\" or \"close associate.\" The connection lies in proximity, emphasizing the influence of being closely linked to someone, whether positively or negatively. قَرِينٌ reflects the idea of shared influence, where one’s behavior often mirrors that of their companions. In the Qur'an, this term highlights how companionship shapes behavior, guiding one towards righteousness or misguidance.",
  "2945": "قَرَّبَ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" قَرَّبَ means \"he brought near\" or \"he made closer,\" emphasizing deliberate action to reduce distance or create nearness. Broader root meanings highlight physical proximity, nearness in rank or status, and drawing closer in relationships or spirituality. The connection lies in actively facilitating closeness, whether through physical movement, offerings, or actions that elevate proximity in status or devotion.",
  "2946": "قَرْحٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ح, with the root verb قَرَحَ meaning \"he wounded\" or \"he inflicted injury.\" قَرْحٌ means \"wound\" or \"injury,\" referring to both physical and metaphorical damage. The connection lies in the root's focus on inflicting harm, representing not only the physical wounds sustained in conflict but also the deeper emotional or spiritual injuries one might experience. Broader root meanings highlight the concept of suffering, loss, and the impact of harm, whether through external causes or internal struggles.",
  "2947": "قَرْضٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ض, with the root verb قَرَضَ meaning \"he cut off,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he lent.\" قَرْضٌ means \"loan\" or \"something cut off.\" The connection lies in lending being like cutting off a part of one's wealth to assist others. This reflects the sacrifice and generosity inherent in giving a loan, emphasizing trust in Allah's (ﷻ) recompense. In the Qur'an, the term قَرْضٌ حَسَنٌ (\"a goodly loan\") symbolizes sincere charitable acts done purely for Allah's (ﷻ) sake.",
  "2948": "قَرْنٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ن, with the root verb قَرَنَ meaning \"he coupled\" or \"he joined.\" قَرْنٌ means \"generation,\" \"century,\" or \"horn.\" The connection lies in things being linked or occurring together. As a \"generation,\" it signifies people bound by time, with continuity and shared experiences. As a \"horn,\" it symbolizes something prominent, like a visible sign, highlighting how generations, like horns, are distinct and clearly connected to the past and future. The broader root meanings emphasize unity, continuity, and visibility across time.",
  "2949": "قَرْيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ى, with the root verb قَرَىٰ meaning \"he gathered together,\" \"he collected,\" or \"he offered provisions.\" قَرْيَةٌ, meaning \"village\" or \"town,\" embodies the concept of gathering, as villages are centers where people come together to live, form communities, and share resources. The root meaning highlights the essential role of collective living, emphasizing how villages foster mutual care, hospitality, and social cohesion.",
  "2950": "قَسَتْ and related words stem from the root ق-س-و, with the root verb قَسَا meaning \"he became hard\" or \"he was harsh.\" قَسَتْ means \"she became hard\" or \"it hardened,\" signifying the process of becoming unyielding or resistant. The connection highlights the gradual hardening of hearts, particularly in a spiritual context, where neglect of divine guidance and repeated rejection of truth can lead to insensitivity. This term highlights the importance of remaining receptive to guidance and avoiding actions that cause emotional or spiritual rigidity.",
  "2951": "قَسَمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided,\" \"he apportioned,\" or \"he swore an oath.\" قَسَمٌ means \"oath\" or \"division,\" emphasizing both the solemnity of making a binding promise and the careful distribution of portions. The connection lies in the root's focus on precision and accountability, whether in words or actions. This term highlights the importance of fairness and trustworthiness, reflecting the weight of commitments and the need to uphold balance and justice in all dealings.",
  "2952": "قَسَمْنَا and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided\" or \"he swore an oath.\" قَسَمْنَا means \"we divided\" or \"we apportioned,\" emphasizing the act of distributing or assigning portions. The connection lies in the deliberate and methodical allocation of resources, responsibilities, or shares. This term highlights themes of fairness, precision, and the fulfillment of obligations in distribution, reflecting the importance of balance and accountability in ensuring justice and equity.",
  "2953": "قَسْوَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-و, with the root verb قَسَا meaning \"he was hard\" or \"he became harsh.\" قَسْوَةٌ means \"hardness\" or \"cruelty,\" describing a state of being unfeeling, merciless, or disconnected. The connection lies in the absence of softness or empathy, which fosters injustice and alienation. This term warns against developing such traits, emphasizing the need for compassion, sensitivity, and a heart that remains responsive to truth and the needs of others.",
  "2954": "قَسْوَرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-ر, with the root verb قَسَرَ meaning \"he forced,\" \"he subdued,\" or \"he overpowered.\" قَسْوَرَةٌ refers to \"lion,\" \"hunter,\" or \"archer,\" symbolizing strength, dominance, and the ability to subdue or overpower. The term conveys attributes of majesty and fear-inspiring presence, reflecting overwhelming power. It is used metaphorically to draw an analogy, comparing those who avoid truth to wild donkeys fleeing in irrational panic from a powerful and intimidating presence. This highlights themes of fear, authority, and the instinctive reactions provoked by awe or perceived danger.",
  "2955": "قَصَصٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ص, with the root verb قَصَّ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he traced,\" or \"he narrated.\" قَصَصٌ means \"stories\" or \"narratives.\" The connection lies in the act of tracing or following closely, much like following a path or footsteps, which mirrors how a story unfolds by following events in sequence. The root emphasizes precision and continuity, reflecting the meticulous recounting of events that compose a narrative. In the Qur'an, قَصَصٌ refers to the stories of previous peoples and prophets, providing lessons by closely tracing their experiences.",
  "2956": "قَصَمْنَا and related words stem from the root ق-ص-م, with the root verb قَصَمَ meaning \"he broke,\" \"he shattered,\" or \"he snapped.\" قَصَمْنَا translates to \"we broke\" or \"we destroyed,\" indicating a forceful and decisive act of breaking. The connection lies in the sudden and complete destruction or downfall of something, often implying an irreversible state. The root emphasizes abrupt and total ruin, highlighting the fragility of structures or entities when subjected to overwhelming force.",
  "2957": "قَصِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ي, with the root verb قَصَا meaning \"it was distant\" or \"it became remote.\" قَصِيٌّ means \"remote,\" \"far away,\" or \"distant,\" emphasizing a state of separation or removal in space or time. The connection lies in the notion of being physically, emotionally, or metaphorically distanced from something, creating barriers or challenges to closeness or accessibility. The root reflects themes of remoteness, detachment, and inaccessibility, highlighting the significance of distance in altering relationships, interactions, or objectives. This term highlights the impact of being far removed, whether in terms of physical location, emotional connection, or spiritual proximity.",
  "2958": "قَصَّ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ص, with the root verb قَصَّ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he trimmed,\" \"he followed closely,\" or \"he narrated.\" The connection between cutting and narrating lies in the idea of carefully selecting and arranging details, much like shaping material to achieve precision. The root emphasizes meticulousness and attentiveness, reflecting the deliberate effort required to convey a story accurately. This highlights the importance of precision and clarity in communication, ensuring knowledge and wisdom are transmitted faithfully and effectively.",
  "2959": "قَصْدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-د, with the root verb قَصَدَ meaning \"he intended.\" قَصْدٌ means \"intention,\" \"aim,\" or \"moderation,\" reflecting the idea of purposeful direction and a balanced approach. The connection lies in the deliberate effort to focus on a specific goal while avoiding excess or deficiency. This term highlights the importance of having clear intentions and maintaining equilibrium in one’s actions, promoting a thoughtful and focused pursuit of objectives, free from extremes.",
  "2960": "قَصْرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ر, with the root verb قَصَرَ meaning \"he confined,\" \"he restricted,\" or \"he shortened.\" قَصْرٌ translates to \"palace,\" \"castle,\" or \"mansion,\" denoting a grand and often fortified structure. The connection lies in the concept of an enclosed and protected space, symbolizing both magnificence and confinement. Such structures are typically designed to limit access, providing security and exclusivity, which reflects the root's emphasis on restriction and limitation.",
  "2961": "قَضَىٰ and related words stem from the root ق-ض-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he decreed,\" \"he judged,\" \"he decided,\" or \"he completed.\" This verb emphasizes the act of bringing something to a decisive conclusion, reflecting themes of authority, resolution, and fulfillment. The root conveys the power to determine outcomes with certainty and the capacity to bring matters to their destined completion. It symbolizes a definitive and unalterable decision, highlighting the importance of judgment, order, and the finality of actions.",
  "2962": "قَضْبٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ض-ب, with the root verb قَضَبَ meaning \"he cut off,\" \"he clipped,\" or \"he lopped.\" قَضْبٌ refers to \"fresh herbage\" or \"green fodder\" that is cut for animals. The connection lies in the act of cutting or trimming plants to provide nourishment. The root emphasizes the action of severing or harvesting vegetation, highlighting the human role in cultivating and preparing natural resources for sustenance. This term highlights the relationship between deliberate agricultural practices and the provision of food, reflecting the importance of responsible stewardship of the environment.",
  "2963": "قَطِرَانٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ر, with the root verb قَطَرَ meaning \"he dripped\" or \"he distilled.\" قَطِرَانٌ refers to \"tar\" or \"resin,\" a viscous substance obtained through the process of distillation or extraction from organic materials. The connection lies in the slow and deliberate process of dripping or distilling, emphasizing the transformation of raw materials into a usable product. This root highlights themes of refinement, extraction, and the gradual accumulation of liquid, reflecting both the physical process and its broader symbolic implications of patience and precision in obtaining something of value.",
  "2964": "قَطَّعَ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" قَطَّعَ is an intensified form meaning \"he cut into pieces,\" \"he dismembered,\" or \"he fragmented,\" emphasizing repeated or forceful cutting that leads to complete disintegration. The connection lies in the deliberate and thorough action of breaking something into smaller parts, reflecting intensity and persistence. This root highlights themes of fragmentation and disassembly, symbolizing not only physical division but also metaphorical disintegration, such as the breakdown of relationships, unity, or continuity.",
  "2965": "قَعَدَ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-د, with the root verb قَعَدَ meaning \"he sat,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" The connection lies in the deliberate act of taking a seat, choosing to stay in place, or refraining from action. This root emphasizes themes of rest, stillness, or inaction, reflecting both physical and metaphorical states of remaining stationary. It can convey neutrality, as in resting or settling, or hesitation and reluctance, as in staying behind when action is required. The root highlights the dual nature of staying in place, which can signify purposeful rest or passive inaction, depending on context.",
  "2966": "قَعِيدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-د, with the root verb قَعَدَ meaning \"he sat,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" قَعِيدٌ refers to \"seated,\" \"watcher,\" or \"observer,\" emphasizing the state of being stationary or positioned in a specific place. The connection lies in the act of sitting, which often conveys attentiveness, readiness, or a deliberate role, such as watching or observing. This word reflects themes of stillness and focus, where remaining in place symbolizes a purposeful station, whether for monitoring, guarding, or observing events. The root highlights the importance of being grounded and steadfast in fulfilling a specific role or duty.",
  "2967": "قَلَمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-م, with the root verb قَلَّمَ meaning \"he trimmed,\" \"he clipped,\" or \"he pruned.\" قَلَمٌ refers to a \"pen\" or \"writing instrument,\" traditionally crafted by cutting and shaping a reed, a hollow and slender plant. The connection lies in the act of trimming and shaping the reed to create a functional pen, embodying the root’s emphasis on precision and refinement through cutting.",
  "2968": "قَلَىٰ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ي, and as the root verb, it means \"he hated,\" \"he detested,\" or \"he turned away in aversion.\" It also encompasses themes of estrangement, distancing, and severing ties, reflecting a deliberate act of rejection or abandonment. These meanings emphasize the root's focus on emotional and relational severance, often symbolizing a complete turning away or repudiation.",
  "2969": "قَلِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ل, with the root verb قَلَّ meaning \"it was little,\" \"it became few,\" or \"it diminished.\" قَلِيلٌ means \"little,\" \"few,\" or \"small in quantity,\" describing something minimal in amount, number, or significance. The root conveys themes of scarcity, reduction, and insufficiency, highlighting the concept of limitedness. قَلِيلٌ reflects the root's focus on smallness, often used to emphasize contrast with abundance or to draw attention to what is lacking or insufficient.",
  "2970": "قَلِيلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ل, with the root verb قَلَّ meaning \"it was little,\" \"it became few,\" or \"it diminished.\" قَلِيلَةٌ means \"little,\" \"few,\" or \"small in quantity,\" referring specifically to feminine nouns. The root emphasizes scarcity and reduction, with قَلِيلَةٌ highlighting minimal quantity or presence. This term mirrors the root’s focus on smallness and insufficiency, emphasizing subtle contrasts or the absence of abundance.",
  "2971": "قَلَّ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ل, with the root verb قَلَّ meaning \"it was little,\" \"it decreased,\" or \"it diminished.\" This root conveys the concept of reduction, scarcity, or becoming few in number. It encompasses themes of insufficiency and limitation, highlighting the transition from abundance to a small amount or scarcity of something. The root's applications extend to various contexts, such as describing a decrease in quantity, a reduction in size, or a diminishment in strength or intensity, all reflecting the overarching notion of lessening or becoming minimal.",
  "2972": "قَلَّبُوا and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" قَلَّبُوا means \"they turned over\" or \"they manipulated.\" The connection lies in the act of altering or reversing something, reflecting the root's emphasis on change and transformation. It highlights actions that cause shifts in states or conditions, whether physical or metaphorical.",
  "2973": "قَلْبٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ل-ب, with the root verb قَلَبَ meaning \"he turned over,\" \"he inverted,\" or \"he changed.\" قَلْبٌ means \"heart.\" The connection lies in the heart's ability to turn or change, reflecting human emotions and intentions. The root emphasizes transformation and changeability. In Islam, the heart is the center of consciousness and faith, susceptible to turning towards or away from guidance, highlighting the importance of spiritual vigilance.",
  "2974": "قَمَرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-م-ر, with the root verbs قَامَرَ meaning \"he gambled\" or \"he played a game of chance,\" and تَقَمَّرَ meaning \"he deceived.\" قَمَرٌ refers to the moon, whose luminous presence dominates the night sky. The connection can be seen in the moon’s ability to \"overcome\" darkness, reflecting themes of mastery and prominence. The notion of deception in the root aligns metaphorically with the moon’s borrowed light, which, though captivating, is not its own, symbolizing both beauty and an illusory quality. These layers highlight the moon’s role as a guide, a source of brilliance, and a symbol of subtle mastery.",
  "2975": "قَمِيصٌ and related words stem from the root ق-م-ص, with the root verb قَمَصَ meaning \"he (a horse or other animal) raised his forelegs together and put them down together, and beat the ground with his hind feet.\" This action reflects a wrapping or enclosing motion as the legs move together rhythmically. قَمِيصٌ, meaning \"shirt,\" directly connects to this concept, as the shirt wraps around and encloses the midsection of the body, much like the coordinated and enclosing motion described in the root. This connection emphasizes the functional role of the shirt as both a covering and a secure layer, aligning with the dynamic and enclosing themes of the root.",
  "2976": "قَمْطَرِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-م-ط-ر, with the root verb قَمْطَرَ signifying \"it was distressful\" or \"calamitous,\" implying an overwhelming severity or harshness. قَمْطَرِيرٌ conveys the meaning of something severe, grim, or distressing, capturing the essence of intense hardship or calamity. The root encompasses themes of contraction, tightness, or grimness, which metaphorically reflect the furrowing of features or the constriction caused by distress. This connection highlights the idea of an overwhelming state of difficulty, aligning the word’s application with the vivid imagery of severity and discomfort inherent in the root.",
  "2977": "قَنَطُوا and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ط, with the root verb قَنَطَ meaning \"he despaired\" or \"he lost hope.\" قَنَطُوا means \"they despaired,\" describing a state of hopelessness or loss of optimism. The term reflects moments of adversity when individuals experience despair, emphasizing the spiritual and emotional dangers of losing faith in Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy. The root highlights the importance of maintaining trust in divine provision and cautions against allowing hardship to lead to hopelessness. قَنَطُوا serves as a reminder to remain steadfast and believe in Allah’s (ﷻ) ability to bring relief, no matter the circumstances.",
  "2978": "قُنُوطٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ط, with the root verb قَنَطَ meaning \"he despaired\" or \"he lost hope.\" قُنُوطٌ refers to \"despair\" or \"hopelessness,\" capturing the abstract state of emotional and spiritual despondency. The root highlights the profound impact of despair on an individual’s faith, depicting it as a condition that distances one from trust in Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy. قُنُوطٌ serves as a reminder of the necessity of maintaining hope and reliance on Allah’s (ﷻ) infinite mercy, even in times of difficulty. It highlights the Qur'anic call to resist despair, aligning with the broader message of seeking strength and guidance through Allah (ﷻ).",
  "2979": "الْقَهَّارُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, also stems from ق-ه-ر and is an intensive form meaning \"The All-Prevailing\" or \"The Ever-Dominating.\" It highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) absolute and continuous power over all creation. The root conveys themes of ultimate dominance and authority, reflecting Allah’s (ﷻ) ability to subdue all things to His will. This name serves as a reminder to humbly submit to Allah’s (ﷻ) unmatched authority and recognize His supreme control in all aspects of existence, emphasizing the profound and unchallenged nature of His power.",
  "2980": "قَوَارِيرُ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ر, with the root verb قَرَّ meaning \"he settled,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he became fixed.\" قَوَارِيرُ (plural of قَارُورَةٌ) means \"glass vessels\" or \"crystals.\" The connection lies in the qualities of glass—its transparency, clarity, and ability to hold and display its contents visibly and undisturbed—aligning with the root’s emphasis on settling, stability, and remaining fixed. These vessels symbolize delicacy and refinement while also representing balance and precision in their ability to contain and showcase what is within. The term reflects themes of purity, order, and the tranquil beauty of stability, highlighting the harmonious relationship between form and function.",
  "2981": "قَواعِدُ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-د, with the root verb قَعَدَ meaning \"he sat,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he established.\" قَواعِدُ (plural of قَاعِدَة) refers to \"foundations,\" \"principles,\" or \"bases,\" emphasizing the concept of stability and permanence. The connection lies in the idea of something firmly settled or established, providing a stable base upon which other things are built or supported. Whether referring to physical foundations, such as the base of a structure, or abstract principles, such as guiding rules, the root reflects themes of steadiness, groundedness, and reliability. It highlights the importance of firm bases in ensuring strength and continuity.",
  "2982": "قَوامٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root encompasses concepts of standing upright, balance, and maintaining stability. قَوامٌ means \"balance,\" \"moderation,\" or \"uprightness,\" signifying a state of equilibrium or the essence that sustains and stabilizes something. The connection lies in the idea of balance being akin to standing firmly and steadily, embodying the root's themes of uprightness and stability. It highlights the importance of moderation and balance in life, ensuring steadiness and alignment with principles of justice and truth.",
  "2983": "قَوِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ي, with the verb قَوِيَ meaning \"he was strong\" or \"he became strong.\" The root signifies strength, firmness, and power in both physical and metaphorical dimensions. قَوِيٌّ means \"strong\" or \"powerful,\" reflecting innate vigor and might. ٱلْقَوِيُّ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, denotes \"The All-Powerful,\" emphasizing His unparalleled strength and His complete dominion over all creation. This name reminds us of Allah’s (ﷻ) infinite power, which supports and sustains all existence, inviting reliance upon Him for strength in moments of human frailty. The root also highlights firmness in resolve and the enduring power that emanates from unwavering faith.",
  "2984": "قَوَّامُونَ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys concepts of standing upright, maintaining, and upholding. قَوَّامُونَ is an intensive form meaning \"protectors,\" \"maintainers,\" or \"those who stand firm.\" It describes individuals who diligently and consistently uphold or maintain something with steadfastness and care. The connection lies in intensifying the act of standing to signify ongoing maintenance, protection, and vigilance, embodying the root's essence of uprightness and stability. It highlights the role of being a steadfast guardian or caretaker, ensuring that things remain upright, secure, and in proper order.",
  "2985": "قَوْسَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ق-و-س, with the root verb قَاسَ meaning \"he measured the thing by another thing like it.\" قَوْسٌ means \"bow,\" and قَوْسَيْنِ refers to \"two bows,\" often used to describe a measured distance of \"two bows' length.\" The root conveys themes of curvature, tension, and measured space, reflecting the bow's dual role as a weapon and a tool for precision. This connection highlights the importance of balance and exactness, as represented by the bow’s physical structure and its metaphorical application in measured distances or relationships.",
  "2986": "قَوْلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ل, with the root verb قَالَ meaning \"he said\" or \"he spoke.\" قَوْلٌ means \"speech,\" \"word,\" or \"saying,\" representing the content of what is spoken. It emphasizes the significance of words as carriers of meaning, intention, or truth. The root highlights the power and influence of speech, with قَوْلٌ symbolizing the outcome of speaking, whether it is truthful, persuasive, or misleading, reflecting the root’s essence of communication as a force for shaping thought and action.",
  "2987": "قَوْمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root embodies concepts of standing, rising, and establishing. قَوْمٌ means \"people,\" \"nation,\" or \"community,\" reflecting the idea of a group standing together or being established as a collective entity. While it often emphasizes unity and shared purpose, the standing together of a group does not inherently imply uprightness or moral alignment. A community may be united in just causes or deviate toward injustice, showing that the root’s application extends beyond positive contexts. This highlights the dual potential of collective standing, depending on alignment with truth and justice.",
  "2988": "قَيُّومٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قَامَ meaning \"he stood,\" \"he rose,\" or \"he maintained.\" The root conveys themes of standing upright, sustaining, and preserving. ٱلْقَيُّومُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Absolute Sustainer,\" emphasizing His role in upholding and maintaining all existence without need or dependence. It highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) continuous care and oversight of creation, embodying the root’s essence of perpetual maintenance, firm establishment, and unmatched sovereignty.",
  "2989": "قَيِّمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys concepts of standing upright, maintaining, upholding, and establishing balance or justice. قَيِّمٌ means \"upright,\" \"just,\" or \"firmly established.\" It reflects the act of maintaining or aligning with what is correct, emphasizing uprightness in both moral and practical dimensions. This term captures the idea of something or someone being steadfast and balanced, actively upholding principles of justice and truth. In spiritual contexts, قَيِّمٌ is often associated with the uprightness and correctness of divine guidance, emphasizing its role as the unerring standard for human conduct. ",
  "2990": "قَيِّمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root embodies concepts of standing upright, maintaining, and establishing value or correctness. قَيِّمَةٌ, derived from قَوَّمَ, means \"upright,\" \"just,\" or \"correct,\" reflecting a state of being aligned with truth and balance. It also conveys the idea of intrinsic worth, emphasizing value and rectitude. In a broader sense, قَيِّمَةٌ signifies something firmly established in truth, whether it refers to religion, scripture, or a principle, highlighting its uprightness and consistency. The term reflects the root’s themes of stability, correctness, and enduring value.",
  "2991": "قُبُلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قُبُلٌ means \"front\" or \"face to face,\" emphasizing a direct encounter or orientation. The connection lies in the act of facing directly, reflecting the root's theme of meeting, engaging, or confronting willingly. This highlights the idea of immediacy and openness in interactions, where facing something head-on symbolizes clarity, straightforwardness, and a lack of barriers.",
  "2992": "قُدُسٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-س, with the root verb قَدُسَ meaning \"he was pure,\" \"he was holy,\" or \"he was sacred.\" قُدُسٌ means \"holiness,\" \"sanctity,\" or \"purity,\" emphasizing a state of being entirely free from imperfection or impurity. The term is associated with ultimate purity and transcendence, reflecting the root’s emphasis on absolute sanctity and separation from flaws. In the context of رُوحُ الْقُدُسِ, it refers to the Angel Gabriel (ﷺ), whose role is to faithfully deliver divine revelations, symbolizing purity of purpose and the exalted task of conveying truth from Allah (ﷻ).",
  "2993": "قُدُورٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-ر, with the root verb قَدَرَ meaning \"he measured,\" \"he determined,\" or \"he decreed.\" قُدُورٌ (plural of قِدْرٌ) means \"pots\" or \"cauldrons,\" used for cooking or boiling. The connection lies in the vessel's role in holding, containing, and managing specific quantities of food or liquid, reflecting the root’s emphasis on measurement and precise determination. These pots symbolize practicality and order, as they facilitate controlled preparation and allocation. The term highlights the balance between function and precision, highlighting the root’s broader themes of measuring, apportioning, and determining in both tangible and metaphorical contexts.",
  "2994": "قُدَّ and related words stem from the root ق-د-د, with the root verb قَدَّ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleft,\" or \"he tore.\" قُدَّ is a passive form meaning \"it was cut,\" \"it was cleft,\" or \"it was torn apart.\" The root emphasizes the act of severing, splitting, or creating a separation, whether physical or metaphorical. This term reflects the impact of an external force causing division or rupture, often implying a significant or deliberate action. It highlights themes of fragmentation, division, and the consequences of actions that separate or tear, highlighting the transformative nature of such forces.",
  "2995": "قُدُّوسٌ stems from the root ق-د-س, with the root verb قَدُسَ meaning \"he was pure,\" \"he was holy.\" الْقُدُّوسُ is an intensive form meaning \"The Most Holy,\" or \"The Most Sacred,\" embodying the pinnacle of sanctity and purity. As one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect and beautiful names, الْقُدُّوسُ signifies His absolute transcendence, purity, and freedom from all imperfection. The root conveys themes of exaltation, sanctity, and purification, reflecting Allah’s (ﷻ) unmatched holiness and perfection. This name invites believers to recognize and revere Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme sanctity, inspiring humility and devotion while emphasizing the vast difference between Allah’s (ﷻ) perfection and human limitation.",
  "2996": "قُرَيْشٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ش, with the root verb قَرَشَ meaning \"he gathered,\" \"he earned,\" or \"he collected provisions.\" قُرَيْشٌ refers to the tribe of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ) and is associated with meanings such as \"gatherer\" or, metaphorically, \"small shark,\" symbolizing strength, dominance, and resilience. This connection reflects the tribe’s prominent role in gathering wealth and provisions, particularly through their control over trade and caravan routes. The term embodies themes of accumulation, provision, and leadership, emphasizing the tribe’s historical significance in fostering commerce, securing resources, and providing for their community.",
  "2997": "قُرُبَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" قُرُبَاتٌ (plural of قُرْبَةٌ) means \"acts of devotion\" or \"means of drawing near [to Allah(ﷻ)].\" Broader root meanings encompass closeness, connection, and approach, reflecting the idea of reducing spiritual distance through good deeds or acts of worship. The connection lies in how acts of charity, devotion, and kindness bring one closer to Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing nearness not just in proximity but also in spiritual rank and favor.",
  "2998": "قُرُوءٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-أ, with the root verb قَرَأَ meaning \"he read,\" \"he recited,\" or \"he gathered.\" قُرُوءٌ (plural of قُرْءٌ) means \"periods\" specifically referring to the menstrual cycles or the intervals of purity between them. The connection lies in the concept of gathering or recurring cycles, directly reflecting the root's idea of collecting or assembling. This term is significant in legal contexts, marking the prescribed waiting periods, and emphasizes the cyclical nature of certain bodily processes.",
  "2999": "قُرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ر, with the root verb قَرَّ meaning \"he became cool\" or \"he settled.\" قُرَّةٌ means \"coolness\" or \"delight,\" often used in the expression قُرَّةُ عَيْنٍ (\"coolness of the eye\") to signify deep joy and comfort. The connection lies in the root's concept of coolness and settling, reflecting the soothing relief and satisfaction that bring peace to the soul. This term highlights the profound happiness and contentment that one experiences through blessings and divine favor.",
  "3000": "قُرْآنٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-أ, with the root verb قَرَأَ meaning \"he read,\" \"he recited,\" or \"he gathered.\" قُرْآنٌ means \"the Recitation\" or \"the Qur'an,\" referring to the sacred scripture of Islam. The term embodies reciting and gathering divine revelations into a unified text, reflecting both the oral tradition and the written preservation of the message. The root emphasizes themes of articulation, clarity, and collection, highlighting the Qur'an’s role as a guide for recitation and a repository of divine wisdom. It highlights the importance of engaging with the text through reading, reciting, and reflecting, reinforcing its timeless connection to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3001": "قُرْبَانٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" قُرْبَانٌ means \"offering\" or \"sacrifice,\" referring to something presented to seek nearness to Allah (ﷻ). Broader root meanings highlight proximity, approach, and connection, with قُرْبَانٌ symbolizing an act that reduces spiritual distance by demonstrating devotion and humility. The connection lies in embodying the act of approaching through offerings, reflecting the root's emphasis on drawing near, whether physically or spiritually.",
  "3002": "قُرْبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" قُرْبَةٌ means \"an act of devotion\" or \"a means of drawing near [to Allah (ﷻ)],\" highlighting actions performed to reduce spiritual distance. Broader root meanings emphasize nearness, approach, and connection, reflecting the idea of actively seeking closeness to Allah (ﷻ) through acts of worship, charity, or righteousness. The connection lies in embodying the root’s concept of reducing separation, symbolizing spiritual proximity and submission.",
  "3003": "قُرْبَىٰ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ب, with the root verb قَرُبَ meaning \"he was near\" or \"he approached.\" قُرْبَىٰ means \"kinship\" or \"close relatives,\" emphasizing the state of nearness, particularly within familial ties. Broader root meanings highlight proximity, connection, and intimacy, reflecting the importance of maintaining strong relational bonds. The connection lies in embodying the root's concept of nearness, illustrating the moral and social responsibility of nurturing kinship and strengthening family ties through acts of care and compassion.",
  "3004": "قُصْوَىٰ and related words also stem from the root ق-ص-ي, with the root verb قَصَا meaning \"it was distant\" or \"it became remote.\" قُصْوَىٰ means \"utmost,\" \"extreme,\" or \"farthest,\" denoting the outermost limit or the highest degree of separation. The connection lies in reaching the furthest point or boundary, symbolizing a point beyond which nothing further can be attained. This root emphasizes the idea of surpassing all intermediate stages to reach the absolute limit, whether in physical distance, time, or metaphorical boundaries. It reflects themes of extremity and finality, illustrating the significance of striving toward or reaching the ultimate degree of something.",
  "3005": "قُطُوفٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ف, with the root verb قَطَفَ meaning \"he plucked,\" \"he picked,\" or \"he gathered (fruit).\" قُطُوفٌ refers to \"fruits to be picked\" or \"clusters (of fruit),\" emphasizing their readiness and ease of access. The connection lies in the deliberate act of plucking, which signifies the fruit’s ripeness and suitability for harvest. This root reflects themes of abundance, accessibility, and the fulfillment of effort, as ripe fruits are the culmination of growth and care. It symbolizes rewards that are prepared and within reach, highlighting the importance of effort and timing in achieving desired outcomes.",
  "3006": "قُطِعَ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" قُطِعَ means \"it was cut,\" \"it was severed,\" or \"it was broken off,\" emphasizing the result of being forcibly divided or disconnected. The connection lies in the finality and decisiveness of being cut off, whether physically or metaphorically. This root highlights themes of separation, interruption, and disconnection, often symbolizing an end to continuity, relationships, or access, highlighting the impactful and often irreversible nature of severance.",
  "3007": "قُعُودٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ع-د, with the root verb قَعَدَ meaning \"he sat,\" \"he remained,\" or \"he stayed behind.\" قُعُودٌ refers to \"sitting\" or \"remaining behind,\" emphasizing the act or state of being stationary. The connection lies in the deliberate choice to remain inactive or in one place, reflecting themes of stillness, inaction, or hesitation. This takes on deeper significance in a spiritual context, where قُعُودٌ can symbolize reluctance, apathy, or refusal to fulfill obligations, contrasting with the proactive pursuit of good deeds. The root highlights the distinction between purposeful rest and avoidance, urging reflection on the consequences of inaction in matters of faith and responsibility.",
  "3008": "قُمَّلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-م-ل, referring to \"lice,\" small parasitic insects known for their rapid reproduction and infestation, causing discomfort and irritation. The root conveys ideas of multiplication and infestation, emphasizing the overwhelming and troubling nature of being overrun. In the Qur'an, قُمَّلٌ represents a divine affliction, symbolizing persistent nuisance and serving as a reminder of Allah’s (ﷻ) power to test and humble humanity. It highlights how Allah (ﷻ) can use something as small and seemingly insignificant as lice to cause severe affliction, highlighting the vulnerability, weakness, and insignificance of human beings in the face of His power.",
  "3009": "قُوَّةٌ and related words come from the root ق-و-ي, with the verb قَوِيَ meaning \"he was strong\" or \"he became strong.\" قُوَّةٌ means \"strength,\" \"power,\" or \"firmness\" and represents strength as a key quality. It includes not only physical power but also resilience, mental toughness, and spiritual strength, reflecting how strength appears in many forms. This word highlights the importance of using strength for good, channeling it towards actions aligned with Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance. It also reminds us that all strength ultimately belongs to Allah (ﷻ), the possessor of ultimate power, encouraging reliance on Him to strive for excellence while using the strength granted to us in ways that please Him.",
  "3010": "قِبَلٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قِبَلٌ means \"direction\" or \"towards,\" emphasizing orientation or facing a particular way. The connection to the root lies in the concept of willingly turning toward or receiving something, as قِبَلٌ reflects the act of facing or orienting oneself intentionally. This highlights the purposeful alignment and readiness to engage with a particular direction, illustrating the root’s broader themes of reception, intentional movement, and focus in both physical and metaphorical contexts.",
  "3011": "قِبْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ب-ل, with the root verb قَبِلَ meaning \"he took, received, or admitted willingly,\" or \"he accepted.\" قِبْلَةٌ means \"direction of prayer\" or \"qibla,\" specifically the orientation Muslims face during prayer. The connection lies in the root's theme of acceptance and intentional facing, as قِبْلَةٌ represents a deliberate and willing orientation toward a specific point. This act embodies the root’s essence of receiving guidance and aligning oneself purposefully. It symbolizes unity, focus, and devotion, bringing believers into physical and spiritual alignment with the Kaaba in Mecca, reflecting harmony and a collective acknowledgment of a central point of worship.",
  "3012": "قِتَالٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ت-ل, with the root verb قَتَلَ meaning \"he killed.\" قِتَالٌ means \"fighting\" or \"combat,\" reflecting the idea of mutual engagement in killing or warfare. The word captures the essence of conflict as a reciprocal act, emphasizing the intensity and struggle involved in combat.",
  "3013": "قِثَّاءٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ث-أ, which refers to \"cucumber.\" The term highlights the plant's role as a nourishing and refreshing food. The root suggests themes of growth and natural provision, emphasizing the connection between the earth’s produce and sustenance. This term reflects the bounty and variety of blessings provided through vegetation, highlighting the importance of appreciating and utilizing what has been made available for nourishment and benefit.",
  "3014": "قِدَدٌ and related words stem from the root ق-د-د, with the root verb قَدَّ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he cleft,\" or \"he divided.\" قِدَدٌ means \"diverse parts,\" \"pieces,\" or \"fragments.\" The connection lies in the idea of cutting or dividing something into various sections, reflecting the root's concept of separation. This term conveys the notion of diversity or disparity among parts that were once whole, emphasizing differences and divisions within a group or entity.",
  "3015": "قِرَدَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-د, with the root verb قَرِدَ meaning \"he became humble or submissive,\" \"he became silent from impotence of speech,\" or \"he became abject.\" قِرَدَةٌ (plural of قِرْدٌ) means \"monkeys\" or \"apes,\" symbolizing submission. The term reflects how monkeys are often seen as subservient or imitative, embodying both physical behavior and a metaphorical sense of inferiority. The broader root meanings of submission and silence align with monkeys' behavior, often imitating others, representing passive behavior or mimicry.",
  "3016": "قِرْطَاسٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ر-ط-س, which carries meanings including \"paper,\" \"papyrus,\" \"scroll,\" or \"target to shoot at.\" قِرْطَاسٌ primarily refers to \"paper\" or \"writing material,\" symbolizing a medium for recording and preserving knowledge. The term also carries the idea of precision and purpose, as seen in its connection to a target, which requires focused intent and accuracy. This duality reflects themes of careful preservation and deliberate intent, whether in the context of safeguarding wisdom or aiming for an objective. قِرْطَاسٌ embodies the transformative power of written materials as tools for transmitting knowledge and maintaining focus and purpose.",
  "3017": "قِسِّيسِينَ and related words stem from the root ق-س-س, with the root verb قَسَّ meaning \"he narrated\" or \"he followed closely.\" قِسِّيسِينَ means \"priests\" or \"clergymen.\" The connection lies in the role of a priest as one who closely follows religious teachings and narrates sacred stories. It emphasizes the duty of guiding others in faith and maintaining adherence to spiritual doctrines.",
  "3018": "قِسْطٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-ط, with the root verb قَسَطَ meaning \"he was unjust.\" قِسْطٌ carries the opposite meaning, referring to \"justice,\" \"fairness,\" or \"due portion.\" It emphasizes balanced and equitable dealings, reflecting the antithesis of the negative connotation of the root. This term embodies the principles of giving each their rightful due, upholding fairness and equity as foundational values. It highlights themes of divine justice and moral integrity, highlighting the importance of measured actions and adherence to truth in human interactions.",
  "3019": "قِسْطَاسٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-ط-س, which some consider to be an Arabicized term of Greek origin. It refers to \"balance,\" \"scales,\" or \"measuring instrument,\" emphasizing precision and fairness in measurement. Accurate scales are essential for ensuring equitable transactions and preventing deceit. This term reflects themes of justice, integrity, and accountability, highlighting the universal importance of fairness in all dealings. It symbolizes the foundational role of truth and exactness in maintaining trust and harmony.",
  "3020": "قِسْمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-س-م, with the root verb قَسَمَ meaning \"he divided\" or \"he allotted.\" قِسْمَةٌ refers to \"division,\" \"apportionment,\" or \"distribution,\" emphasizing the careful and methodical allocation of portions. The connection lies in the act of dividing something into shares with fairness and precision. This term highlights themes of justice, responsibility, and adherence to established guidelines, particularly in contexts such as inheritance laws, where the equitable distribution of wealth is paramount. The root highlights the importance of balance and meticulousness in fulfilling obligations while maintaining fairness.",
  "3021": "قِصَاصٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ص-ص, with the root verb قَصَّ meaning \"he cut\" or \"he measured precisely.\" قِصَاصٌ refers to \"retaliation\" or \"legal retribution,\" emphasizing the principle of equal punishment for a crime. The connection lies in the concept of cutting back equally, ensuring justice is served with exactness and balance. The root highlights themes of precision, fairness, and proportionality, reflecting the idea of \"an eye for an eye,\" where the punishment mirrors the offense. In the context of Islamic jurisprudence, قِصَاصٌ represents the application of divine justice, maintaining order and equity through measured retribution.",
  "3022": "قِطَعٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ع, with the root verb قَطَعَ meaning \"he cut,\" \"he severed,\" or \"he separated.\" قِطَعٌ (plural of قِطْعَة) refers to \"pieces,\" \"portions,\" or \"fragments,\" emphasizing the result of cutting or dividing a whole into multiple parts. The connection lies in the act of segmentation, where something is deliberately or forcibly divided into distinct parts. This root highlights themes of fragmentation, separation, and disconnection, symbolizing both physical division and metaphorical breaks in unity, continuity, or relationships.",
  "3023": "قِطٌّ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ط, with the root verb قَطَّ meaning \"he cut\" or \"he divided.\" قِطٌّ refers to a \"portion,\" \"lot,\" or \"share,\" emphasizing something that has been divided or allocated. The connection lies in the act of cutting or partitioning, where a whole is separated into distinct parts. This root highlights themes of division, allocation, and distribution, reflecting the deliberate assignment of portions. Whether literal, as in dividing physical items, or metaphorical, as in apportioning responsibilities or fates, قِطٌّ highlights the significance of equity, order, and the purposeful separation of things into manageable or meaningful parts.",
  "3024": "قِطْرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-ر, with the root verb قَطَرَ meaning \"he dripped\" or \"he distilled.\" قِطْرٌ can mean \"region,\" \"diameter,\" or \"molten metal,\" reflecting different facets of the root’s meanings. The connection lies in the concept of flow, measurement, or extension. The sense of \"diameter\" reflects the act of measuring across a circle, symbolizing breadth and precision, while \"molten metal\" ties to the idea of distillation or transformation through heat. This root emphasizes processes of refinement, measurement, and the distribution or extension of something, whether in physical space or through a transformational process.",
  "3025": "قِطْمِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ط-م-ر, referring to the thin membrane or skin covering a date stone. The connection lies in the idea of a minute, negligible layer that is easily peeled off, symbolizing something insignificant. The root emphasizes minuteness and triviality. It is used to illustrate the smallest and most insignificant thing, highlighting that even such things belong entirely to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting human dependence on divine provision and Allah’s (ﷻ) ultimate ownership of all things.",
  "3026": "قِنْطَارٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-ط-ر, with the root verb قَنْطَرَ meaning \"he tied, vaulted, or made something firm and strong.\" قِنْطَارٌ refers to \"a great amount of wealth or property,\" encompassing large quantities of gold, silver, money, or other valuable possessions. The root conveys the idea of tying or binding firmly, symbolizing strength, security, and permanence. This connection emphasizes wealth as something amassed, safeguarded, and valued for its ability to provide stability and power. The term reflects humanity's inclination to accumulate and protect abundant resources, linking material wealth to concepts of endurance, steadfastness, and the pursuit of stability and influence.",
  "3027": "قِنْوَانٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ن-و, with the root verb قَنَا meaning \"he acquired\" or \"he possessed.\" قِنْوٌ refers to \"a cluster of dates,\" specifically the hanging fruit of the date palm, while قِنْوَانٌ is its plural form, meaning \"clusters\" or \"bunches.\" The root emphasizes acquisition, possession, and productivity, reflecting how the date palm produces visible clusters, symbolizing provision and bounty. These clusters represent the tree’s fruit as an accessible offering, embodying the root’s themes of acquiring and providing sustenance.",
  "3028": "قِيامَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root conveys concepts of standing, rising, and being established. قِيامَةٌ means \"resurrection\" or \"standing up again,\" referring specifically to the Day of Resurrection when all beings will rise from their graves for judgment. The connection lies in the act of standing on a universal scale, embodying the root's essence of rising and being brought to an upright state. قِيامَةٌ signifies a time of justice and accountability, reflecting the establishment of truth and alignment with divine justice.",
  "3029": "قِيعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ق-ي-ع, with the root verb قَاعَ meaning \"it was low\" or \"it was depressed.\" قِيعَةٌ refers to \"plains\" or \"level grounds,\" often describing broad, expansive terrains. It emphasizes openness, uniformity, and vastness, particularly in spaces that are unobstructed and continuous. The word conveys a sense of emptiness and clarity, symbolizing settings where things appear prominent yet remain unreachable or illusory, highlighting themes of vastness and unattainable perceptions.",
  "3030": "قِيلَ and related words stem from the root ق-و-ل, with the root verb قَالَ meaning \"he said\" or \"he spoke.\" The root embodies concepts of speech, expression, and verbal communication, emphasizing the act of conveying thoughts or messages. قِيلَ is the passive form, meaning \"it was said,\" shifting the focus from the speaker to the speech itself. This highlights communication as independent of the originator, emphasizing the dissemination, reception, and impact of words. The root reflects speech as a means of transmitting ideas, whether authoritative, speculative, or general, shaping understanding and conveying meaning beyond the speaker.",
  "3031": "قِيَمٌ and related words stem from the root ق-و-م, with the root verb قامَ meaning \"he stood\" or \"he rose.\" The root encompasses concepts of standing upright, value, and establishing. قِيَمٌ is the plural of قَيِّمَةٌ, meaning \"values\" or \"principles.\" The connection lies in the idea that values are principles that stand firm and guide behavior. They represent what is upheld and maintained as important in life. This reflects the root's emphasis on uprightness and stability, highlighting how values establish the foundation upon which actions and character are built.",
  "3032": "The particle كَ means \"like\" or \"as\" and is essential for forming comparisons and metaphors. It helps to illustrate similarities, making abstract or complex concepts more relatable by linking them to familiar ideas. In the Qur'an, كَ is used to draw comparisons that enhance understanding, often employing vivid imagery to deepen the audience’s grasp of profound truths or lessons. Its usage enriches the language by bridging the gap between the known and the unknown, facilitating clearer and more impactful communication.",
  "3033": "كاتِبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb كَتَبَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" كاتِبٌ means \"writer,\" \"scribe,\" or \"one who writes.\" It denotes someone actively engaged in writing or recording information. The connection to the root emphasizes the essential role of writing in communication and preservation. By highlighting the person who writes, it highlights the significance of documenting knowledge, agreements, or decrees, reflecting the transformative power of the written word in society.",
  "3034": "كَاتِبُوا and related words stem from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb كَتَبَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" كَاتِبُوا means \"write a contract,\" specifically referring to entering into a formal written agreement. The root emphasizes writing as a means of establishing permanence, accountability, and authority. In the context of كَاتِبُوا, it highlights the significance of fairness and trust, where documentation preserves the terms of agreements, binds both parties to their commitments, and reinforces the enduring role of written records in promoting justice and mutual understanding.",
  "3035": "كَادَ and related words stem from the root ك-و-د, and as the root verb, it means \"he was near to doing something\" or \"he was about to act.\" It emphasizes proximity to an action, highlighting deliberation and intent without necessarily achieving the outcome. The root encompasses dimensions of calculated planning, scheming, and deliberate contrivance, often involving artful or skillful measures. In specific contexts, it extends to deceit, cunning, or plotting, whether for good or ill, reflecting intentional efforts to achieve a result through subtle or indirect means. Additionally, كَادَ conveys striving or laboring with effort and intensity, often implying exertion to overcome obstacles or achieve an objective.",
  "3036": "كَادِحٌ and related words stem from the root ك-د-ح, with the root verb كَدَحَ meaning \"he labored,\" \"he toiled,\" or \"he exerted himself with effort.\" كَادِحٌ means \"toiler,\" \"laborer,\" or \"one who strives.\" It describes an individual engaged in continuous, strenuous effort, often under challenging conditions. The root emphasizes intense labor and exertion, symbolizing the persistent struggle inherent in the human condition. كَادِحٌ reflects the ceaseless striving required in life's journey, whether for worldly goals or higher spiritual pursuits, highlighting the concept of perseverance amidst challenges.",
  "3037": "كَاذِبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied\" or \"he told a falsehood.\" كَاذِبٌ means \"liar\" or \"one who lies,\" describing a person who engages in deceit or spreads falsehoods. While the root encompasses both intentional and unintentional falsehoods, كَاذِبٌ focuses on an active characteristic of dishonesty. It reflects the breach of trust and integrity associated with lying, emphasizing the moral failing and societal harm caused by deceit. This term highlights the personal nature of falsehood, marking the liar as someone who distorts truth, undermines trust, and disrupts the fabric of human relationships.",
  "3038": "كَارِهُونَ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, with the root verb كَـرِهَ meaning \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" كَارِهُونَ means \"ones who dislike\" or \"ones who are averse.\" It describes individuals who harbor strong feelings of aversion, reflecting the root’s core theme of emotional rejection. It is often associated with resistance, whether to an idea, an obligation, or an external force. The term emphasizes internal disapproval or reluctance, portraying the human experience of rejecting or resisting what is perceived as unpleasant or undesirable.",
  "3039": "كَاشِفٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ش-ف, with the root verb كَشَفَ meaning \"he uncovered\" or \"he revealed.\" كَاشِفٌ means \"one who uncovers\" or \"a remover,\" describing an individual or entity that removes coverings or brings hidden things to light. In classical Arabic, the term also conveys the idea of alleviation or removing burdens, as in lifting hardships or exposing concealed realities. This connects to the root’s overarching theme of transition—from concealment to clarity or from burden to relief. It highlights the transformative nature of revelation, emphasizing the pursuit of knowledge, clarity, and understanding.",
  "3040": "كَاشِفَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ش-ف, with the root verb كَشَفَ meaning \"he uncovered\" or \"he revealed.\" كَاشِفَةٌ means \"one who uncovers\" or \"a remover,\" often used to signify something or someone that reveals truths or alleviates burdens. Classical texts associate this term with the act of unveiling or lifting, whether it refers to physical coverings or metaphorical burdens, such as distress or uncertainty. The root emphasizes the transition from hiddenness to clarity, aligning كَاشِفَةٌ with the idea of providing relief, exposing truths, or resolving ambiguities. This highlights its profound role in enabling understanding and alleviating hardship.",
  "3041": "كَاظِمِينَ and related words stem from the root ك-ظ-م, with the root verb كَظَمَ meaning \"he suppressed\" or \"he restrained.\" كَاظِمِينَ refers to \"those who suppress emotions,\" particularly anger or distress. While it often describes individuals who actively control their emotions, embodying restraint and self-discipline, it can also refer to those overwhelmed by fear or anguish, suppressing their inner turmoil under immense pressure. This term highlights the dual aspects of emotional control: the active virtue of patience and composure, as well as the burden of silent suppression during moments of intense fear or distress, reflecting the root's focus on internal struggle and containment.",
  "3042": "كَافٍ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ى, with the root verb كَفَىٰ meaning \"he sufficed,\" \"he was sufficient,\" or \"he fulfilled.\" The term كَافٍ signifies \"sufficient\" or \"one who suffices,\" embodying the concept of adequacy and completeness. The root encompasses meanings of sufficiency, fulfillment, and the ability to meet needs without deficiency. This connection highlights a state of completeness where no further addition is required, symbolizing a fulfillment that leaves nothing needing. The term highlights the perfection of sufficiency, often emphasizing the ultimate and unparalleled sufficiency attributed to Allah (ﷻ), whose adequacy encompasses all needs entirely and perfectly.",
  "3043": "كَافُورٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَافُورٌ refers to \"camphor,\" a fragrant substance known for its cooling and soothing properties. In the context of paradise, this term symbolizes a beverage enhanced by camphor’s cooling and aromatic qualities, superior in taste and fragrance, and free from any negative effects. The connection lies in how camphor \"covers\" or masks undesirable qualities, offering a divine experience that surpasses anything in the worldly life, bringing unmatched comfort, purity, and relief. This reflects the perfect blessings of the Hereafter, where everything is pure and beyond comparison.",
  "3044": "كَافِرِينَ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَافِرِينَ means \"disbelievers,\" \"those who conceal the truth,\" or \"disbelieving.\" The connection lies in the collective act of \"covering\" or \"hiding\" the truth, directly reflecting the root’s concept of concealment. This term emphasizes the shared moral responsibility in rejecting or denying evident truth, highlighting how disbelief or ingratitude arises from a deliberate choice to obscure guidance or blessings. It points to the severity of rejecting faith and truth, reinforcing accountability at both individual and collective levels.",
  "3045": "كَافِرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَافِرَةٌ is the feminine form of كَافِرٌ, meaning \"disbeliever\" or \"one who conceals the truth,\" specifically referring to females or feminine nouns. The connection lies in the act of \"covering\" or \"hiding\" the truth, directly aligning with the root’s concept of concealment. This term highlights the moral and spiritual deficiency of denying or obscuring evident truths or blessings, reflecting the broader theme of rejection tied to the root.",
  "3046": "كَافَّةً and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ف, with the root verb كَفَّ meaning \"he restrained,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he prevented.\" كَافَّةً means \"all\" or \"entirety,\" embodying the concept of encompassing or including everything within certain bounds. This term reflects the root’s essence of control and restraint, as it suggests an action or entity that is unified and complete, restrained from division or exclusion. كَافَّةً emphasizes totality and inclusiveness, whether describing a group acting collectively, a concept encompassing all, or a state of being whole.",
  "3047": "كَالُوا and related words stem from the root ك-ي-ل, with the root verb كَالَ meaning \"he measured\" or \"he weighed.\" كَالُوا means \"they measured\" or \"they gave measure.\" The connection lies in the act of providing measured quantities to others, highlighting the importance of fairness and accuracy in transactions. This term emphasizes the ethical duty to be just in dealings.",
  "3048": "كَالِحُونَ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ح, with the verb كَلَحَ meaning \"he bared his teeth\" or \"he grimaced.\" كَالِحُونَ means \"grimacing\" or \"one who bares teeth,\" often used to describe an expression of extreme distress, anger, or pain. The connection lies in the physical act of baring teeth, reflecting intense emotional states. This term captures the vivid and impactful imagery of a contorted face, emphasizing discomfort, hostility, or anguish, and symbolizing an outward display of internal turmoil. It highlights the link between visible expressions and profound emotional or situational intensity.",
  "3049": "كَامِلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-م-ل, with the root verb كَمُلَ meaning \"he or it was complete\" or \"he or it was perfect.\" كَامِلَةٌ means \"complete\" or \"perfect,\" describing a state of being whole, flawless, or free from deficiencies. The connection lies in achieving a condition where nothing is lacking, directly reflecting the root’s emphasis on entirety and perfection. This term highlights the idea of completeness in its most comprehensive sense, whether physical, moral, or metaphorical, highlighting the fulfillment of purpose or function.",
  "3050": "كَامِلَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ك-م-ل, with the root verb كَمُلَ meaning \"he or it was complete\" or \"he or it was perfect.\" كَامِلَيْنِ is the dual form, meaning \"two complete\" or \"two perfect,\" emphasizing that both items or entities are whole, flawless, and without deficiency. The connection lies in the duality of completeness, where two distinct things are brought to their ideal state together.",
  "3051": "كَانَ and related words stem from the root ك-و-ن, with the root verb كَانَ meaning \"he was,\" \"he existed,\" or \"he came into being.\" This verb captures the essence of being and existence, encompassing the act of coming into a state, manifesting over time and space. The root connects to physical space, reflecting how existence occupies a specific location, and extends to social standing, symbolizing one’s role or position within a hierarchy. These meanings highlight the dynamic nature of being—its continuity, permanence, and impact—yet serve as a reminder that all existence, whether physical presence, spatial occupation, or social status, will transition to \"it was\" and cease to \"be.\"",
  "3052": "كَاهِنٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ه-ن, with the root verb كَهَنَ meaning \"he prophesied\" or \"he acted as a soothsayer.\" كَاهِنٌ refers to \"a soothsayer\" or \"a fortune-teller,\" denoting someone who claims knowledge of hidden matters or future events. The root conveys themes of foretelling, divining, and seeking insight into the unseen, often through mystical or spiritual practices. The connection lies in the act of mediating between the known and the unknown, embodying the concept of attempting to access hidden realms or divine will.",
  "3053": "The particle كَأَيِّنْ means \"how many\" or \"many a\" and combines كَ (like) with أَيٍّ (which). In the Qur'an, it is used to emphasize abundance, whether referring to the multitude of signs of Allah’s (ﷻ) power, the numerous past nations, or frequent occurrences of significant phenomena. كَأَيِّنْ draws attention to these examples to inspire reflection, gratitude, or caution, encouraging the listener to recognize the vastness of Allah’s (ﷻ) creation and the lessons embedded in history. Its usage enhances the depth and contemplative nature of the language.",
  "3054": "كَأْسٌ and related words stem from the root ك-أ-س, meaning \"cup,\" referring to a drinking vessel. In the Qur'an, كَأْسٌ is used to symbolize the blessed, pure drinks offered to the righteous in Paradise. These cups, filled with untainted, heavenly beverages, represent the ultimate joy, reward, and divine favor. The term emphasizes the purity and perfection of the sustenance awaiting the righteous, free from any impurity or negative influence. كَأْسٌ highlights the concept of divine blessings in the Hereafter, reflecting the joy and contentment that come from Allah’s (ﷻ) reward for those who are upright in faith.",
  "3055": "كَبَدٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-د, with the root verb كَبَدَ meaning \"to hit or strike the liver,\" reflecting the organ’s role as the seat of life and intense emotion. كَبَدٌ means \"liver\" but extends metaphorically to denote \"hardship\" or \"strenuous effort,\" as in كَبَدَهُمُ البَرْدُ, meaning \"the cold distressed them\" or \"struck their livers,\" symbolizing suffering. The root also conveys themes of bulkiness, slowness, and difficulty, as in a person being \"bulky in the belly,\" emphasizing burdensome weight or struggle. These meanings tie back to the liver as a metaphor for enduring both physical toil and emotional anguish, illustrating the profound link between the organ and life’s hardships.",
  "3056": "كَبُرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb meaning \"he became great,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he matured,\" embodying concepts of greatness, magnitude, and growth. It signifies the process of increasing in size, age, or status, reflecting the root's core theme of becoming significant or prominent. This verb forms the foundation for numerous derivatives that highlight greatness in various dimensions, from the positive aspects of growth, reverence, and maturity, to the negative implications of arrogance and pride. The root reminds us of the dual potential of growth: to elevate with humility or to falter through self-exaltation.",
  "3057": "كَبِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كَبِيرٌ denotes \"great,\" \"big,\" or \"elder,\" reflecting size, age, or prominence. The root conveys themes of magnitude and distinction, applicable to physical, social, or abstract greatness. Socially, it signifies respect and honor for elders or those of higher status. ٱلْكَبِيرُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) perfect names, means \"The Most Great\" or \"The Grand,\" expressing His absolute majesty, infinite vastness, and supreme authority. This name reminds us of Allah’s (ﷻ) unparalleled greatness, urging humility, as all greatness belongs solely to Him, contrasting with the finite nature of human achievements.",
  "3058": "كَبِيرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كَبِيرَةٌ signifies \"great,\" \"big,\" or \"major,\" often denoting significant magnitude, heaviness, or importance. In Islamic terminology, كَبائِر (plural of كَبِيرَةٌ) refers to major sins, emphasizing their severe consequences and moral gravity. The root highlights the impact of magnitude, symbolizing actions weighty in their moral implications and burden on faith and the soul. This illustrates how major sins make seeking Allah’s (ﷻ) help and submission feel burdensome, highlighting the need to avoid them for spiritual clarity and ease in worship.",
  "3059": "كَبِّرْ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبَّرَ meaning \"he magnified\" or \"he declared greatness.\" كَبِّرْ is the command form, meaning \"Magnify!\" or \"Glorify!\" The connection lies in commanding someone to actively acknowledge and proclaim the greatness of Allah (ﷻ). This reflects the root’s emphasis on magnitude, grandeur, and exaltation. The term not only highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) unparalleled greatness but also fosters humility, reverence, and submission in the one who magnifies Him. It highlights the transformative power of recognizing Allah’s (ﷻ) supreme authority in one’s worship and daily life.",
  "3060": "كَتَبَ and related words stem from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" This verb embodies the act of writing or inscribing with formality and authority. The concept extends beyond mere writing to include the prescription of laws, the decree of destinies, and the establishment of obligations, highlighting the profound role of writing in documenting decisions, conveying authority, and preserving knowledge. It reflects the enduring power of the written word as a tool for communication, governance, and the safeguarding of wisdom and guidance.",
  "3061": "كَتَمَ and related words stem from the root ك-ت-م, and as the root verb, it means \"he concealed,\" \"he hid,\" or \"he kept secret.\" This verb encompasses the act of hiding information, suppressing truth, or withholding knowledge. The connection lies in the deliberate act of keeping something unseen or unknown, often implying intentional secrecy. The root emphasizes the moral implications of concealing truth, highlighting the potential harm in withholding important information from others.",
  "3062": "كَثُرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" This form signifies the natural process of growth in numbers or abundance. The connection lies in the root’s core concept of profusion and increase, emphasizing organic or unintentional multiplication, such as the growth of populations, resources, or blessings. كَثُرَ reflects the expansive quality inherent in abundance, showing how the root captures the fundamental idea of increase as a universal phenomenon.",
  "3063": "كَثِيبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ب, with the root verb كَثَبَ meaning \"he collected,\" \"he gathered together,\" or \"he accumulated.\" كَثِيبٌ refers to a \"heap of sand\" or \"sandhill,\" formed through the gradual accumulation of sand particles. This reflects the root’s central idea of gathering, where small and seemingly insignificant grains come together to create something larger and more noticeable. It highlights the power of steady, consistent efforts in building something significant, while also reminding us of the fragile and impermanent nature of such formations, easily scattered or undone.",
  "3064": "كَثِيرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" كَثِيرٌ means \"much,\" \"many,\" or \"abundant,\" referring to something that exists in a large amount or number. It is connected to the root’s focus on abundance, covering both physical and non-physical forms of plenty.",
  "3065": "كَثِيرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" كَثِيرَةٌ means \"much,\" \"many,\" or \"abundant\" and is the feminine form, describing things or entities existing in large quantities. The connection to the root lies in the idea of profusion and multiplication, which can also convey nuances of expansiveness and sustenance in some contexts. This reflects the root's focus on abundance and the enduring impact of increase across various dimensions.",
  "3066": "كَثَّرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" كَثَّرَ means \"he multiplied (something),\" \"he increased (something),\" or \"he made abundant.\" This causative, transitive form highlights the deliberate act of causing growth or profusion, where an external force or source actively contributes to abundance. The connection to the root is found in the transformative nature of the action, reflecting the capacity to generate growth and enhance abundance. It highlights themes of purposeful action and influence in fostering plentitude, whether physical, numerical, or metaphorical.",
  "3067": "كَثْرَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" كَثْرَةٌ means \"abundance,\" \"plenty,\" or \"multitude,\" describing a state of profusion or being plentiful. This word encapsulates the result of multiplication or increase, directly tying back to the root’s focus on the growth and expansive nature of quantities. The term highlights not just numerical increase but also the richness and diversity that abundance can signify in various contexts, from physical resources to metaphorical blessings.",
  "3068": "كَدْحٌ and related words stem from the root ك-د-ح, with the root verb كَدَحَ meaning \"he labored,\" \"he toiled,\" or \"he struggled persistently.\" كَدْحٌ refers to \"toil,\" \"hardship,\" or \"continuous exertion,\" highlighting the act of laboring or enduring hardship in pursuit of a goal. The connection lies in the root's focus on the intensity and perseverance of effort, encapsulating the challenges and endurance required in the journey of life. كَدْحٌ emphasizes the notion of striving and struggling as a defining aspect of human experience, often with the understanding that such effort leads to meaningful outcomes, whether in this world or the hereafter.",
  "3069": "كَذَبَ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he lied,\" \"he spoke falsely,\" or \"he told an untruth.\" The root conveys broad meanings related to \"lying,\" \"fabrication,\" or \"speaking falsely.\" كَذَبَ encompasses both intentional falsehoods and unintentional inaccuracies, reflecting the root's thematic focus on deviation from truth in any form. It signifies not only the act of fabricating or denying reality but also the distortion of trust and authenticity in communication. The inclusion of unintentional falsehoods highlights the gravity of even minor deviations from truth, emphasizing the moral and societal implications of falsehood.",
  "3070": "كَذِبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied,\" \"he spoke falsely,\" or \"he told an untruth.\" كَذِبٌ means \"lie,\" \"falsehood,\" or \"untruth,\" referring to the content or act of lying. The root encompasses intentional and unintentional deviations from truth, reflecting the broader implications of falsehood in speech and action. كَذِبٌ highlights the act of falsity as a phenomenon, emphasizing the root's connection to communication and trust, and highlighting how deviations from truth—intentional or not—erode the integrity of relationships and understanding.",
  "3071": "كَذَّابٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied\" or \"he spoke falsely.\" كَذَّابٌ is an intensive form meaning \"great liar,\" \"habitual liar,\" or \"frequent liar,\" describing someone persistently and habitually engaging in falsehoods. This form intensifies the personal characteristic of dishonesty, highlighting a deep entrenchment in deceit. Unlike كِذَّابٌ, which focuses on the act or state of falsehood, كَذَّابٌ characterizes an individual as someone defined by repeated or extreme acts of lying. The root’s broader implications of fabrication and falsehood are concentrated here on the person who exemplifies these traits in their habitual behavior.",
  "3072": "كَذَّبَ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied\" or \"he told a falsehood.\" كَذَّبَ means \"he declared (someone) a liar,\" \"he denied,\" or \"he rejected (the truth).\" This intensive form emphasizes deliberate actions of accusing others of falsehood or rejecting their claims as untrue. It extends the root's focus on falsehood to active opposition, highlighting rejection or disbelief, often in response to a message or testimony. The root connects to the inherent falsity in both lying and the denial of authenticity, making كَذَّبَ a term that embodies persistent rejection or deliberate discrediting of truth.",
  "3073": "كَـرِهَ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, and as the root verb, it means \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" This verb encapsulates the feeling of aversion or reluctance toward something. It reflects emotional resistance, often tied to moral or situational discontent. كَـرِهَ emphasizes the subjective experience of displeasure, highlighting the tension between one’s desires and external circumstances. It serves as a foundation for derived forms that explore both personal aversion and the imposition of unwelcome actions, illustrating the multifaceted nature of human discontent and resistance.",
  "3074": "كَرِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-م, with the root verbs كَـرُمَ meaning \"he or it was highly esteemed, valued, precious, or rare,\" and كَرَّمَ meaning \"he honored greatly\" or \"he ennobled.\" كَرِيمٌ means \"noble\" or \"generous,\" describing someone or something distinguished by honorable conduct, magnanimity, and high value. It also conveys the idea of being precious or of great worth, whether referring to a person, object, or quality. ٱلْكَرِيمُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, refers to \"The Generous\" or \"The Noble,\" signifying His boundless generosity and nobility in granting blessings. This inspires believers to reflect divine generosity and nobility through kindness, giving, and dignity.",
  "3075": "كَرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ر, with the root verb كَرَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repeated,\" \"he charged repeatedly,\" or \"he turned back.\" كَرَّةٌ means \"a turn,\" \"a return,\" or \"a repetition,\" emphasizing the root's core idea of recurrence and persistence. This term reflects the concept of revisiting or experiencing something again, whether it is a physical return, a repeated action, or an opportunity to try once more. The root also conveys a sense of persistence or determination, as seen in repeated efforts or attempts, highlighting the cyclical nature of certain actions. كَرَّةٌ embodies the idea of striving again, symbolizing second chances or renewed efforts.",
  "3076": "كَرَّمَ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-م, with the root verb كَـرُمَ meaning \"he or it was highly esteemed, valued, precious, or rare.\" كَرَّمَ is an intensive form meaning \"he honored greatly\" or \"he ennobled,\" reflecting deliberate and significant acts of elevating or dignifying someone. The term conveys a bestowal of respect, dignity, or privilege, emphasizing the recognition of inherent value and worth. It embodies the active elevation of others through reverence and honor. In a divine context, كَرَّمَ emphasizes Allah’s (ﷻ) deliberate act of ennobling His creation, as in وَلَقَدْ كَرَّمْنَا بَنِي آدَمَ, highlighting humanity’s elevated and distinguished status among all creation.",
  "3077": "كَرَّهَ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, with the root verb كَـرِهَ meaning \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" كَرَّهَ is an intensified form meaning \"he made someone dislike\" or \"he caused to be detested,\" signifying an active effort to instill aversion or hatred in others. This reflects the root's emphasis on strong emotional rejection. كَرَّهَ often implies a divine or intentional act of making something detestable, emphasizing its moral or spiritual unacceptability. The term highlights the transformative power of aversion, where dislike becomes a means of guiding actions or attitudes.",
  "3078": "كَرْبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ب, with the root verb كَـرَبَ meaning \"he was in distress,\" \"he was afflicted,\" or \"he was anxious.\" The root also conveys \"tightening,\" \"pressing,\" or \"binding,\" reflecting a sense of constriction or severe difficulty. كَرْبٌ means \"distress,\" \"affliction,\" or \"anguish,\" describing intense emotional or mental strain. It connects to the root’s imagery of being overwhelmed or burdened, akin to being physically bound. This term highlights human vulnerability during profound hardship and the universal need for relief, symbolizing the transformative power of enduring trials.",
  "3079": "كَرْهٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, with the root verb كَـرِهَ meaning \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" كَرْهٌ means \"unwillingness\" or \"reluctance.\" It describes the state of being compelled to act against one's will, directly tied to the root’s focus on aversion and resistance. In classical usage, it conveys both an emotional reluctance and a situational compulsion, highlighting the tension between one’s internal desires and external obligations. This term highlights the struggle of performing actions without joy or consent, often reflecting broader themes of endurance and submission under pressure.",
  "3080": "كَسادٌ and related words stem from the root ك-س-د, with the root verb كَسَدَ meaning \"it became unsalable\" or \"it stagnated.\" كَسادٌ means \"stagnation\" or \"lack of demand.\" The connection lies in the concept of goods or markets becoming inactive or sluggish, reflecting the root's idea of decline or inactivity. This term highlights economic or social situations where progress halts, emphasizing the effects of inactivity on growth and prosperity.",
  "3081": "كَسَبَ and related words stem from the root ك-س-ب, and as the root verb, it means \"he earned,\" \"he gained,\" or \"he acquired.\" It reflects the act of obtaining something through effort or work. The root encompasses concepts of earning, gaining, or profiting. It highlights the fundamental human endeavor of striving to acquire benefits or provisions, emphasizing the importance of effort and labor in achieving gains.",
  "3082": "كَشَفَ and related words stem from the root ك-ش-ف, and as the root verb, it means \"he uncovered\" or \"he revealed.\" It reflects the fundamental action of removing a covering, whether physical or metaphorical, to make something known or visible. It encompasses concepts of exposure, revelation, and disclosure. In classical Arabic, كَشَفَ also signifies alleviating burdens or lifting hardships, as when distress is removed or harm is averted. This verb highlights the transformative process of transitioning from obscurity to visibility, emphasizing the importance of discovery, clarity, and enlightenment in human understanding.",
  "3083": "كَشْفٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ش-ف, with the root verb كَشَفَ meaning \"he uncovered\" or \"he revealed.\" كَشْفٌ refers to \"uncovering,\" \"removal,\" or \"disclosure,\" describing the act or process of making something visible or known. This word carries the root’s emphasis on exposure and revelation, often applied to contexts of alleviating distress, revealing truths, or lifting concealments. كَشْفٌ symbolizes the transition from hiddenness to clarity, illustrating the profound significance of uncovering insights, resolving ambiguities, or bringing hidden realities to light, both in a physical and metaphorical sense.",
  "3084": "كَظِيمٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ظ-م, with the root verb كَظَمَ meaning \"he suppressed\" or \"he restrained.\" كَظِيمٌ means \"filled with suppressed emotions,\" particularly those of grief or anger. It describes a state of internal tension and silent struggle, where emotions are intensely felt yet held back. This term reflects the burden of emotional restraint, emphasizing the weight of containment and the root’s imagery of being filled to the brim, symbolizing a profound inner conflict.",
  "3085": "الكَعْبَةُ and related words stem from the root ك-ع-ب, which conveys the idea of something elevated, prominent, or distinct in shape. This root is foundational in describing the Kaaba, the sacred cuboid structure in Mecca known as the House of Allah (ﷻ). The term emphasizes its physical elevation and spiritual prominence as a central point of worship and reverence. The root also encompasses notions of stability and centrality, reflecting the Kaaba's role as a unifying direction for prayers and its enduring sanctity in Islamic tradition. This connection to elevation and prominence highlights its unmatched significance in the hearts of believers.",
  "3086": "كَعْبَيْنِ and related words stem from the root ك-ع-ب, meaning \"two ankles.\" The root signifies prominence and elevation, which can be metaphorically connected to the ankles as a distinct and essential joint. The ankles are pivotal for movement, balance, and enabling the act of walking upright—a defining characteristic of human beings. By facilitating purposeful action in this world, the ankles symbolize a means through which one can strive for higher deeds and spiritual elevation. This serves as a profound reminder that the correct use of physical faculties in this life can lead to spiritual elevation in the hereafter, beautifully illustrating the integration of physical function and spiritual purpose.",
  "3087": "كَفَرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَفَرَ means \"he disbelieved\" or \"he was ungrateful,\" describing the act of rejecting truth or failing to acknowledge blessings. The connection lies in \"covering\" or \"concealing\" truth or favors, directly relating to the root's concept of hiding. This verb emphasizes the moral failing of denying evident truths or being ungrateful for blessings, highlighting the ethical and spiritual consequences of such actions.",
  "3088": "كَفَىٰ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ى, which means \"he sufficed,\" \"he was sufficient,\" or \"he fulfilled.\" This root captures the concept of being adequate, fulfilling requirements, or fully meeting a need without leaving any deficiency. The verb كَفَىٰ reflects the act of sufficing in a way that ensures completeness, aligning with the root’s emphasis on adequacy and fulfillment. This word highlights the profound sufficiency that meets all demands, often referring to the perfection of Allah’s (ﷻ) sufficiency, where His fulfillment of needs is unparalleled and entirely encompassing.",
  "3089": "كَفُورٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَفُورٌ is an intensive descriptive form meaning \"inherently ungrateful\" or \"inherent disbeliever,\" emphasizing a deeply rooted state of ingratitude or disbelief. The connection lies in the persistent \"covering\" or denial of blessings or truth, aligning with the root’s concept of concealment. This term highlights the moral deficiency of an individual whose character is defined by a lack of gratitude or acknowledgment of truth. While كَفُورٌ emphasizes the inward quality of rejection, كَفَّارٌ reflects habitual outward behaviors, distinguishing inner disposition from repeated actions.",
  "3090": "كَفِيلٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ل, with the root verb كَفَلَ meaning \"he took care of,\" \"he guaranteed,\" or \"he supported.\" كَفِيلٌ translates as \"guarantor\" or \"sponsor,\" describing an entity that assumes responsibility for another, whether in providing care, fulfilling obligations, or ensuring security. The root embodies accountability and guardianship, reflecting the act of guaranteeing or taking charge comprehensively. كَفِيلٌ highlights the gravity of making oaths or pledges, particularly when invoking Allah’s (ﷻ) name, signifying binding responsibility. The term emphasizes sacred trust, requiring integrity and fulfillment of obligations, and symbolizes trust, reliability, and support.",
  "3091": "كَفَّارٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَفَّارٌ is an intensive active form meaning \"habitually ungrateful\" or \"habitual disbeliever,\" emphasizing repeated and excessive actions of rejection or denial. The connection lies in the ongoing and active \"covering\" or \"concealing\" of truth or blessings, reflecting a pattern of persistent ingratitude or disbelief. Unlike كَفُورٌ, which highlights an inherent state, كَفَّارٌ focuses on outward habitual behaviors, emphasizing the repeated rejection of guidance or blessings.",
  "3092": "كَفَّارَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَفَّارَةٌ means \"expiation\" or \"atonement,\" referring to an act that \"covers\" sins or nullifies their impact. The connection to the root lies in the act of \"covering\" past wrongdoings through repentance or corrective actions, symbolizing the mercy and opportunity for redemption. This term reflects the transformative process of concealing errors through sincere effort, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) provision for erasing sins and restoring spiritual balance.",
  "3093": "كَفَّ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ف, and as the root verb, it means \"he restrained,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he prevented.\" It conveys the idea of controlling or holding something back, whether physically, emotionally, or socially. The root emphasizes restraint as a means of discipline and balance, reflecting self-control or the prevention of harm or excess. كَفَّ highlights the importance of measured action, where restraint ensures fairness, order, and the prevention of negative consequences, embodying the broader theme of intentional limitation.",
  "3094": "كَفَّرَ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَفَّرَ means \"he atoned for\" or \"he made expiation for,\" denoting the active effort to \"cover\" sins through repentance or corrective measures. The connection lies in nullifying the effects of wrongdoing by following up with good deeds, directly aligning with the root's concept of concealment. This verb highlights the dynamic nature of atonement as a process that not only removes sins but also restores harmony, highlighting the moral responsibility to seek forgiveness and actively rectify one’s actions.",
  "3095": "كَفَّلَ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ل, with the root verb كَفَلَ meaning \"he took care of,\" \"he guaranteed,\" or \"he supported.\" كَفَّلَ means \"he entrusted\" or \"he made someone responsible,\" with the doubled middle consonant intensifying the act, emphasizing deliberate and active delegation. It reflects the root’s essence of care, guardianship, and accountability, highlighting the weight of entrusting responsibilities and the trust involved. كَفَّلَ highlights the importance of fulfilling duties with integrity and commitment, embodying themes of mutual reliance and the moral gravity of delegation.",
  "3096": "كَفَّيْنِ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ف, with the root verb كَفَّ meaning \"he restrained,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he prevented.\" كَفَّيْنِ means \"two palms,\" connecting to the root through the hands' role as tools of action and restraint. The root verb’s meaning of restraining or withholding is significant, as humans are often prone to exceeding limits in actions involving the hands—whether in spending, physical acts, or other interactions. This connection serves as a reminder of accountability, urging control and balance in actions. كَفَّيْنِ thus symbolizes the importance of discipline in both physical and metaphorical senses, emphasizing the need to manage what the hands produce or withhold.",
  "3097": "كَلالَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ل, with the root verb كَلَّ meaning \"he became weak,\" \"he was exhausted,\" or \"it became dim or dull.\" كَلالَةٌ refers to a person who has neither parents nor children as heirs, emphasizing the absence of direct lineage. The root broadly conveys weakness, depletion, or the loss of sharpness. This term metaphorically reflects the concept of diminished familial ties and the depletion of immediate successors, resonating with the root’s broader themes of fatigue, incapacity, and incompleteness.",
  "3098": "كَلامٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-م, with the root verbs كَلَمَ, meaning \"he wounded,\" and كَـلَّمَ, meaning \"he spoke.\" كَلامٌ means \"speech,\" specifically referring to structured and meaningful communication that expresses thoughts or ideas. The connection lies in speech's ability to convey a coherent message, directly linking to the root’s dual concepts. This term emphasizes the profound power of speech to inspire, enlighten, or, metaphorically, to wound, highlighting its intentionality and clarity. Unlike a mere aggregation of words, كَلامٌ always implies meaningful and deliberate communication, reinforcing the idea that impactful speech carries the weight of responsibility and influence.",
  "3099": "كَلِمٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-م, with the root verbs كَلَمَ, meaning \"he wounded,\" and كَـلَّمَ, meaning \"he spoke.\" كَلِمٌ means \"words,\" referring to a collection of individual words, whether connected meaningfully or not. The connection lies in the collective potential of words, where even disjointed terms can evoke emotions, clarify ideas, or leave lasting impressions, much like a wound. This term highlights the cumulative power of language, where words, when aggregated, hold the potential to unify or divide. While كَلامٌ emphasizes coherence and purpose, كَلِمٌ reflects broader themes of language as a tool for expression, aligning with the root’s impactful and versatile nature.",
  "3100": "كَلِمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-م, with the root verbs كَلَمَ meaning \"he wounded\" and كَـلَّمَ meaning \"he spoke.\" كَلِمَةٌ means \"word,\" signifying the fundamental unit of speech. The connection lies in the dual meaning of the root, which highlights the power of words to metaphorically \"wound\" or heal, reflecting their profound impact. This term highlights how a single word can influence emotions, convey truth, or cause harm, embodying the transformative potential of language.",
  "3101": "كَلٌّ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ل, with the root verb كَلَّ meaning \"he became weak,\" \"he was exhausted,\" or \"it became dim or dull.\" كَلٌّ means \"a tired or exhausted person,\" and it can also refer to \"a burden\" or \"one dependent on others for support.\" The root connects to physical and emotional depletion, weakness, or incapacity. The broader meanings reflect the concept of diminished strength or vitality, whether in a person, object, or lineage. كَلٌّ emphasizes dependency and fatigue, resonating with the root’s theme of weariness and burden.",
  "3102": "كَـلَّمَ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-م, with the root verbs كَلَمَ, meaning \"he wounded,\" and كَـلَّمَ, meaning \"he spoke.\" كَـلَّمَ means \"he spoke to\" or \"he addressed,\" emphasizing the initiation of communication. The connection between the root meanings lies in the profound impact of speech, which, like a wound, can leave a lasting impression. This verb highlights the interactive nature of communication, where words, much like physical actions, have the power to create connections, influence emotions, and shape relationships.",
  "3103": "كَلْبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ب, with the root verb كَلِبَ meaning \"he was greedy\" or \"he became rabid.\" كَلْبٌ means \"dog,\" reflecting traits often associated with dogs, such as loyalty, persistence, or voracity. The connection lies in the duality of characteristics: while dogs are known for their loyalty and service, they can also exhibit greed or intense desire, aligning with the root's broader concepts. This term symbolically captures both positive traits, like devotion and reliability, and negative traits, such as unchecked appetite or aggression, depending on the context.",
  "3104": "The interrogative particle كَمْ means \"how much\" or \"how many\" and is essential for asking about quantity, number, or extent. It is used both literally, to count or measure, and rhetorically, to prompt reflection or emphasize significant concepts. In the Qur'an, كَمْ often serves as a rhetorical device, encouraging contemplation of Allah’s (ﷻ) countless blessings, the lessons from history, or the magnitude of divine actions. This dual purpose makes كَمْ a powerful tool for both precise inquiry and profound reflection, enriching the language with depth and versatility.",
  "3105": "كَنْزٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ن-ز, with the root verb كَنَزَ meaning \"he hoarded\" or \"he stored away.\" كَنْزٌ refers to \"treasure\" or \"hoarded wealth,\" emphasizing valuables that are accumulated, hidden, or buried. The connection lies in the act of gathering and concealing resources. Additionally, the root carries nuances of pressing or compacting items into a confined space, such as storing dates or filling a bag to its maximum capacity, highlighting the deliberate effort to secure and protect wealth. This term highlights themes of accumulation and hidden resources.",
  "3106": "كَنَزَ and related words stem from the root ك-ن-ز, where the root verb كَنَزَ primarily means \"he hoarded\" or \"he stored away.\" This verb denotes the deliberate act of gathering and concealing wealth or resources, often by burying, compacting, or storing them in hidden locations. The root also extends to tightly packing objects, reflecting effort to secure possessions. The connection lies in the physical act of concealment and its metaphorical implications, particularly greed and selfishness. This term emphasizes the dangers of material accumulation, cautioning against neglecting social and moral responsibilities, as wealth hoarded can become a source of hardship rather than benefit.",
  "3107": "كَنُودٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ن-د, with the root verb كَنَدَ meaning \"he was ungrateful,\" \"he denied favors,\" or \"he refused to acknowledge blessings.\" كَنُودٌ refers to someone who is \"extremely ungrateful\" or \"an ingrate,\" emphasizing a heightened and persistent state of ingratitude. The root conveys themes of rejection, denial, and a refusal to recognize or repay kindness or blessings. It also carries the nuance of severing ties, metaphorically reflecting the rejection of bonds created by generosity. The term كَنُودٌ highlights entrenched ungratefulness that leads to neglecting duties of gratitude and repayment, often resulting in isolation or estrangement.",
  "3108": "كَـهْفٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ه-ف, which means \"a cave.\" كَـهْفٌ refers to a natural hollow or cavity in the earth, serving as a protective shelter. The connection lies in the cave's role as a refuge, offering safety and concealment from external dangers. This concept extends to both physical and spiritual refuge, symbolizing a place of solace, protection, and retreat in times of need, emphasizing the themes of security and sanctuary inherent in the root.",
  "3109": "كَـهْلٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ه-ل, which conveys the idea of \"maturity\" or \"middle age,\" referring specifically to a person who has attained full physical and mental maturity. كَـهْلٌ describes an individual in the prime of life, characterized by strength, wisdom, and experience. The connection lies in the transition from youth to maturity, embodying the peak of human capability and readiness. This term emphasizes the concept of completeness and the ability to shoulder responsibilities, reflecting a stage of life marked by balance, stability, and the fulfillment of one's potential.",
  "3110": "كَواعِبُ and related words stem from the root ك-ع-ب, referring to graceful companions of the hereafter. The root signifies prominence, elevation, and distinction. The term describes young women adorned with refinement, maturity, and grace, embodying vitality and elegance. It conveys an ideal of perfection and distinction, aligned with the root’s emphasis on elevated qualities. This word encapsulates the essence of youth and beauty in a dignified and honorable manner, reflecting themes of prominence and excellence that transcend the physical, emphasizing purity, refinement, and grace.",
  "3111": "كَوافِرُ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كَوافِرُ, the plural of كَافِرَةٌ, means \"female disbelievers\" or \"women who conceal the truth.\" The root’s meaning of \"covering\" connects to the act of denying or rejecting what is evident, particularly truth or faith. This term highlights the deliberate nature of concealing or turning away from guidance, emphasizing the moral and spiritual responsibility to acknowledge and uphold truth.",
  "3112": "الْكَوْثَرُ stems from the root ك-ث-ر, with the root verb كَثُرَ meaning \"it became numerous,\" \"it increased,\" or \"it multiplied.\" The root conveys themes of abundance, vastness, and profusion. الْكَوْثَرُ refers to a magnificent river in Paradise granted to the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ), symbolizing unmatched abundance and divine favor. Described as whiter than milk, sweeter than honey, and bordered with pavilions of hollowed pearls, it epitomizes ultimate bounty and purity. The root highlights both the river’s physical abundance and spiritual generosity, reflecting the infinite blessings Allah (ﷻ) bestows. It signifies not just a river but the immeasurable rewards reserved for the righteous.",
  "3113": "كَوْكَبٌ and related words stem from the root ك-و-ك-ب, referring to \"a star,\" \"a celestial body,\" or \"a constellation.\" The term is used to describe luminous bodies visible in the night sky, symbolizing guidance, brilliance, and beauty. كَوَاكِبُ is the plural form meaning \"stars\" or \"constellations,\" emphasizing the multitude of these celestial entities. The root conveys the idea of radiance and prominence, as stars often serve as markers of direction and points of wonder in human observation. The term also carries metaphorical significance in Arabic literature, where stars symbolize loftiness, excellence, and clarity, reflecting their elevated and enduring position in the heavens.",
  "3114": "كَيْدٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ي-د, with the root verb كَادَ meaning \"he plotted,\" \"he schemed,\" or \"he devised.\" كَيْدٌ refers to \"a plot,\" \"a scheme,\" or \"a plan,\" often involving calculated efforts to achieve an outcome, frequently with cunning or deception. The term emphasizes strategic thinking, whether to outwit, deceive, or overcome a challenge. While it carries negative connotations in human actions, it can also denote cleverness or tactical skill. When attributed to Allah (ﷻ), it signifies a perfect, faultless plan executed with wisdom, justice, and His divine will, reflecting His supreme ability to counteract schemes and fulfill His purpose flawlessly.",
  "3115": "The particle كَيْفَ is an interrogative adverb used to ask about the manner, condition, or state of something. It translates as \"how?\" or \"in what manner?\" The word seeks to determine the nature or method of an action or state, often emphasizing clarity or understanding. In classical usage and in the Qur'an, كَيْفَ is also employed to highlight amazement or wonder, depending on context, as in rhetorical questions or expressions of astonishment. Its role lies in serving as a tool for inquiry or reflection, inviting thought about the condition, quality, or method of something. This versatility makes it central to both practical and expressive language, fostering understanding and articulation.",
  "3116": "كَيْلٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ي-ل, with the root verb كَالَ meaning \"he measured\" or \"he weighed.\" كَيْلٌ refers to \"measure\" or \"measurement,\" emphasizing the act or process of quantifying goods. The connection lies in the fundamental role of measurement in trade, highlighting the importance of fairness and precision in societal transactions. This term highlights the ethical obligation to ensure accurate and equitable dealings.",
  "3117": "كُبَراءُ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كُبَراءُ, the plural of كَبِيرٌ, means \"prominent ones,\" \"elders,\" or \"leaders,\" referring to individuals of significant status, age, or influence. The root emphasizes magnitude and importance, capturing the respect and authority such figures command in societal contexts. This term highlights the influential roles of leaders and elders, whose prominence often shapes collective decisions and cultural values.",
  "3118": "كُبِتَ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ت, with the root verb كَبَتَ meaning \"to suppress,\" \"to subdue,\" or \"to humiliate.\" كُبِتَ is a passive form meaning \"he was frustrated,\" \"he was suppressed,\" or \"he was humiliated.\" This root conveys themes of suppression, restraint, and quelling, whether physically, emotionally, or morally. It reflects the experience of being thwarted or subdued, often through external forces or divine intervention. In a moral context, it signifies the humiliation or downfall of those who engage in wrongdoing, emphasizing how their schemes and desires are ultimately subdued or rendered powerless.",
  "3119": "كُبّارٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كُبّارٌ is an intensive form meaning \"immense\" or \"very great,\" denoting amplified magnitude or enormity. The root conveys themes of greatness, growth, and prominence, which can apply to physical size, numbers, or abstract significance. While كُبّارٌ can reflect extraordinary scale or prominence, it may also imply something overwhelmingly excessive or burdensome, highlighting the potential for both positive and negative associations with such immensity. This duality highlights the root's capacity to signify grandeur as well as overbearing or oppressive largeness.",
  "3120": "كُبَّتْ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ب, with the root verb كَبَّ meaning \"he threw down,\" \"he overturned,\" or \"he cast down.\" كُبَّتْ means \"it was thrown down\" or \"it was cast down.\" The connection lies in being overturned or toppled, reflecting themes of downfall, subjugation, or humiliation. This reflects the root's essence of inversion, where something or someone is brought to a lower position. It symbolizes the consequences of arrogance, wrongdoing, or resistance to truth, leading to downfall. The use of كُبَّتْ highlights not just the physical act of being cast down, but the metaphorical representation of how such actions result in disgrace and loss of status.",
  "3121": "كُبْكِبُوا and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ك-ب, with the root verb كَبَّ meaning \"he threw down,\" \"he overturned,\" or \"he cast down upon his face.\" كُبْكِبُوا means \"they will be hurled down one upon another.\" The reduplication in the word intensifies the action, emphasizing forceful and sequential casting down. This connects directly to the root's concept of overturning or throwing down, symbolizing complete defeat and humiliation. It highlights the wrongdoers’ inevitable downfall into the Hellfire, reflecting the consequences of their deeds.",
  "3122": "كُرْهٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ر-ه, with the root verb كَـرِهَ meaning \"he disliked\" or \"he hated.\" كُرْهٌ refers to \"hardship\" or \"unwilling difficulty,\" emphasizing not just aversion but the strain or burden associated with it. Unlike كَرْهٌ, which leans more toward emotional reluctance, كُرْهٌ focuses on the experience of difficulty endured reluctantly. كُرْهٌ is often used to describe situations where hardship is accepted under compulsion, reflecting both physical and emotional resistance. The term vividly portrays the discomfort and strain of enduring what is detested or burdensome.",
  "3123": "كُسَالَىٰ and related words stem from the root ك-س-ل, with the root verb كَسِلَ meaning \"he was or became lazy\" or \"he was sluggish.\" كُسَالَىٰ means \"lazy ones\" or \"slothful people.\" The connection lies in describing those who embody the root's concept of laziness or inactivity. This term highlights the state of lethargy and lack of motivation, emphasizing the consequences of indolence on personal and communal productivity.",
  "3124": "كُشِطَتْ and related words stem from the root ك-ش-ط, with the root verb كَشَطَ meaning \"he stripped off,\" \"he skinned,\" or \"he removed.\" كُشِطَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was stripped off\" or \"it was removed.\" The connection lies in the action of something being peeled away or uncovered, reflecting the root's concept of removal or exposure. This term evokes imagery of layers being taken off to reveal what lies beneath, emphasizing transitions from concealment to exposure.",
  "3125": "كُفُؤٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-أ, meaning \"to be equal,\" \"to correspond,\" or \"to be suited.\" كُفُؤٌ means \"equal,\" \"match,\" or \"peer.\" The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on balance, suitability, and correspondence, where one entity is \"fit\" or \"suitable\" for another. The broader range of meanings also points to equivalence in status or worth and compatibility. In the context of Allah’s (ﷻ) uniqueness, this term highlights that there is none equal to Allah (ﷻ), for no one corresponds or matches His divine perfection. It emphasizes Allah’s (ﷻ) absolute and unmatched nature, reinforcing His incomparable greatness and sovereignty, and that nothing is \"fit\" to be Allah’s (ﷻ) equal.",
  "3126": "كُفُورٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كُفُورٌ refers to \"acts of disbelief\" or \"instances of ingratitude,\" emphasizing repeated actions of denial. The connection lies in the cumulative \"covering\" or \"concealing\" of truth or blessings, compounding rejection over time. This term warns against habitual disbelief or ingratitude, highlighting how repeated actions create barriers to recognizing truth and appreciating blessings, deeply tied to the root's concept of \"covering.\"",
  "3127": "كُفْرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كُفْرٌ means \"disbelief\" or \"ingratitude,\" describing the act of rejecting or denying truth or blessings. The root’s concept of \"covering\" aligns with obscuring acknowledgment of Allah’s (ﷻ) signs or favors. كُفْرٌ highlights the seriousness of rejection, serving as a reminder of the responsibility to recognize truth and gratitude to avoid spiritual and moral consequences.",
  "3128": "كُفْرَانَ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ر, with the root verb كَفَرَ meaning \"he covered,\" \"he concealed,\" or \"he disbelieved.\" كُفْرَانَ means \"denial,\" \"rejection,\" or \"ingratitude,\" emphasizing the act of covering or disregarding what is due, such as a blessing, effort, or truth. The connection to the root lies in \"covering\" a truth or favor, making it seem as though it does not exist. In contexts like فَلَا كُفْرَانَ لِسَعْيِهِ, it assures that no effort will be dismissed, emphasizing accountability and recognition. كُفْرَانَ highlights the ethical and spiritual responsibility to appreciate and uphold truth, blessings, and efforts, warning against the grave consequences of concealment, rejection, or ingratitude.",
  "3129": "كُلٌّ and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ل, with the root verb كَلَّ meaning \"he encompassed,\" \"he included all,\" or \"it became weak or dull.\" كُلٌّ means \"all,\" \"every,\" or \"entire,\" signifying inclusiveness and totality. The root also relates to weakness or incapacity, as seen in the word كَلالَةٌ, referring to the incapacitation of lineage. The connection lies in the completeness or encompassing nature of things, including their eventual decline. كُلٌّ embodies the concept of universality while subtly tying to the transient nature of all-encompassing entities, as all things ultimately weaken and perish.",
  "3130": "كُلَّمَا and related words stem from the root ك-ل-ل, with the root verb كَلَّ meaning \"he encompassed,\" \"he included all,\" or \"it became fatigued or weak.\" كُلَّمَا means \"whenever,\" \"every time,\" or \"as often as,\" signifying the recurrence or universality of an action whenever a condition is met. The connection lies in the root’s concept of totality, encompassing all instances, while also reflecting the idea of repetitive actions leading to fatigue or weariness. This subtle tie highlights how recurring events, though encompassing, may also imply a sense of limitation or strain over time.",
  "3131": "كُنَّسٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ن-س, with the root verb كَنَسَ meaning \"he entered his lair\" or \"he sought a hiding place,\" often referring to an antelope retreating to its covert. كُنَّسٌ describes \"those who withdraw\" or \"those who enter hiding places,\" emphasizing the act of retreat or concealment. In the Qur'an, it refers to celestial bodies, particularly planets, that \"withdraw\" from sight during specific phases. The connection lies in the act of retreating, hiding, or becoming concealed, directly reflecting the root's concept. This term highlights the cyclical and deliberate nature of celestial movements, likened to the purposeful withdrawal of creatures to their shelter.",
  "3132": "كُوِّرَتْ and related words stem from the root ك-و-ر, with the root verb كَوَّرَ meaning \"he wrapped up,\" \"he rolled up,\" or \"he folded up.\" كُوِّرَتْ is a passive form meaning \"it was wrapped\" or \"it was rolled up.\" The root conveys the imagery of gathering something vast into a compact form, emphasizing the acts of tightening, enclosing, or concluding. Historically, it was used to describe wrapping a turban, illustrating the process of folding or winding into a compact state. In the Qur'an, it describes the wrapping of night over day and day over night, highlighting their seamless alternation, and also refers to the sun being folded up or extinguished, symbolizing a dramatic cosmic event marking the end times.",
  "3133": "كِبَرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كِبَرٌ signifies \"old age\" or \"greatness,\" connecting the idea of physical and temporal growth to significance or importance. It reflects the state of advanced years, symbolizing the wisdom, respect, and honor often associated with maturity. The root's dimension of growth and magnitude ties to the concept of experience and endurance, highlighting the reverence due to those who have grown through life’s trials and gained insight over time.",
  "3134": "كِبْرٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كِبْرٌ means \"pride\" or \"arrogance,\" derived from the root's broader concept of greatness and magnitude. This term reflects the negative side of perceiving oneself as superior to others, where the pursuit of greatness turns into moral arrogance. It serves as a caution against excessive pride, which not only leads to looking down on others but also undermines humility, a core ethical value in human behavior.",
  "3135": "كِبْرِياءُ and related words stem from the root ك-ب-ر, with the root verb كَبُرَ meaning \"he became great\" or \"he grew.\" كِبْرِياءُ means \"majesty,\" \"grandeur,\" or \"supremacy,\" representing the ultimate and purest form of greatness, which belongs solely to Allah (ﷻ). For humans, this term carries inherently negative connotations, as it implies arrogance and an inflated sense of self-importance, claiming a greatness that is not theirs. الْكِبْرِيَاءُ, meaning \"the grandeur\" or \"the greatness,\" is an exclusive attribute of Allah (ﷻ), emphasizing that true and absolute greatness belongs only to Him, reminding creation of their need for humility and submission.",
  "3136": "كِتابٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb كَتَبَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" كِتابٌ refers to a \"book,\" \"scripture,\" or \"record,\" representing what is written, established, and decreed. The root reflects not only the act of writing but also firm determination and authoritative decree. In the context of كِتَابُ اللَّهِ, it signifies Allah’s (ﷻ) divine decree and guidance, reflecting laws, knowledge, and commands preserved with purpose. This highlights the connection between writing and authority, where what is written becomes binding and enduring, serving as a record of accountability and wisdom for humanity.",
  "3137": "كِتابِيَ and related words derive from the root ك-ت-ب, with the root verb كَتَبَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he prescribed,\" or \"he decreed.\" كِتابِيَ translates as \"my book\" or \"my record,\" referring to a written document or record associated with an individual. The root encompasses broader themes of writing, prescribing, or establishing something in a determined or formal manner. In its various applications, it conveys the idea of recording or documenting, often with a sense of authority or permanence.",
  "3138": "كِذَّابٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ذ-ب, with the root verb كَذَبَ meaning \"he lied,\" \"he spoke falsely,\" or \"he gave an untrue account.\" كِذَّابٌ means \"falsehood,\" \"lying,\" or \"persistent denial,\" referring to the act or state of engaging in falsehoods. This term emphasizes intensified and repeated acts of denial or lying, making it distinct from personal characteristics like كَذَّابٌ (habitual liar). The root conveys broader themes of fabrication, opposition to truth, and the rejection of authenticity. In specific contexts, كِذَّابٌ can highlight persistent rejection of truth or repeated opposition, emphasizing the disruptive impact of untruths on trust, integrity, and moral clarity.",
  "3139": "كِسَفٌ and related words stem from the root ك-س-ف, with the root verb كَسَفَ meaning \"it darkened\" or \"it became eclipsed.\" كِسَفٌ is the plural of كِسْفَةٌ, meaning \"fragments\" or \"pieces.\" It conveys the idea of something broken apart or divided into parts, much like the sky appearing fragmented during an eclipse or a catastrophic event. The root’s emphasis on obscurity and fragmentation reflects imagery of scattered or divided portions, highlighting a sense of separation or concealment. This term vividly portrays events of cosmic or earthly disruption, reinforcing themes of division, obscuration, and the overwhelming power of such occurrences.",
  "3140": "كِسْفٌ and related words stem from the root ك-س-ف, with the root verb كَسَفَ meaning \"it darkened\" or \"it became eclipsed.\" كِسْفٌ means \"a fragment\" or \"a piece,\" describing a portion of something that has been broken, separated, or divided. The connection to the root lies in the association with obscurity, as fragmentation often diminishes clarity or light, much like an eclipse hides the sun’s brilliance. This term captures the dramatic image of singular portions or sections being isolated, reflecting the broader root theme of partial concealment or division, often tied to powerful or awe-inspiring events.",
  "3141": "كِسْوَةٌ and related words stem from the root ك-س-و, with the root verb كَسَا meaning \"he clothed\" or \"he covered.\" كِسْوَةٌ refers to \"clothing\" or \"garment,\" representing items used to cover or adorn the body. Beyond its literal meaning, كِسْوَةٌ conveys themes of protection, honor, and modesty. In classical contexts, clothing is more than a physical covering; it preserves dignity and enhances social interaction. The root reflects a broader concept of concealment and beautification, symbolizing both physical and spiritual care. Providing clothing to others is regarded as a gesture of kindness and social responsibility, aligning with values of charity and nurturing human connections.",
  "3142": "كِفَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ت, with the root verb كَفَتَ meaning \"he turned away from\" or \"he prevented from.\" كِفَاتٌ refers to \"a place that holds\" or \"a place that encompasses.\" The connection lies in the act of holding or containing, preventing something from scattering or being lost, directly aligning with the root's concept of covering or restricting. In the context of the Earth, this term emphasizes its role in holding and encompassing life, sustaining and supporting all that exists within it, ensuring everything remains intact and preserved.",
  "3143": "كِفْلٌ and related words stem from the root ك-ف-ل, with the root verb كَفَلَ meaning \"he took care of,\" \"he guaranteed,\" or \"he supported.\" كِفْلٌ signifies \"share\" or \"portion,\" reflecting the idea of taking responsibility or ensuring the fulfillment of what is due. The name ذَا الْكِفْلِ, meaning \"the one of responsibility,\" refers to Dhul-Kifl, emphasizing his role in justice, duty, and fairness. While the Qur'an does not explicitly mention Dhul-Kifl as a prophet, most Islamic scholarship considers him one based on his mention alongside prophets. Dhul-Kifl is praised for his patience and righteousness, embodying the root's themes of accountability, support, and equitable fulfillment of obligations.",
  "3144": "كِلْتَا and related words stem from the root ك-ل-و, which conveys meanings of completeness and totality. كِلْتَا means \"both\" or \"each of the two,\" specifically referring to two feminine entities. The connection lies in encompassing two items as a unified whole, directly reflecting the root's concept of totality. This term highlights completeness and definiteness, emphasizing the inclusion of both feminine elements together in their entirety, often used to signify their equality and unity as a pair.",
  "3145": "كِيدُوا and related words also derive from the root ك-ي-د, with the root verb كَادَ meaning \"he plotted\" or \"he schemed.\" كِيدُوا means \"plot!\" or \"scheme!\" It reflects the deliberate act of devising a strategy or plan, often in adversarial or confrontational situations. The term highlights the root’s emphasis on calculated effort, highlighting the human tendency toward tactical thinking, whether for offense, defense, or manipulation. While it may imply malice or harm in human usage, when human schemes encounter Allah's (ﷻ) will, His كَيْدٌ supersedes, demonstrating His flawless and just plan that nullifies and overcomes the limitations of human efforts.",
  "3146": "The particle لِ can mean \"for,\" \"to,\" or \"belonging to,\" and it also expresses \"so that\" or \"surely.\" It is fundamental in expressing purpose, possession, or direction. In the Qur'an, لِ often connects actions to their reasons, assigns ownership, or indicates benefit or detriment directed toward someone or something. When used in the sense of \"surely,\" it emphasizes certainty, stressing the assurance of the statement that follows. It constructs meaningful relationships within the text, whether indicating purpose, possession, or certainty in action and consequence.",
  "3147": "The particle لَا is a negation meaning \"no\" or \"not\" and is essential for forming negative statements in Arabic. It is used to negate verbs, nouns, or entire sentences, prohibiting actions or denying the validity of claims. In the Qur'an, لَا plays a vital role in guiding readers toward truth by rejecting false beliefs, invalidating incorrect practices, or issuing prohibitions. Its usage is precise and impactful, emphasizing what is forbidden or untrue, thereby steering individuals away from error and reinforcing Allah’s (ﷻ) commands and guidance.",
  "3148": "لَائِمٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured.\" The root encompasses concepts of blame, criticism, and reproach. لَائِمٌ means \"one who blames\" or \"a blamer,\" directly personifying the act of reproaching others. This reflects the root's focus on assigning fault and holding others accountable for their actions. In a broader sense, it highlights societal tendencies to judge or criticize and serves as a reminder of the potential harm of undue blame, emphasizing the need for fairness and constructive criticism.",
  "3149": "لَابِثِينَ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-ث, with the root verb لَبِثَ meaning \"he remained,\" \"he delayed,\" or \"he lingered.\" لَابِثِينَ means \"remaining\" or \"abiding,\" emphasizing continuity in a place or state. The connection lies in the act of staying, reflecting persistence or endurance over a period of time. This term highlights steadfastness and the idea of remaining in a condition or location, embodying the root’s focus on duration and perseverance, whether physical or metaphorical.",
  "3150": "The particle لَاتَ is a specialized negative particle meaning \"no longer\" or \"not anymore,\" primarily used to negate time-related words. It conveys the absence or impossibility of something at a specific time, often emphasizing that the opportunity or moment has passed. لَاتَ is closely tied to expressions of finality and is most commonly found in classical Arabic, particularly in poetry and rhetorical speech. The particle reflects a nuanced form of negation, distinct from لَا, by focusing on temporal contexts and implying a sense of irrevocable loss or futility.",
  "3151": "لَازِبٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ز-ب, with the root verb لَزِبَ meaning \"it adhered,\" \"it clung,\" or \"it stuck firmly.\" لَازِبٌ means \"adhering\" or \"cohesive,\" referring to substances with a tightly bound or adhesive nature, such as clay or mud. The term highlights qualities of firmness, attachment, and structural integrity, emphasizing materials that cling or hold together strongly. In the Qur'an, it describes the cohesive and pliable nature of clay, symbolizing the foundational material of human creation. This reflects the root's focus on adhesion, steadfastness, and the ability to bind elements into a unified whole.",
  "3152": "لَاعِبِينَ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ب, with the root verb لَعِبَ meaning \"he played,\" \"he jested,\" or \"he engaged in frivolous activity.\" لَاعِبِينَ refers to \"those who play,\" \"jesters,\" or \"those who joke around,\" describing involvement in playful or lighthearted pursuits. The root emphasizes actions lacking seriousness, often associated with amusement, leisure, or triviality. This term highlights a contrast between purposeful action and frivolous behavior, with a deeper connotation of neglecting seriousness in favor of entertainment or jest.",
  "3153": "لاَعِنُونَ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ن, with the root verb لَعَنَ meaning \"he cursed,\" \"he invoked malediction upon,\" or \"he expelled from mercy.\" لاَعِنُونَ refers to \"those who curse\" or \"cursers,\" describing those who actively invoke curses or wish harm upon others. The root conveys the idea of exclusion from divine mercy or favor, often with an emphasis on invoking condemnation or punishment. This act reflects a severe judgment or rejection, symbolizing the removal from blessing and the consequences of wrongdoing.",
  "3154": "لاغِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-غ-و, with the root verb لَغَا meaning \"he spoke vainly,\" \"he engaged in idle talk,\" or \"he uttered purposeless speech.\" لاغِيَةٌ means \"vain utterance\" or \"nonsense,\" referring to fleeting, insignificant, or dismissible instances of meaningless speech. The connection lies in the concept of trivial or purposeless utterances, reflecting the root's emphasis on speech lacking value or benefit. This term highlights the moral and spiritual ideal of avoiding useless talk and focusing on meaningful, truthful communication.",
  "3155": "لَاقِيًا and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" لَاقِيًا means \"will meet,\" \"will encounter,\" or \"will face.\" The root conveys themes of direct interaction, confrontation, or discovery, emphasizing the act of coming into contact with someone or something, whether physically, emotionally, or metaphorically. لَاقِيًا highlights the state or action of engaging with another entity or event, reflecting the root’s focus on impactful connections and encounters. It often highlights purposeful or significant meetings, such as those with profound outcomes or consequences.",
  "3156": "لَاهِيَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ه-و, with the root verb لَهَا meaning \"he was diverted,\" \"he was distracted,\" or \"he engaged in idle amusement.\" لَاهِيَةٌ means \"distracted,\" \"heedless,\" or \"engaged in amusement.\" It describes someone who is absorbed in distractions or diversions, neglecting important matters. The connection to the root lies in embodying the state of being diverted or amused to the point of negligence. This highlights the root's emphasis on the perils of distraction and the importance of remaining attentive to significant responsibilities, serving as a caution against allowing amusements to lead one astray.",
  "3157": "لَبَسْنَا and related words stem from the root ل-ب-س, with the root verb لَبِسَ meaning \"he wore,\" \"he confused,\" or \"he mixed.\" لَبَسْنَا means \"we wore,\" \"we confused,\" \"we obscured,\" or \"we mixed,\" emphasizing the act of metaphorical covering that veils or blends clarity. The connection to the root lies in the overlapping concepts of covering and mixing—just as clothing physically covers the body, confusion and mixing obscure or blend distinct elements, leading to ambiguity. This term highlights the dual nature of the root, encompassing the protective role of covering for safety and the concealing or blending aspects that obscure clarity, distort perception, or create uncertainty.",
  "3158": "لَبَنٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-ن, which encompasses meanings related to \"milk\" and \"bricks.\" لَبَنٌ specifically refers to \"milk,\" highlighting its role as a primary source of nourishment. The connection lies in the foundational nature of both milk and bricks: just as bricks (لَبِنٌ) are fundamental building blocks in construction, providing structure and strength, milk serves as an essential nutrient, building and fortifying the body's bones and overall health. This parallel highlights the concept of foundational sustenance and the importance of basic elements in creating strength and stability, whether in physical structures or in bodily development.",
  "3159": "لَبُوسٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-س, with the root verb لَبِسَ meaning \"he wore\" or \"he dressed.\" لَبُوسٌ specifically refers to \"armor\" or protective \"garments,\" emphasizing attire that shields the body from harm. The connection lies in the protective nature of clothing, especially in contexts of conflict, where armor serves as a safeguard. This term embodies the idea of preparation and self-defense, aligning with the root’s theme of wearing coverings for security and survival.",
  "3160": "لَبِثَ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-ث, with the root verb meaning \"he remained,\" \"he delayed,\" or \"he lingered.\" The root conveys the idea of staying in a place or condition, either temporarily or for a prolonged period. It reflects themes of persistence, patience, or waiting, often implying an intentional pause or hesitation. The connection lies in the action of remaining or lingering, highlighting the root’s emphasis on duration, whether physical or metaphorical, in time or space. This term captures the balance between endurance and delay, illustrating the act of staying in one state while awaiting change or resolution.",
  "3161": "لَبْسٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-س, with the root verb لَبِسَ meaning \"he wore\" or \"he confused.\" لَبْسٌ refers to \"confusion\" or \"obscurity,\" drawing from the metaphorical act of covering or veiling clarity. The connection highlights how just as clothing hides the body, ambiguity obscures understanding, leading to uncertainty or misinterpretation. This term captures the impact of masking on perception and the challenges of navigating through obscurity.",
  "3162": "لَجُّوا and related words stem from the root ل-ج-ج, with the root verb لَجَّ meaning \"he persisted\" or \"he was obstinate.\" لَجُّوا means \"they persist,\" highlighting the relentless continuation of an action or attitude, often despite opposition or reason. The root conveys ideas of continuous, repetitive action or insistence, often marked by resistance or defiance. The connection to the root lies in the concept of repeated and forceful determination, reflecting a refusal to yield or change course. This term emphasizes the intensity of persistence and its potential to become negative when driven by obstinacy or defiance.",
  "3163": "لَحْمٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ح-م, with the root verb لَحِمَ meaning \"to join firmly,\" \"to bind together,\" or \"to weld,\" referring to the physical act of uniting parts. لَحْمٌ specifically denotes \"flesh\" or \"meat,\" emphasizing its role as the soft tissue that binds bones, muscles, and skin into a cohesive structure. This connection to the root highlights how flesh serves as the physical medium that holds the body together, perfectly reflecting the root's inherent sense of fastening and binding in a tangible, structural manner.",
  "3164": "لَحْنٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ح-ن, with the root verb لَحَنَ meaning \"he deviated in speech\" or \"he expressed indirectly.\" لَحْنٌ can mean \"tone,\" \"melody,\" or \"implied meaning.\" The connection lies in the idea that speech, when adorned with tone or melody, diverges from plain, direct expression. This adornment introduces deviation, whether to emphasize, conceal, or beautify the message. Tone and melody become tools for the speaker to subtly express meanings or emotions, layering speech with nuance and implication. This term reflects the depth of communication, where deviation through modulation, deliberate or artistic, reveals or obscures what is truly meant.",
  "3165": "The preposition لَدُنْ translates to \"from,\" \"with,\" \"presence,\" or \"directly,\" depending on the context. It indicates closeness and direct proximity, emphasizing either nearness or immediacy. لَدُنْ is used in both spatial and metaphorical contexts, often denoting something originating directly from a source or in someone's immediate presence. For instance, in مِنْ لَدُنْكَ, it can mean \"from you,\" \"from your presence,\" or \"directly from you,\" depending on the emphasis. This preposition highlights the immediacy and directness of an action while also conveying intimate association and exclusive connection to the source.",
  "3166": "لَذَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ذ-ذ, with the root verb لَذَّ meaning \"it was pleasant,\" \"delightful,\" or \"enjoyable.\" لَذَّةٌ means \"pleasure,\" \"delight,\" or \"enjoyment,\" representing the sensation of sweetness or joy derived from something pleasing. The connection to the root highlights the experience of pleasure as an intrinsic response to what is delightful, highlighting the innate human inclination toward seeking joy and satisfaction.",
  "3167": "لَطِيفٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ط-ف, with the root verb لَطُفَ meaning \"he was subtle,\" \"delicate,\" \"kind,\" or \"gracious.\" لَطِيفٌ signifies qualities such as \"kind,\" \"gentle,\" \"subtle,\" or \"gracious,\" reflecting tenderness, perceptiveness, and precision. ٱللَّطِيفُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Most Gentle and Subtle,\" emphasizing His awareness, mercy, and precise care in managing creation. The root conveys subtlety in action, graciousness in interaction, and kindness in dealings, highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) unmatched delicacy, insight, and benevolence in orchestrating creation beyond human comprehension.",
  "3168": "لَظَى and related words stem from the root ل-ظ-ى, with the root verb لَظِيَ meaning \"it burned fiercely\" or \"it blazed intensely.\" The root conveys the idea of a relentless, unquenchable fire. لَظَى is identified by Islamic scholars as one of the names for Hell, emphasizing its fiercely blazing and all-consuming nature. The term vividly depicts unrelenting heat and torment, symbolizing a punishment that leaves no escape.",
  "3169": "لَعَنَ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ن, meaning \"he cursed,\" \"he invoked malediction upon,\" or \"he expelled from mercy.\" لَعَنَ involves a deliberate invocation of a curse or a call for someone to be excluded from divine mercy and blessings. The root emphasizes severe condemnation or punishment, often implying divine disapproval or rejection. The connection lies in the profound implications of being deprived of mercy, reflecting the weight of invoking such an act and its spiritual consequences, as it separates the cursed from goodness and favor.",
  "3170": "لَعِبٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ب, with the root verb لَعِبَ meaning \"he played,\" \"he jested,\" or \"he amused himself.\" لَعِبٌ signifies \"play,\" \"sport,\" or \"amusement,\" referring to activities undertaken primarily for enjoyment or leisure. The root emphasizes actions driven by entertainment or diversion, often associated with a lack of gravity or purpose. This term reflects the human tendency toward playful or frivolous behaviors and is frequently contrasted with seriousness, truth, or meaningful pursuits, particularly in contexts where playfulness leads to distraction from important matters.",
  "3171": "لَعْنٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ن, with the root verb لَعَنَ meaning \"he cursed,\" \"he expelled from mercy,\" or \"he invoked malediction upon.\" لَعْنٌ means \"curse,\" \"malediction,\" or \"banishment from mercy.\" The connection lies in the concept of a curse as an invocation for harm or exclusion from favor, reflecting the root's emphasis on deprivation and condemnation. This term highlights the severity of being under a curse, emphasizing the spiritual and social ramifications of such a state, and serves as a warning against actions that lead to such consequences.",
  "3172": "لَعْنَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ع-ن, with the root verb لَعَنَ meaning \"he cursed,\" \"he expelled from mercy,\" or \"he invoked malediction upon.\" لَعْنَةٌ signifies \"a curse,\" \"a malediction,\" or \"banishment from mercy,\" referring to a formal or pronounced declaration of condemnation. The root highlights the exclusion from blessings or favor, reflecting the severity of invoking a curse. لَعْنَةٌ carries a sense of permanence or formality, symbolizing deep condemnation and rejection, often as a result of moral or spiritual transgressions.",
  "3173": "لَغْوٌ and related words stem from the root ل-غ-و, with the root verb لَغَا meaning \"he spoke vainly,\" \"he engaged in idle talk,\" or \"he uttered purposeless speech.\" لَغْوٌ means \"vain talk,\" \"idle speech,\" or \"frivolous conversation.\" The connection lies in the broader concept of speech that lacks substance or purpose, reflecting the root's emphasis on unproductive or meaningless utterances. This term highlights the moral responsibility to guard one’s tongue against trivial or harmful talk and to prioritize words that are beneficial and constructive.",
  "3174": "لَفِيفٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ف-ف, with the root verb لَفَّ meaning \"he wrapped,\" \"he wound,\" or \"he folded.\" لَفِيفٌ means \"a collection,\" \"a multitude,\" or \"a mixed gathering,\" referring to a group assembled from various places or elements brought together. The connection lies in the concept of wrapping or gathering together, reflecting the root's emphasis on enveloping and assembling. This term highlights the bringing together of diverse elements into a unified whole, emphasizing unity within diversity or the assembling of people for a common purpose.",
  "3175": "لَقُوا and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he received.\" لَقُوا means \"they met,\" \"they encountered,\" or \"they received.\" The connection lies in the act of coming face to face with someone or something or receiving what is presented, reflecting the root's emphasis on meeting, confronting, or accepting. It highlights moments of interaction or reception, whether friendly, adversarial, or transactional.",
  "3176": "لَقَّىٰ stems from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" لَقَّىٰ introduces a causative aspect, meaning \"he caused to meet,\" \"he delivered,\" or \"he granted.\" This form intensifies the root meaning by emphasizing the act of facilitating encounters or ensuring the receipt of something. In the Qur'an, it often refers to the deliberate act of imparting knowledge, guidance, or information, highlighting the intentionality and significance of the action.",
  "3177": "The particle لَمْ is a negation used with the \"jussive\" form of the verb to indicate the simple past tense negative, meaning \"did not.\" The jussive form refers to a specific way the verb is conjugated, often used to express commands, requests, or conditions. When combined with لَمْ, it negates actions in the past, forming negative statements about completed events. In the Qur'an, لَمْ negates events or actions that have not occurred, providing clarity and emphasizing the truthfulness of the narrative.",
  "3178": "لَمَسُوا and related words stem from the root ل-م-س, with the root verb لَمَسَ meaning \"he touched,\" and لَمَسُوا meaning \"they touched\" or \"they sought out.\" It conveys physical contact, often with intent to sense or feel, and extends metaphorically to seeking or striving to connect with something. The root encompasses perception, investigation, and exploration, where touch serves as a means to engage with or understand. This term emphasizes both literal interaction with the physical world and the broader act of seeking, whether physical or intellectual.",
  "3179": "لَمَمٌ and related words stem from the root ل-م-م, with the root verb لَمَّ meaning \"he gathered,\" \"he collected,\" or \"he brought together.\" لَمَمٌ refers to \"minor sins,\" \"small faults,\" or \"occasional lapses,\" encompassing both unintentional missteps and infrequent intentional transgressions. The connection lies in minor sins being like small, scattered acts that momentarily gather around a person without becoming consistent or persistent. Just as لَمَّ involves bringing together dispersed elements, لَمَمٌ reflects the occasional convergence of minor faults, distinct from major, deliberate sins. This term highlights Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy in forgiving such lapses when one repents and avoids persisting in them.",
  "3180": "لَمًّا and related words stem from the root ل-م-م, with the root verb لَمَّ meaning \"he gathered,\" \"he collected,\" or \"he brought together.\" لَمًّا means \"completely\" or \"entirely,\" emphasizing the totality or completeness of an action. The connection lies in the root’s focus on gathering or amassing, as the act of collecting everything into one place naturally conveys the idea of leaving nothing behind. This reflects how لَمًّا evolves from its root meaning to describe actions performed in a thorough, all-encompassing manner, often implying intensity or greed when used in contexts of consumption or acquisition.",
  "3181": "لَمْحٌ and related words stem from the root ل-م-ح, with the root verb لَمَحَ meaning \"he glanced,\" \"he saw briefly,\" or \"he noticed.\" لَمْحٌ refers to \"a glance,\" \"a moment,\" or \"a twinkling,\" capturing the idea of a brief or instantaneous look. The connection lies in the fleeting nature of perception or moments, reflecting the root's emphasis on quick observation or transitory experiences. This term underscores the rapid passage of time or sudden occurrences, often illustrating the immediacy of significant actions or changes.",
  "3182": "لَهَبٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ه-ب, with the root verb لَهِبَ meaning \"he burned with thirst\" or \"he was intensely thirsty,\" and لَهَّبَ meaning \"he made the fire blaze fiercely.\" لَهَبٌ means \"flaming fire\" or \"blazing flame,\" referring to a bright, smoke-free fire, emphasizing its intensity. The connection lies in the vivid imagery of a pure, fierce flame that aligns with the root's focus on burning. From the same root comes the nickname أَبُو لَهَبٍ, referring to the disbeliever Lahab, whose actual name was ‘Abd al-‘Uzza ibn ‘Abdul Muttalib. He was nicknamed \"Father of Flame\" for his fiery complexion, reflecting both his temperament and fate.",
  "3183": "لَهْوٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ه-و, with the root verb لَهَا meaning \"he was diverted,\" \"he was distracted,\" or \"he engaged in idle amusement.\" لَهْوٌ means \"amusement,\" \"diversion,\" or \"idle pastime,\" referring to distractions rooted in vain or frivolous activities that preoccupy a person and divert them from important matters. It reflects pursuits that provide temporary satisfaction but often lead to neglect of serious responsibilities or spiritual obligations. The connection lies in the root’s emphasis on diversion, highlighting the transient and hollow nature of such amusements. This term serves as a reminder to prioritize meaningful and purposeful endeavors over fleeting distractions.",
  "3184": "لَواقِحُ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ح, with the root verb لَقَحَ meaning \"he impregnated,\" \"he fertilized,\" or \"he inseminated.\" لَواقِحُ means \"fertilizing\" or \"pollinating.\" The connection lies in the action of causing reproduction or growth, reflecting the root's emphasis on fertilization and the initiation of new life. This term highlights the role of winds or agents that carry pollen, facilitating the growth and fruition of plants, emphasizing the intricate natural processes ordained by Allah (ﷻ) that sustain life and provide sustenance.",
  "3185": "لَوَّاحَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-ح, with the root verb لَاحَ meaning \"it scorched,\" \"it burnt,\" or \"it altered the color of skin.\" The root conveys concepts of burning, scorching, or altering appearance. لَوَّاحَةٌ means \"scorching\" or \"burning to blacken,\" emphasizing the intensity of the action. The connection lies in the intensification of the root meaning, focusing on the transformative effect of burning, particularly the blackening or discoloration caused by heat.",
  "3186": "لَوَّامَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured.\" لَوَّامَةٌ is an intensive form meaning \"greatly blaming,\" \"much-reproaching,\" or \"self-reproaching,\" emphasizing frequent or intense blame. In the Qur'an, it refers to the self-reproaching soul, which signifies the inner conscience that frequently holds one accountable for shortcomings and wrongdoings. This reflects the root’s focus on blame, turning inward to emphasize self-criticism as a means of moral and spiritual growth. It highlights the role of the self-reproaching soul in guiding one to repentance and righteousness, while maintaining hope in Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy.",
  "3187": "لَوَّوْا and related words stem from the root ل-و-ي, with the root verb لَوَىٰ meaning \"he twisted,\" \"he bent,\" \"he turned aside,\" \"he made something difficult,\" or \"he concealed.\" The root encompasses concepts of twisting, turning, or diverting. لَوَّوْا means \"they turned aside\" or \"they distorted,\" intensifying the root meaning to highlight deliberate actions of twisting, turning away, or distorting. This can refer literally to physical gestures, such as turning or twisting one's head, or metaphorically to acts of rejecting or distorting the truth. It reflects themes of deliberate deviation, arrogance, and resistance to what is straightforward or truthful, emphasizing an intentional departure from clarity or acceptance.",
  "3188": "لَوْحٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-ح, with the root verb لَاحَ meaning \"it became apparent,\" \"it appeared,\" or \"it gleamed.\" The root conveys concepts of visibility, appearance, or making something known. لَوْحٌ means \"tablet,\" \"board,\" or \"plank,\" emphasizing flat surfaces that make things visible or apparent. Planks are essential for building strong physical foundations and providing structural support, while tablets, as carriers of Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, establish strong moral foundations and spiritual support. This dual role highlights the connection between sustaining physical structures and guiding humanity toward spiritual stability and righteousness.",
  "3189": "لَوْمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured.\" لَوْمَةٌ means \"blame,\" \"reproach,\" or \"censure,\" and it represents the verbal act of expressing blame or disapproval. The connection is direct, highlighting the articulation of criticism or fault-finding, often tied to moral or social accountability. The root reflects the act of addressing perceived wrongdoing or error, emphasizing the clear and explicit expression of blame or disapproval.",
  "3190": "لَوْنٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-ن, which encompasses concepts of color, hue, or variation. لَوْنٌ means \"color,\" \"hue,\" or \"shade,\" emphasizing the diversity and beauty of appearances. The root highlights the variety found in creation through differing colors and forms, symbolizing richness and diversity. Metaphorically, it extends to denote different kinds or types, reflecting variation in forms, categories, or expressions, and capturing the intricate diversity inherent in creation.",
  "3191": "لَيٌّ and related words stem from the root ل-و-ي, with the root verb لَوَىٰ meaning \"he twisted,\" \"he bent,\" \"he turned aside,\" \"he made something difficult,\" or \"he concealed.\" لَيٌّ means \"twisting,\" \"delay,\" or \"evasion,\" reflecting both literal and figurative actions. The connection is direct, as twisting or bending implies a deviation from a straight path or straightforward action. This extends metaphorically to delaying, evading, or distorting, whether in speech, behavior, or intention. The term captures actions that obscure clarity, manipulate meaning, or create barriers, emphasizing themes of resistance, deception, or intentional complexity.",
  "3192": "لَيِّنٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ي-ن, with the root verb لَانَ meaning \"he was soft,\" \"he was gentle,\" or \"he was yielding.\" This root involves concepts of softness, gentleness, and flexibility. لَيِّنٌ means \"soft,\" \"gentle,\" or \"tender.\" The connection lies in embodying the qualities of softness and gentleness. It reflects the root's emphasis on kindness, adaptability, and the ability to be gentle in demeanor or approach. This term highlights the virtues of compassion and flexibility in interactions, encouraging a demeanor that is approachable and considerate.",
  "3193": "The particle لَيْتَ expresses deep wish or longing, often translated as \"if only\" or \"would that,\" capturing the emotion of yearning for the unattainable, often marked by profound regret. In the Qur'an, لَيْتَ introduces statements of deep remorse and reflection, emphasizing the consequences of neglecting one’s purpose and the realization of lost opportunities. It also serves as a rhetorical device to evoke introspection, urging readers to recognize the gravity of their actions and make amends before it is too late. This emotional and reflective usage highlights the weight of accountability and the sorrow of realizing too late what was forsaken.",
  "3194": "لَيْلٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ي-ل, meaning \"night\" or \"the time of darkness between sunset and sunrise.\" لَيْلٌ specifically refers to the collective concept of night as a whole. The term encompasses notions of veiling and obscurity, reflecting the natural characteristics of the night as a time when darkness prevails and visibility diminishes. It also signifies tranquility and rest, as night is traditionally associated with a cessation of activity and a time for renewal.",
  "3195": "لَيْلَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ي-ل, meaning \"a single night\" or \"a specific period of darkness extending between sunset and dawn.\" لَيْلَةٌ emphasizes the distinct, singular aspect of night within the broader concept of darkness. The term highlights themes of concealment and stillness, aligning with the night’s nature as a time of quietude and withdrawal. It also represents a phase of separation from the busyness of the day, offering a symbolic retreat into calm and introspection.",
  "3196": "لُؤْلُؤٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ؤ-ل-ؤ, referring specifically to \"pearls.\" The term represents something precious, rare, and refined, often associated with purity and brilliance. Pearls, formed within the protective layers of a shell, symbolize hidden beauty that emerges through patience and natural processes. Concealed and protected, they reach perfection over time. This term highlights qualities of rarity, excellence, and the extraordinary nature of things that require time and effort to uncover.",
  "3197": "لُبَدٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-د, with the root verb لَبَدَ meaning \"it clung,\" \"it adhered closely,\" or \"it pressed together.\" لُبَدٌ refers to \"heaps,\" \"piles,\" or \"masses gathered together.\" The connection lies in the imagery of things sticking or clustering together, forming an accumulation or density. This term emphasizes abundance and the idea of multitude, whether referring to physical objects, people, or metaphorical concepts like overwhelming quantities or conditions tightly packed and layered.",
  "3198": "لُجَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ج-ج, with the root verb لَجَّ meaning \"he persisted\" or \"he was obstinate.\" لُجَّةٌ refers to \"a vast expanse of water\" or \"the depths of the sea,\" highlighting the imagery of an immense and seemingly endless body of water. The root conveys notions of repetition, intensity, and insistence, which are metaphorically applied to the movement and turbulence of water. The connection to the root lies in the ceaseless and overwhelming nature of water's motion, symbolizing vastness, profundity, and the unknown depths.",
  "3199": "لُجِّيٌّ and related words stem from the root ل-ج-ج, with the root verb لَجَّ meaning \"he persisted\" or \"he was obstinate.\" لُجِّيٌّ specifically means \"vast and deep,\" used to describe the profound, unfathomable nature of deep waters or metaphorical depths.The root conveys themes of repetition and intensity, which are applied metaphorically to describe the vastness or depth of water.  The connection lies in the imagery of overwhelming immensity and ceaseless depth, reflecting the root’s themes of persistence and intensity in both physical and abstract senses.",
  "3200": "لُدٌّ stems from the root ل-د-د, with the verb لَدَّ meaning \"he disputed\" or \"he was stubborn.\" لُدٌّ refers to argumentative individuals, characterized by persistent opposition and resistance in disputes. The root emphasizes intense disputation and verbal contention, highlighting the challenge of reasoning with those who are obstinate and unwilling to yield.",
  "3201": "لُغُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ل-غ-ب, with the root verb لَغِبَ meaning \"he became tired,\" \"he was fatigued,\" or \"he was exhausted.\" لُغُوبٌ signifies \"exhaustion,\" \"weariness,\" or \"tiredness,\" representing a profound state of physical or mental fatigue. The root conveys the idea of depletion of strength, exhaustion from exertion, or a state of being overwhelmed by effort. It also encompasses extreme incapacity or weariness beyond ordinary fatigue, being the utmost degree of exhaustion. The term reflects the human condition of weariness, rooted in limitation and toil, and contrasts with Allah's (ﷻ) perfection, as described in the Qur'an, where He is entirely free from fatigue or weariness.",
  "3202": "لُقْمَانُ has no definitive known root in Arabic, though it is widely recognized for its association with wisdom. In the Qur'an, Luqman is portrayed as a wise figure known for imparting profound advice, particularly in his guidance to his son. Across Nubia and Ethiopia, Luqman is similarly regarded as a symbol of great wisdom, although the exact meaning of the name in these regions is not well-defined. However, the universal association with wisdom transcends linguistic origins, making Luqman a lasting symbol of knowledge and moral integrity in both Arabic and African cultures.",
  "3203": "لُمَزَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-م-ز, with the root verb لَمَزَ meaning \"he criticized,\" \"he found fault with,\" or \"he defamed.\" لُمَزَةٌ refers to someone who habitually engages in defamation, reproach, or fault-finding, whether openly or behind someone's back. This term encompasses behaviors such as backbiting, slandering, and mocking, highlighting the act of speaking ill of others, which leads to social discord and moral degradation. The emphasis is on the persistent nature of such behavior, serving as a stern warning against actions that harm the reputation and dignity of others.",
  "3204": "لُمْتُنَّ and related words stem from the root ل-و-م, with the root verb لَامَ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he reproached,\" or \"he censured.\" لُمْتُنَّ means \"you blamed,\" referring to the act of addressing others with blame or censure. The root conveys notions of reproach, criticism, or fault-finding, often with the intent of correcting or pointing out a perceived wrongdoing. This form highlights the interpersonal nature of blame, where the subject (a group) actively directs censure toward others. The term reflects the root’s broader emphasis on accountability and moral judgment, capturing the tension and relational dynamics inherent in assigning blame within human interactions.",
  "3205": "لُوطُ stems from the root ل-و-ط, with the root verb لاطَ meaning \"he adhered\" or \"clung closely.\" This is the name of Prophet Lot (ﷺ), who remained steadfast in adhering to Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance despite the widespread immorality around him. His unwavering commitment to truth and righteousness reflects the root’s concept of clinging firmly to something, symbolizing his resolute faith and integrity. Prophet Lot (ﷺ) exemplifies the importance of holding fast to one’s beliefs and maintaining righteousness in the face of adversity and widespread transgressions and corruption.",
  "3206": "لِبَاسٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-س, with the root verb لَبِسَ meaning \"he wore\" or \"he dressed.\" لِبَاسٌ refers to \"clothing,\" \"garment,\" or \"covering,\" emphasizing something that serves to protect, conceal, or adorn. The connection to the root lies in the act of wearing, which provides physical security and symbolic significance. In broader contexts, the term extends to anything that acts as a covering, such as the night enveloping the world in darkness, providing tranquility and protection like a garment. This term highlights the multifaceted role of coverings in providing shelter, modesty, comfort, and identity, whether in physical or metaphorical applications.",
  "3207": "لِبَدٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ب-د, with the root verb لَبَدَ meaning \"he clung,\" \"he adhered,\" or \"he crowded together.\" لِبَدٌ means \"compact mass,\" \"layers,\" or \"heaps piled up,\" highlighting things being closely packed or stuck together. The root highlights the idea of density, whether physical or metaphorical, symbolizing overwhelming numbers, unity in compression, or an intensified state of crowding or clustering. This term reflects a strong sense of cohesion or overwhelming accumulation.",
  "3208": "لِحْيَةٌ stems from the root ل-ح-ي, which primarily relates to the jawbone or cheek, the areas where facial hair naturally grows. The singular noun لَحْيٌ refers to the jawbone itself, forming the foundational structure of the face. لِحْيَةٌ specifically denotes the beard, emphasizing the connection between the jaw and the growth of hair. The root conveys not only the physical structure but also the natural emergence of facial hair, highlighting the relationship between the face's anatomy and the beard.",
  "3209": "لِزَامٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ز-م, with the root verb لَزِمَ meaning \"he adhered,\" \"he clinged,\" or \"he remained steadfast.\" لِزَامٌ means \"binding,\" reflecting something that cannot be escaped or avoided. The connection lies in the concept of something firmly adhered to or imposed, emphasizing the root's focus on persistence and unyielding obligation. This term highlights the inescapable nature of certain duties or consequences, highlighting their fixed and binding nature.",
  "3210": "لِسَانٌ and related words stem from the root ل-س-ن, meaning \"tongue,\" referring both to the physical organ and, metaphorically, to language or speech. The root conveys themes of articulation, eloquence, and clarity in communication, emphasizing the power of the tongue as the primary tool for expressing thoughts, emotions, and ideas. لِسَانٌ highlights the importance of clear and effective speech, reflecting the root's focus on the ability to convey meaning with precision and impact. This term highlights the centrality of language in human interaction and the profound role of speech in shaping understanding and relationships.",
  "3211": "لِقَاءٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ق-ي, with the root verb لَقِيَ meaning \"he met,\" \"he encountered,\" or \"he found.\" لِقَاءٌ means \"meeting\" or \"encounter.\" It represents the event or occasion of meeting, embodying the root's central concept of encounter. The term emphasizes the significance of gatherings or confrontations, whether physical, emotional, or spiritual. In a broader sense, it can refer to significant meetings, such as meeting with destiny or with Allah (ﷻ), deepening the root's emphasis on the profound impact of encounters in shaping experiences and outcomes.",
  "3212": "لِنْتَ and related words stem from the root ل-ي-ن, with the root verb لَانَ meaning \"he was soft,\" \"he was gentle,\" or \"he was yielding.\" لِنْتَ translates to \"you were soft\" or \"you were gentle,\" indicating a state of pliability or tenderness. This term emphasizes the root's focus on softness and flexibility, reflecting a gentle or yielding nature. لِنْتَ conveys an instance of gentleness, highlighting a moment of softness or yielding.",
  "3213": "لِوَاذٌ and related words stem from the root ل-و-ذ, with the root verb لَاذَ meaning \"he sought refuge,\" \"he clung,\" or \"he sheltered himself.\" This root conveys concepts of seeking protection, clinging to something, or hiding. لِوَاذٌ means \"seeking refuge,\" \"concealment,\" or \"hiding,\" emphasizing the act of clinging to something for safety or shelter. The connection lies in the effort to shield oneself, reflecting the root's emphasis on refuge, protection, and concealment. It highlights human tendencies to seek safety or avoid exposure in times of uncertainty. In a moral context, it describes those using pretexts or excuses to avoid responsibilities, metaphorically hiding behind others or circumstances.",
  "3214": "لِينَةٌ and related words stem from the root ل-ي-ن, with the root verb لَانَ meaning \"he was soft,\" \"he was gentle,\" or \"he was yielding.\" لِينَةٌ refers to a palm tree, particularly one that is young, soft, or tender. The connection lies in the root's emphasis on softness and pliability, reflecting the tree's tender characteristics, especially in its early stages. This word highlights the physical aspects of the palm and metaphorically evokes gentleness, linking growth with softness. لِينَةٌ conveys an image of pliability and youthfulness, distinguishing it from the more mature and hardened نَخْلٌ.",
  "3215": "The particle ما is highly versatile, with meanings such as \"what\" or \"not,\" and it serves various functions depending on the context. As an interrogative pronoun, it is used to ask questions and translates to \"what.\" As a relative pronoun, it connects clauses, functioning like \"that which\" or \"what.\" As a negation particle, it negates verbs or sentences, similar to \"not.\" Additionally, as an exclamatory particle, it expresses surprise or emphasis, often translating to \"what\" or \"how.\" Its exact meaning and usage are determined by the surrounding context.",
  "3216": "مَاءٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ه, with the root verb مَاهَ meaning \"it flowed\" or \"it was fluid.\" مَاءٌ means \"water,\" directly tied to the root's concept of fluidity and movement. The word reflects the essential role of water as a substance that flows and sustains life. This connection highlights its indispensability in creation, aligning with its broader implications as a fundamental and vital element provided by Allah (ﷻ) for the continuity of life.",
  "3217": "مَائِدَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ي-د, with the root verb مَادَ meaning \"it became in a state of motion\" or \"it became agitated,\" as well as \"he bestowed benefits or favors.\" مَائِدَةٌ refers to a \"table spread of food,\" particularly one prepared for a meal, symbolizing abundance and provision. The connection to the root meanings reflects how the earth undergoes motion and commotion—through growth, cultivation, and harvest—to produce its blessings. This mirrors Allah’s (ﷻ) role as the bestower of benefits and favors, orchestrating these processes and providing sustenance with wisdom and mercy, showing that all provision ultimately stems from His perfect generosity.",
  "3218": "مَاتَ and related words stem from the root م-و-ت, with the root verb مَاتَ meaning \"he died,\" referring to the cessation of life. This term highlights the natural conclusion of vitality and movement, transitioning to stillness and lifelessness. It extends metaphorically to barren lands, inactivity, or the absence of growth, symbolizing the shift from existence to a state of dormancy or nonexistence. The word serves as a reminder of the fragility of life and the inevitability of death, urging reflection on life’s impermanence.",
  "3219": "مارُوتُ is a name referring to one of the two angels, Harut (ﷺ) and Marut (ﷺ). The name Marut does not have a clear Arabic root and is considered of foreign origin. Despite this, the story of Harut (ﷺ) and Marut (ﷺ) conveys a powerful lesson about the misuse of knowledge and the importance of obedience to Allah (ﷻ). Sent as a trial to test people's faith, this story emphasizes responsibility, temptation, and the consequences of straying from Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance, highlighting the need for humility when endowed with knowledge and power.",
  "3220": "مَارِجٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ج, with the root verb مَرَجَ meaning \"he mingled,\" \"he mixed,\" or \"he became confused.\" مَارِجٌ refers to a \"smokeless flame\" or a \"pure, whirling flame.\" The connection lies in the chaotic, dynamic nature of fire, reflecting the root's idea of mixing or instability. In the Qur'an, it describes the fire from which jinn were created, emphasizing their origin in a powerful, intense, and untamed force that mirrors the unpredictable and interwoven nature of a flame.",
  "3221": "مارِدٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-د, with the root verb مَرَدَ meaning \"he was rebellious,\" \"he was obstinate,\" or \"he was stripped of goodness.\" مارِدٌ means \"rebellious\" or \"defiant.\" The connection lies in the idea of being stripped of obedience or moral restraint, indicating someone who resists authority and guidance. This term emphasizes rebellion as an active shedding of virtue and submission, reflecting a being who has cast off the constraints of righteousness. It is commonly used to describe rebellious spirits or devils, focusing on their defiance and refusal to comply with rightful authority. While مارِدٌ highlights general rebellion, it stops short of the extreme intensity conveyed by مَرِيدٌ.",
  "3222": "مَاعُونٌ and related words stem from the root ع-و-ن, with the root verb عَانَ meaning \"he helped,\" \"he assisted,\" or \"he supported.\" مَاعُونٌ refers to \"small acts of kindness,\" \"articles of daily use,\" or \"charitable assistance,\" encompassing both tangible items and simple actions that ease others’ burdens. It highlights the importance of sharing basic necessities, such as utensils or provisions, and emphasizes the broader values of support, generosity, and mutual care. This term reflects how even minor contributions can strengthen social bonds and fulfill the collective responsibility of helping those in need.",
  "3223": "مَاكِثُونَ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ث, with the root verb مَكَثَ meaning \"he remained,\" \"he lingered,\" or \"he stayed.\" مَاكِثُونَ means \"remaining,\" \"abiding,\" or \"dwelling.\" The connection is the act of staying or residing in a place, reflecting the root's concept of permanence and continuity. It emphasizes steadfastness and the importance of enduring presence.",
  "3224": "مَاكِرِينَ and related words stem from the root م-ك-ر, with the root verb مَكَرَ meaning \"he plotted,\" \"he schemed,\" or \"he deceived.\" مَاكِرِينَ means \"ones who plot\" or \"schemers.\" The connection lies in the act of cunning or deceptive planning, reflecting the root's concept of strategizing with hidden intentions. When attributed to Allah (ﷻ), it signifies His supreme and just planning to counteract the deceitful schemes of others, turning their plans against them with wisdom and justice. This highlights the ultimate futility of human deceit in the face of Allah's perfect and strategic planning.",
  "3225": "مَالٌ and related words stem from the root م-و-ل, with the root verb مَالَ meaning \"he inclined,\" \"he leaned,\" or \"he turned.\" مَالٌ means \"wealth\" or \"property,\" reflecting how material possessions can cause one's heart to incline towards them. The root also conveys themes of deviation or turning away, emphasizing the risks of being led astray by worldly desires. This highlights the tests associated with wealth and the importance of managing it responsibly in accordance with Allah’s (ﷻ) guidance. By aligning one’s inclinations with divine principles, wealth becomes a means for personal growth and societal benefit, rather than a source of distraction or deviation.",
  "3226": "مَالِكٌ and related words stem from the root م-ل-ك, with the root verb مَلَكَ meaning \"he possessed,\" \"he owned,\" or \"he ruled.\" مَالِكٌ means \"owner\" or \"possessor,\" reflecting mastery, control, and sovereignty. The root encompasses authority, governance, and the power to manage and direct. مَالِكُ is also the name of the angel who guards Hell, signifying strict control and unwavering enforcement of Allah’s (ﷻ) decrees. مَالِكُ ٱلْمُلْكِ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Master of the Kingdom,\" emphasizing His unparalleled authority over all realms of existence—seen and unseen. This term reminds us that all dominion, governance, and decision-making ultimately belong to Allah (ﷻ) alone.",
  "3227": "مَانِعَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ن-ع, with the root verb مَنَعَ meaning \"he prevented,\" \"he withheld,\" or \"he forbade.\" مَانِعَةٌ means \"preventing,\" \"hindering,\" or \"defending.\" The connection lies in the act of stopping or withholding, reflecting the root's core concept of prevention. It highlights the role of an agent actively obstructing or restricting access, whether to protect, defend, or enforce boundaries. This word conveys a sense of authority and deliberate action in restricting harm or safeguarding what is deemed valuable. In classical usage, مَانِعَةٌ can also signify a protective force, emphasizing the dual role of preventing harm while ensuring safety or order.",
  "3228": "مَاهِدُونَ and related words stem from the root م-ه-د, with the root verb مَهَدَ meaning \"he spread out\" or \"he prepared.\" مَاهِدُونَ means \"ones who prepare\" or \"ones who make smooth.\" The connection reflects the role of someone who actively sets the stage or makes conditions favorable. It highlights the significance of being proactive in creating a conducive environment for growth or action.",
  "3229": "مَآبٌ and related words stem from the root أ-و-ب, with the root verb آبَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he came back.\" مَآبٌ means \"place of return\" or \"final abode.\" The connection lies in the destination or refuge to which one ultimately returns, highlighting the root's concept of returning. It signifies the final dwelling in the Hereafter, emphasizing the importance of striving for a favorable end and the impermanence of worldly life.",
  "3230": "مَآرِبُ and related words stem from the root أ-ر-ب, with the root verb أَرِبَ meaning \"he was skillful\" or \"he had a need or desire.\" مَآرِبُ is the plural of مَأْرَبَةٌ, meaning \"needs,\" \"desires,\" or \"purposes.\" The connection reflects the various aims a person may pursue, highlighting the root's emphasis on intent and the skillful attainment of goals. This term highlights the diversity of human ambitions and the resourcefulness applied in seeking their fulfillment.",
  "3231": "مَأْتِيٌّ and related words stem from the root أ-ت-ى, with the root verb أَتَى meaning \"he came\" or \"he arrived.\" مَأْتِيٌّ is a passive form meaning \"that which is approached\" or \"sure to be reached.\" The root emphasizes the act of coming and approaching, and مَأْتِيٌّ reflects being the object of that movement. In the Qur'an, it describes Allah’s promise of Paradise, emphasizing the certainty of its fulfillment and the inevitability of reaching what Allah (ﷻ) has decreed.",
  "3232": "مَأْجُوجُ stems from the root أ-ج-ج, with the root verb أَجَّ meaning \"it blazed,\" \"burned fiercely,\" or \"was inflamed.\" مَأْجُوجُ refers to Magog, from the pair Gog and Magog, a people mentioned in the Qur'an associated with chaos and destruction. The connection lies in the imagery of intense burning, symbolizing the destructive and overwhelming force attributed to Magog. In Islamic studies of the 'end times,' Gog and Magog represent forces that will emerge before the Day of Judgment, testing humanity's faith through overwhelming trials and challenges.",
  "3233": "مَأْكُولٌ and related words stem from the root أ-ك-ل, with the root verb أَكَلَ meaning \"he ate\" or \"he consumed.\" مَأْكُولٌ is a passive form meaning \"eaten,\" \"consumed,\" or \"edible,\" describing something that is consumed or intended to be eaten. The connection turns the root’s action into its object, focusing on what is being eaten. In a broader sense, the root also encompasses meanings related to the consumption or depletion of resources, as well as gradual erosion or destruction. In the Qur'an, it emphasizes complete annihilation, as in the phrase \"like eaten straw\", highlighting total destruction.",
  "3234": "مَأْمَنٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ن, with the root verb أَمِنَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he trusted,\" or \"he felt secure.\" مَأْمَنٌ means \"place of safety,\" \"refuge,\" or \"secure haven.\" The connection lies in being a location or state where one feels completely safe and at peace, reflecting the root’s emphasis on trust, security, and protection. مَأْمَنٌ provides not only physical safety but also emotional reassurance, serving as a sanctuary where one is free from fear, embodying both peace and dependability.",
  "3235": "مَأْمُونٌ and related words stem from the root أ-م-ن, with the root verb أَمِنَ meaning \"he was safe,\" \"he trusted,\" or \"he felt secure.\" مَأْمُونٌ translates to \"trusted,\" \"reliable,\" or \"secure.\" The connection lies in describing someone or something that is dependable and inspires confidence, reflecting the root’s emphasis on trustworthiness, security, and reliability. An individual described as مَأْمُونٌ is one whose actions inspire peace and confidence in others, embodying both honesty and steadfastness. This term highlights the value of reliability and the sense of assurance that comes from placing trust in someone dependable.",
  "3236": "مَأْوًى and related words stem from the root أ-و-ي, with the root verb أَوَىٰ meaning \"he took shelter\" or \"he sought refuge.\" مَأْوًى means \"refuge,\" \"abode,\" or \"dwelling place,\" referring to a place where one finds shelter, rest, or stability. The connection lies in the concept of a secure place of residence, embodying the root’s essence of providing or seeking safety and comfort. It often signifies the ultimate dwelling, such as Paradise or Hell, highlighting the idea of an enduring refuge that reflects the consequences of one's actions.",
  "3237": "مَبْثُوثٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ث-ث, with the root verb بَثَّ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he dispersed.\" مَبْثُوثٌ translates as \"scattered\" or \"dispersed,\" describing something that has been actively spread out or scattered by an external force, resulting in separation across a wide area. This term suggests the breaking apart of a unified whole, often implying a sense of disorder or dispersal from a central point. It reflects the root’s concept of scattering, emphasizing an action that causes elements to be separated or dispersed beyond one’s control.",
  "3238": "مَبْثُوثَةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ث-ث, with the root verb بَثَّ meaning \"he scattered\" or \"he dispersed.\" مَبْثُوثَةٌ means \"scattered,\" \"dispersed,\" or \"spread out.\" This term can refer to something laid out widely and arranged in multiple directions, such as a display of abundance. In some contexts, it also suggests being broken up or separated from an original state, reflecting the root’s concept of dispersal.",
  "3239": "مَبْسُوطَتانِ and related words stem from the root ب-س-ط, with the root verb بَسَطَ meaning \"he spread it,\" \"he expanded, extended, or made it wide or ample.\" مَبْسُوطَتانِ is the dual form of مَبْسُوط, meaning \"spread out\" or \"extended,\" and refers to \"two things that are spread out or extended.\" Root concepts include openness, ease, and abundance, emphasizing accessibility and readiness. In classical usage, it often describes hands that are مَبْسُوطَتانِ—spread out in a gesture of giving, symbolizing generosity and ample provision.",
  "3240": "مَبْعُوثُونَ and related words stem from the root ب-ع-ث, with the root verb بَعَثَ meaning \"he sent,\" often referring to sending a messenger or dispatching something important. It also means \"he awakened\" or \"put in motion,\" particularly when stirring someone from rest or stillness. In the Qur'an, مَبْعُوثُونَ refers to \"those who are raised,\" meaning those \"sent back\" to Allah (ﷻ) on the Day of Resurrection. The root conveys themes of awakening, motion, and purposeful action, emphasizing Allah’s (ﷻ) power in sending guidance through messengers and resurrecting humanity for accountability and divine judgment.",
  "3241": "مَبْلَغٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ل-غ, with the root verb بَلَغَ meaning \"he reached\" or \"he attained.\" مَبْلَغٌ refers to the \"utmost point,\" \"scope,\" or \"extent\" of something, such as knowledge or achievement. It describes the maximum reach or limit to which something can extend, capturing the idea of full attainment or the culmination of efforts. This term emphasizes the concept of reaching the highest or most complete degree possible in a goal, purpose, or state.",
  "3242": "مَبْنِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ب-ن-ي, with the root verb بَنَىٰ meaning \"he built, framed, or constructed.\" مَبْنِيَّةٌ, meaning \"built up\" or \"constructed in layers,\" reflects something set firmly in place, each layer reinforcing the one before it. Beyond physical construction, the root conveys ideas of establishing, stabilizing, and elevating. This suggests not only physical height but also resilience and enduring purpose, portraying something deliberately raised to withstand the passage of time.",
  "3243": "مَتَابٌ and related words stem from the root ت-و-ب, with the root verb تَابَ meaning \"he repented\" or \"he returned [to God] from sin to obedience.\" مَتَابٌ means \"place of return,\" indicating a state or destination to which one turns back, especially in the sense of repentance. Rooted in the concept of seeking Allah’s (ﷻ) mercy, مَتَابٌ emphasizes both the act of returning and the refuge found in Allah (ﷻ) as one’s ultimate place of acceptance. This term highlights repentance as a path to divine grace, where returning to Allah (ﷻ) restores inner peace and spiritual alignment.",
  "3244": "مَتَاعٌ and related words stem from the root م-ت-ع, with the root verb مَتَعَ meaning \"he enjoyed,\" \"he benefited,\" or \"he made use of.\" مَتَاعٌ means \"goods,\" \"provisions,\" \"commodities,\" or \"enjoyment\"—referring to items or experiences that provide utility, benefit, or pleasure. The connection lies in these being sources of satisfaction and benefit, reflecting the root's emphasis on utility and transient enjoyment. It highlights the fleeting nature of worldly possessions and pleasures, serving as means to fulfill needs and desires but never as ultimate ends.",
  "3245": "مَتِينٌ and related words stem from the root م-ت-ن, with the verb مَتُنَ meaning \"he was firm,\" \"he was strong,\" or \"he was solid.\" مَتِينٌ means \"strong\" or \"firm,\" emphasizing resilience and unyielding strength. The root conveys the idea of enduring solidity and steadfastness, reflecting the capacity to withstand challenges without weakening. ٱلْمَتِينُ, one of Allah's (ﷻ) perfect names, refers to \"The Firm\" or \"The Steadfast,\" highlighting Allah’s (ﷻ) unshakeable strength and unwavering power. It reminds us of Allah’s (ﷻ) stability and reliability, urging us to seek His support in our lives and to develop firmness in our convictions and actions.",
  "3246": "مَتِّعُوا and related words stem from the root م-ت-ع, with the root verb مَتَعَ meaning \"he enjoyed,\" \"he benefited,\" or \"he made use of.\" مَتِّعُوا means \"grant provision!\" or \"allow to enjoy!\" The connection lies in bestowing benefit or facilitating enjoyment for others, reflecting the root's emphasis on utility, satisfaction, and temporary enjoyment. It highlights the act of generosity in enabling others to experience benefits and the kindness inherent in sharing provisions or pleasures.",
  "3247": "مَتْرَبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ت-ر-ب, with the root verb تَرِبَ meaning \"he became dusty\" or \"he was destitute.\" مَتْرَبَةٌ means \"the suffering loss, and becoming poor, so as to cleave to the dust, or earth,\" describing a state of deep poverty where one is metaphorically or literally covered in dust. This term conveys profound deprivation and humility, reflecting the lowest condition of hardship, symbolized by dust. Rooted in the concept of dust, مَتْرَبَةٌ emphasizes vulnerability and reliance on survival, illustrating how poverty brings a person to the most humble, earthbound state.",
  "3248": "مَثَابَةٌ and related words stem from the root ث-و-ب, with the root verb ثَابَ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he went back,\" or \"he came back to a place or state.\" مَثَابَةٌ means \"place of return\" and also signifies \"a place of reward,\" directly tied to the root's concept of returning. This connection emphasizes a location to which people repeatedly come back for refuge, connection, or renewal, whether physically or spiritually. It reflects the root’s broader theme of restoration, as the term symbolizes a central space where individuals find belonging, reflect on their efforts, and experience the rewards of devotion and effort, highlighting its deep significance in fostering both unity and renewal.",
  "3249": "مَثَانِيَ and related words stem from the root ث-ن-ي, with the root verb ثَنَىٰ meaning \"he folded,\" \"he doubled,\" or \"he bent.\" مَثَانِيَ is the plural of مَثْنَى, meaning \"paired\" or \"doubled,\" and also conveys the idea of repetition due to the root’s connection to folding and doubling. This term describes something frequently repeated or revisited to emphasize reinforcement, reflection, and importance, ensuring deeper understanding and lasting impact.",
  "3250": "مَثَلُ and related words stem from the root م-ث-ل, with the root verb مَثَلَ meaning \"he resembled,\" \"he was like,\" or \"he set forth an example.\" مَثَلُ means \"example,\" \"parable,\" or \"likeness,\" illustrating concepts through comparison or analogy. The connection lies in the root’s focus on exemplification, making abstract ideas relatable by drawing parallels. It serves as a powerful tool for teaching and understanding, simplifying complex concepts through meaningful comparisons.",
  "3251": "مَثُلَاتُ and related words stem from the root م-ث-ل, with the root verb مَثَلَ meaning \"he resembled,\" \"he was like,\" or \"he set forth an example.\" مَثُلَاتُ refers to \"examples\" or \"instances\" that illustrate or represent something, often serving as lessons for others. The connection lies in their role as cautionary examples that convey significant outcomes or principles, reflecting the root's concept of exemplification and comparison. It highlights how certain events or actions can serve as illustrative lessons, demonstrating consequences or truths to guide behavior or understanding.",
  "3252": "مَثُوبَةٌ and related words stem from the root ث-و-ب, with the root verb ثَابَ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he went back,\" or \"he came back to a place or state.\" مَثُوبَةٌ means \"reward\" or \"recompense,\" directly tied to the root's sense of returning, as it represents the idea of giving back or restoring something as a consequence of one’s actions. This connection highlights the fairness and moral balance inherent in the concept of recompense. While ثَوَابٌ also means \"reward,\" it often emphasizes an enduring or ultimate return, whereas مَثُوبَةٌ focuses on a deserved or measured recompense, highlighting the justice and restoration linked to the root’s overarching theme of returning what is due.",
  "3253": "مَثْبُورٌ originates from the root ث-ب-ر, with the root verb ثَبَرَ meaning \"he confined, restrained, withheld, hindered, or prevented,\" or \"he expelled,\" or \"he destroyed.\" Metaphorically extended, مَثْبُورٌ means \"destroyed\" or \"ruined,\" describing someone afflicted by profound ruin or doomed to destruction. This usage connects to the root by reflecting the idea of prevention or withholding, where being \"ruined\" or \"cut off\" signifies a state of being restrained from continuity or prosperity. It highlights how actions that figuratively hinder or sever moral and ethical boundaries lead to ultimate devastation, aligning with the root's themes of restraint, hindrance, and destruction.",
  "3254": "مَثْنَىٰ and related words stem from the root ث-ن-ي, with the root verb ثَنَىٰ meaning \"he folded,\" \"he doubled,\" or \"he bent.\" مَثْنَىٰ means \"in pairs\" or \"two by two,\" reflecting the concept of things occurring in twos. Unlike the numeral اثْنَانِ, which denotes the number two in a straightforward sense, مَثْنَىٰ emphasizes pairing or grouping, highlighting balance and harmony. It is used descriptively to indicate duality, often implying a natural or inherent pairing.",
  "3255": "مَثْوًى and related words stem from the root ث-و-ي, with the root verb ثَوَى meaning \"he remained,\" \"he dwelled,\" or \"he stayed in place.\" مَثْوًى means \"abode\" or \"dwelling place,\" signifying a location where one resides, either temporarily or permanently. The root emphasizes the act of staying or remaining, and مَثْوًى extends this meaning to the physical space associated with that act. It often carries connotations of permanence, reflecting the idea of a final resting place or a destination of stability and continuity.",
  "3256": "مَجَالِسُ and related words stem from the root ج-ل-س, with the root verb جَلَسَ meaning \"he sat,\" conveying the basic act of sitting or settling. The root extends to broader meanings of stability, presence, and readiness for interaction. مَجَالِسُ, the plural of مَجْلِسٌ, refers to \"gatherings\" or \"assemblies,\" signifying spaces where individuals come together for discussion, deliberation, or social interaction. The connection lies in the foundational act of sitting, which facilitates engagement and interaction, reflecting themes of stability and community.",
  "3257": "المَجُوسُ is a non-Arabic word widely regarded as originating from Persia. It refers to the Magians, a nation associated with Zoroastrianism, who venerated false deities, with fire serving as a central symbol of divine purity and light. In Persian, المَجُوسُ specifically refers to the Magi, the priestly class of Zoroastrianism, responsible for conducting rituals, interpreting sacred texts, and maintaining sacred fires, which were central to their religious practices.",
  "3258": "مَجِيدٌ and related words stem from the root م-ج-د, with the verb مَجَدَ meaning \"he was glorious\" or \"he possessed nobility.\" مَجْدٌ signifies \"glory,\" \"nobility,\" or \"honor,\" reflecting qualities of grandeur and excellence. مَجِيدٌ means \"glorious\" or \"magnificent,\" emphasizing lofty and esteemed attributes tied to the root’s concept of unmatched glory and honor. ٱلْمَجِيدُ, one of Allah’s (ﷻ) beautiful names, means \"The Glorious,\" highlighting His boundless majesty, intrinsic perfection, and unparalleled greatness that inspire awe and reverence.",
  "3259": "مَجْذُوذٌ and related words stem from the root ج-ذ-ذ, with the root verb جَذَّ meaning \"he cut off\" or \"he broke into pieces.\" مَجْذُوذٌ is a passive form meaning \"cut off\" or \"severed,\" describing something forcibly detached or disconnected. The root emphasizes themes of separation, disconnection, and finality, often conveying a sense of loss or deprivation. مَجْذُوذٌ reflects these ideas by illustrating the state of being severed from sources of sustenance, unity, or guidance, highlighting the profound impact of such a separation.",
  "3260": "مَجْرًى and related words stem from the root ج-ر-ي, with the root verb جَرَىٰ meaning \"it flowed,\" \"it ran,\" or \"it passed along qickly.\" مَجْرًى means \"course,\" \"channel,\" or \"place of flowing,\" referring to the path through which something flows, such as a riverbed or a ship’s trajectory. The root highlights the structured flow or motion within a defined space, emphasizing how movement requires a pathway. مَجْرًى reflects the root’s broader theme of motion directed through a specific route or channel.",
  "3261": "مَجْمَعٌ and related words stem from the root ج-م-ع, with the root verb جَمَعَ meaning \"he gathered.\" مَجْمَعٌ refers to a \"place of gathering\" or \"assembly point,\" highlighting a physical or metaphorical space designated for uniting individuals or elements. The connection emphasizes the central role of such spaces in fostering unity and collaboration, serving as focal points for bringing together diverse components for a shared purpose.",
  "3262": "مَجْمُوعٌ and related words stem from the root ج-م-ع, with the root verb جَمَعَ meaning \"he gathered\" or \"he collected.\" مَجْمُوعٌ means \"gathered\" or \"collected,\" emphasizing the state of having been brought together or assembled into a unified whole. The root conveys the act of bringing together separate parts into a unified whole, emphasizing intentionality, organization, and unity. The connection reflects the result of deliberate gathering, highlighting themes of completeness, order, and cohesion.",
  "3263": "مَجْنُونٌ and related words stem from the root ج-ن-ن, with the root verb جَنَّ meaning \"he concealed\" or \"he covered.\" مَجْنُونٌ is a passive form meaning \"possessed\" or \"insane person,\" reflecting a state where the mind is veiled, obscured, or overtaken. The root conveys broader meanings of concealment, covering, or shielding, often associated with hiddenness or inaccessibility. This connection emphasizes the notion of the intellect being metaphorically shrouded or hidden, symbolizing a disruption of clarity, awareness, or reason, and highlighting the profound implications of mental veiling in both literal and figurative senses.",
  "3264": "مَحَارِيبُ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-ب, with the root verb حَرَبَ meaning \"he plundered\" and حَرْبٌ meaning \"war\" or \"battle.\" مَحَارِيبُ means \"prayer niches,\" \"sanctuaries,\" or \"elevated chambers.\" The connection lies in struggle, separation, and exclusivity. Just as plundering seizes possessions, the مِحْرَابُ metaphorically \"plunders\" worldly distractions, calling one to worship. It signifies spiritual conquest, where devotion overcomes material attachments. The root’s link to war reflects the inner struggle against lower desires, as worship demands discipline. Historically, مَحَارِيبُ also refer to grand chambers of governance and prayer, symbolizing authority and a space for higher purpose.",
  "3265": "مَحَبَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ب-ب, with the root verb حَبَّ meaning \"he was loved.\" مَحَبَّةٌ can mean \"love\" or \"affection,\" but more specifically, it often refers to a manifestation of affection, emphasizing the source or action that inspires love. The root conveys themes of endearment, nurturing, and connection, highlighting the active and relational aspects of love. The connection lies in love as a reflection of love in action, fostering bonds and harmony.",
  "3266": "مَحَوْنَا and related words stem from the root م-ح-و, with the root verb مَحَا meaning \"he erased,\" often implying the removal of something until no trace remains. مَحَوْنَا means \"We erased,\" emphasizing the act of complete removal. The connection lies in the root’s theme of negation and obliteration, whether physical, abstract, or metaphorical, reflecting the idea of wiping away what existed to render it null. This captures the transformative power of erasure, whether in the context of natural phenomena, written records, or symbolic acts of change, highlighting both the fragility of what is erased and the deliberate nature of the act.",
  "3267": "مَحِلٌّ and related words stem from the root ح-ل-ل, with the root verb حَلَّ meaning \"he untied\" or \"he loosened.\" From this comes أَحَلَّ, meaning \"he made lawful,\" and تَحَلَّلَ, meaning \"he became free from restriction.\" مَحِلٌّ refers to the lawful place of slaughter for a sacrificial animal. The root dimensions encompass untying, resolving, and settling, emphasizing the removal of restrictions and the completion of actions. The connection lies in the designated place where an act is \"untied\" or brought to fulfillment, such as the lawful site for carrying out sacrificial rites. This reflects the root’s broader themes of permissibility, resolution, and fulfillment, where specific actions align with divine law and purpose.",
  "3268": "مَحِيصٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ص, with the root verb حَاصَ meaning \"he fled, escaped, or ran away,\" \"he avoided or deviated,\" or \"he sought a place of refuge.\" مَحِيصٌ means \"a place to which one turns away\" or \"a place of refuge.\" The root conveys themes of fleeing, avoidance, and seeking safety. The connection lies in the nature of this refuge—it is sought by one who has deviated or turned aside, emphasizing that the act of seeking protection here is not just escape but a consequence of wrongdoing or straying from the right path.",
  "3269": "مَحِيضٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ض, with the root verb حَاضَ meaning \"she menstruated,\" referring specifically to a woman experiencing her menstrual cycle. مَحِيضٌ means \"time of menstruation,\" referring to the menstrual period. This word also means \"it declined or turned away,\" indicating shifting or turning aside. The connection lies in the natural process of change during this time, where a woman transitions through a cyclical phase, temporarily turning away from its usual state. This reflects a period of inward focus and renewal, aligning with the root’s theme of movement, change, and temporary separation from the norm.",
  "3270": "مَحْجُوبٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ب, with the root verb حَجَبَ meaning \"he prevented or precluded\" and \"he concealed or protected.\" مَحْجُوبٌ is a passive form meaning \"hidden\" or \"veiled,\" referring to something obscured, blocked, or kept out of view. The root conveys meanings of covering, restricting, and shielding. The connection lies in the dual function of مَحْجُوبٌ—it signifies something kept distant or inaccessible while also being concealed or protected. This highlights how certain realities remain unseen, either as a barrier preventing access or as a safeguard preserving what lies beyond, emphasizing the distinction between the visible and hidden.",
  "3271": "مَحْجُورٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ج-ر, with the root verb حَجَرَ meaning \"he prevented\" or \"he restrained.\" مَحْجُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"forbidden,\" \"prohibited,\" or \"restricted.\" The root dimensions encompass concepts of prevention, enclosure, and safeguarding, with مَحْجُورٌ signifying something actively restrained or rendered inaccessible. The connection lies in being the object of prohibition, embodying the root's emphasis on boundaries and limitations. It highlights legal, moral, or physical restrictions designed to prevent transgression or ensure protection, reflecting the root’s focus on controlled access and restraint.",
  "3272": "مَحْذُورٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ذ-ر, with the root verb حَذِرَ meaning \"he was cautious\" or \"he was vigilant.\" مَحْذُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"something to be avoided\" or \"object of fear.\" The connection lies in being the cause of caution, reflecting the root's emphasis on avoiding harm. It denotes a danger or risk that prompts wariness, highlighting the importance of recognizing and steering clear of potential threats.",
  "3273": "مَحْرُومٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ر-م, with the root verb حَرُمَ meaning \"it was forbidden or prohibited,\" and حَرَمَ meaning \"he denied,\" and حَرَّمَ meaning \"he forbade, prohibited, or made unlawful.\" مَحْرُومٌ translates as \"deprived\" or \"destitute,\" referring to someone who has been denied something. The connection lies in being prevented from accessing certain benefits, reflecting the root's essence of prohibition and deprivation. This term often describes individuals in need or those unjustly denied their rights, emphasizing their state of hardship and exclusion.",
  "3274": "مَحْسُورٌ and related words stem from the root ح-س-ر, with the root verb حَسَرَ meaning \"he was tired or fatigued,\" and حَسِرَ meaning \"he felt grief, sorrow, or regret.\" مَحْسُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"exhausted,\" \"depleted,\" or \"drained,\" describing a state of being worn out due to exertion, hardship, or emotional strain. The connection lies in complete weariness and depletion, directly tied to the root’s emphasis on losing strength, vitality, or capability. This term conveys utter exhaustion, whether physical, emotional, or even metaphorical, highlighting the toll taken by continuous effort, prolonged hardship, or deep sorrow.",
  "3275": "مَحْشُورَةٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ش-ر, with the root verb حَشَرَ meaning \"he congregated or collected together\" or \"he made [them] go forth, collected together, from one place to another.\" The root also includes the idea of expelling or driving out and describes creatures like insects, which gather or move collectively. This highlights the inherent state of being drawn together, whether intentionally or instinctually. The term emphasizes the inevitability and universality of gathering, particularly in contexts like the Day of Judgment, where all beings will be assembled by Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3276": "مَحْظُورٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ظ-ر, with the root verb حَظَرَ meaning \"he forbade,\" \"he restricted,\" or \"he placed a barrier around something.\" مَحْظُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"forbidden,\" \"prohibited,\" or \"restricted,\" reflecting a state of being barred from access or action. The root conveys placing a boundary to limit movement, access, or participation, whether physically, legally, or metaphorically. It extends beyond prohibition to controlled limitation, ensuring order, security, or exclusivity. This highlights the balance between permissibility and restriction, shaping what is allowed and what is off-limits.",
  "3277": "مَحْفُوظٌ and related words stem from the root ح-ف-ظ, with the root verb حَفِظَ meaning \"he guarded,\" \"he protected,\" or \"he preserved.\" مَحْفُوظٌ is a passive form meaning \"protected,\" \"preserved,\" or \"guarded.\" This reflects the state of being kept safe from harm or loss, directly connecting to the root's emphasis on protection. The term highlights the value of what is being protected, whether it be physical items, knowledge, or spiritual states.",
  "3278": "مَحْمُودٌ and related words stem from the root ح-م-د, with the root verb حَمِدَ meaning \"he praised\" or \"he thanked.\" مَحْمُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"praised\" or \"commendable.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of praise due to virtuous qualities, noble actions, or inherent excellence. It signifies someone worthy of admiration, whose deeds or character evoke appreciation and respect. This reflects a status of distinction, where recognition is not merely given but deserved through righteousness, wisdom, or excellence in conduct. It is rooted in genuine merit, where honor is granted by virtue of one's integrity, sincerity, and contribution to what is good and just.",
  "3279": "مَحْيَا and related words stem from the root ح-ي-ي, with the root verb حَيِيَ meaning \"he was shy\" or \"he felt modesty,\" and حَيَّ meaning \"he lived\" or \"he became fresh or lively.\" مَحْيَا translates as \"life\" or \"manner of living,\" referring to how one conducts their life, encompassing actions, intentions, and purpose. The connection lies in how one's manner of living is not just about being alive but about living with awareness and direction. Just as the root verb reflects a state of liveliness or renewal, مَحْيَا embodies a person's choices and path, emphasizing a purposeful existence, as expressed in the declaration, \"Indeed, my prayer, my rites of sacrifice, my living (مَحْيَا), and my dying are for Allah.\"",
  "3280": "مَخَاضٌ and related words stem from the root م-خ-ض, with the root verb مَخَضَ meaning \"he churned\" (as in churning milk to extract butter), \"he shook or agitated the thing vehemently,\" and \"the sky became ready to rain,\" while مَخِضَتْ refers to pre-birth pains. مَخَاضٌ means \"labor pains\" or \"childbirth.\" The connection lies in the root's essence of intense agitation and preparation leading to transformation. Whether in churning milk, the shaking of objects, or the readiness of the sky for rain, the root reflects effort and movement resulting in creation. In childbirth, this is mirrored in the labor pains that bring forth new life, emphasizing profound effort leading to valuable outcomes.",
  "3281": "مَخْتُومٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ت-م, with the root verb خَتَمَ meaning \"he sealed\" or \"he concluded.\" مَخْتُومٌ means \"sealed\" or \"stamped,\" indicating something that has been securely closed or authenticated. The connection lies in the act of sealing as a means of protection or confirmation, reflecting the root's emphasis on finality and security. This term conveys the idea of something preserved or untouched until a designated time.",
  "3282": "مَخْذُولٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ذ-ل, with the root verb خَذَلَ meaning \"he abandoned or deserted,\" or \"he failed or disappointed.\" مَخْذُولٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is forsaken\" or \"abandoned,\" referring to someone left without aid or support. The connection lies in the state of being deserted, where مَخْذُولٌ reflects the consequences of abandonment—helplessness, vulnerability, and the absence of assistance—emphasizing the root’s theme of being left without support in a time of need.",
  "3283": "مَخْرَجٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ر-ج, with the root verb خَرَجَ meaning \"he went out\" or \"he exited.\" مَخْرَجٌ means \"exit,\" \"way out,\" or \"escape.\" The root conveys themes of departure, emergence, and separation. This word emphasizes a means or place of departure, representing a path to freedom or relief. It reflects the idea of finding an opening or solution, whether physically, situationally, or metaphorically, highlighting the concept of leaving behind restrictions or difficulties.",
  "3284": "مَخْضُودٌ and related words stem from the root خ-ض-د, with the root verb خَضَدَ meaning \"he removed the thorns.\" مَخْضُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"thornless.\" The root conveys breaking or bending without complete separation, particularly concerning wood or branches, and also relates to consuming soft, moist items. The connection lies in the act of removing thorns, making something smooth and accessible. In the Qur'anic description of Paradise, it refers to thornless lote trees, symbolizing perfect beauty and ease, where all obstacles and hardships are removed.",
  "3285": "مَخْمَصَةٌ and related words stem from the root خ-م-ص, with the root verb خَمَصَ meaning \"he suffered from hunger,\" \"his belly became contracted or shrunk (due to hunger),\" or \"he became weak or thin.\" The root revolves around hunger, contraction, thinness, and weakness, conveying the physical effects of emptiness and deprivation. مَخْمَصَةٌ means \"famine\" or \"extreme hunger,\" describing a state of severe lack and physical strain caused by insufficient sustenance. The connection to the root lies in the bodily effects of hunger—shrinkage, weakness, and emptiness—capturing the essence of deprivation and highlighting the harsh toll of famine on the body.",
  "3286": "مَدَائِنُ and related words stem from the root م-د-ن, with the root verb مَدَنَ meaning \"he resided in a city\" or \"he urbanized.\" مَدَائِنُ refers to \"cities\" or \"towns,\" emphasizing settled areas marked by structured governance and societal organization. The root conveys themes of urban settlement and civilization, reflecting the establishment of permanent communities. The connection lies in the development of cities as centers of interaction, culture, and administration, complementing other forms of organized living, such as nomadic societies, by highlighting the permanence and infrastructure unique to urban environments.",
  "3287": "مَدَدٌ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended,\" \"he stretched,\" or \"he prolonged.\" مَدَدٌ means \"aid,\" \"reinforcements,\" or \"supplies\" and focuses on the result or outcome of what is being provided. The connection lies in the idea of providing supplementary assistance, directly reflecting the root’s concept of extending or enhancing. This emphasizes the supply itself, rather than the supplier or the act of supplying.",
  "3288": "مَدِينِينَ and related words stem from the root دَيَن, with the root verb دَانَ meaning \"he obeyed\" or \"he borrowed.\" مَدِينٌ refers to \"ones who are in debt\" or \"ones who are accountable.\" The root revolves around obedience, judgment, and indebtedness, encompassing faith, legal rulings, and financial obligations. The connection lies in the sense of being bound by obligation, whether financially, morally, or spiritually. It reflects both a state of owing a debt and the broader concept of being held accountable for one’s actions. This term ties into justice and repayment, emphasizing responsibility not just in financial matters but in all aspects of life.",
  "3289": "مَدِينَةٌ and related words stem from the root م-د-ن, with the root verb مَدَنَ meaning \"he resided in a city\" or \"he urbanized.\" مَدِينَةٌ refers to a \"city\" or \"town,\" emphasizing a settled area marked by structured governance and societal organization. In the Qur'an, it is also used to refer to Al-Madinah Al-Munawwarah, the city of the Prophet Muhammad (ﷺ). The root conveys themes of urban settlement, civilization, and structured living. The connection lies in cities as centers of administration, culture, and interaction, offering distinct forms of organized living alongside other systems of settlement, such as nomadic or rural lifestyles. Each reflects a unique societal structure and function.",
  "3290": "مَدٌّ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, with the root verb مَدَّ meaning \"he extended,\" \"he stretched,\" or \"he prolonged.\" مَدٌّ means \"extension,\" \"prolongation,\" or \"expansion.\" The connection lies in the act or state of something being stretched out in space, time, or scope. It reflects the root’s emphasis on elongation and growth, highlighting the idea of something being made longer, broader, or more enduring, whether physically or metaphorically.",
  "3291": "مَدَّ and related words stem from the root م-د-د, and as the root verb, it means \"he extended,\" \"he stretched,\" or \"he prolonged.\" The connection is direct, involving the act of elongating or increasing something, whether physically or metaphorically. مَدَّ emphasizes the fundamental concept of extension, reflecting actions like lengthening time, expanding space, or amplifying quantity. It encapsulates the idea of growth or enhancement, often highlighting processes that result in continuity, enlargement, or reinforcement.",
  "3292": "مَدْحُورٌ and related words stem from the root د-ح-ر, with the root verb دَحَرَ meaning \"he drove away\" or \"he expelled.\" مَدْحُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"expelled,\" \"banished,\" or \"repelled,\" signifying someone forcibly driven away. The root revolves around repulsion, expulsion, subjugation, and rejection, conveying the forceful removal or suppression of something, often with an element of defeat or humiliation. The connection highlights a state of being cast out or rejected, reinforcing themes of overpowering and enforced separation.",
  "3293": "مَدْيَنُ stems from the root م-د-ن, with the root verb مَدَنَ meaning \"he resided in a city\" or \"he urbanized.\" مَدْيَنُ refers to the ancient people and region of Midian, a community to whom Prophet Shuayb (ﷺ) was sent. The root conveys themes of settlement, governance, and structure, which align with the physical and societal aspects of مَدْيَنُ as a settled community. Prophet Shuayb's (ﷺ) mission emphasized justice, accountability, and adherence to ethical principles, urging the people of Midian to abandon corruption and uphold Allah's (ﷻ) commands. مَدْيَنُ represents both the concept of physical settlement and the societal dimensions necessary for a just and thriving community.",
  "3294": "ذِئْبٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-أ-ب, with the root verb ذَأَبَ meaning \"he frightened him (as does a wolf),\" \"he despised him,\" or \"he drove him away.\" ذِئْبٌ means \"a wolf,\" directly reflecting the root’s meanings of fear, hostility, and expulsion. Just as a wolf instills fear and chases away its prey, this word conveys themes of aggression, isolation, and relentless pursuit, emphasizing the wolf’s nature as a feared predator often associated with ruthlessness and deception.",
  "3295": "مَذْكُورٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-ك-ر, with the root verb ذَكَرَ meaning \"he remembered\" or \"he mentioned.\" مَذْكُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"mentioned\" or \"remembered,\" referring to something that has been brought to attention. The connection lies in being the subject of mention or remembrance, reflecting the root's emphasis on memory and speech. It highlights the significance of being noteworthy or deserving of mention, often in the context of praise or importance.",
  "3296": "مَذْمُومٌ and related words stem from the root ذ-م-م, with the root verb ذَمَّ meaning \"he blamed,\" \"he censured,\" or \"he reproached.\" مَذْمُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"blamed,\" \"censured,\" or \"blameworthy,\" referring to someone or something deserving of disapproval or reproach. The root extends to themes of dishonor, disgrace, and condemnation, emphasizing actions or traits that lead to blame or moral failure. It also carries connotations of weakness or deficiency, as blame often arises from shortcomings or faults. This term highlights the consequences of engaging in dishonorable or reprehensible behavior, serving as a reminder to strive for conduct that is praiseworthy and free of reproach.",
  "3297": "مَرَاضِعُ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-ع, with the root verb رَضَعَ meaning \"he suckled\" or \"he nursed.\" مَرَاضِعُ means \"wet nurses\" or \"women who breastfeed others' children.\" The connection is through the role of providing nourishment to infants who are not one's own, extending the root's concept of nursing and caregiving beyond the biological mother. This term reflects societal practices where women offer their nurturing abilities to care for others' children, emphasizing communal support and the universal importance of nurturing.",
  "3298": "مَرَافِقُ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ق, with the root verb رَفَقَ meaning \"he was kind\" or \"he was gentle.\" مَرَافِقُ is the plural of مِرْفَقٌ, meaning \"facilities,\" \"conveniences,\" or \"elbows\" in anatomical context. The connection lies in things that provide ease or assistance, embodying the root's emphasis on kindness and helpfulness. This term reflects the provisions and amenities that facilitate comfort and ease in life.",
  "3299": "مَرَجَ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ج, and as the root verb, it means \"he let loose,\" \"he mingled,\" or \"he set free.\" The connection lies in the act of releasing elements to interact freely, leading to a state of blending or meeting. This reflects the root's emphasis on intermingling, highlighting both the potential for interaction and the maintenance of boundaries, as exemplified in the Qur'anic verse where two seas are set free to meet yet remain distinct.",
  "3300": "مَرَحٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ح, with the root verb مَرِحَ meaning \"he exulted,\" \"he was joyous,\" or \"he was insolently proud.\" مَرَحٌ means \"exultation,\" \"arrogance,\" or \"insolent pride.\" The root reflects a state of excessive joy that transforms into haughtiness, highlighting the dangers of unrestrained elation leading to arrogance. It emphasizes the pitfalls of prideful behavior, cautioning against allowing joy to overshadow humility or foster disdain for others. This connects to the root’s core idea of overstepping bounds, showing how unchecked joy can lead to arrogance and imbalance.",
  "3301": "مَرَدُوا and related words stem from the root م-ر-د, with the root verb مَرَدَ meaning \"he was rebellious\" or \"he became hardened in disobedience.\" مَرَدُوا means \"they persisted\" or \"they became hardened,\" describing a group entrenched in hypocrisy or defiance. The connection lies in the deliberate and sustained nature of their disobedience, highlighting an active shedding of moral guidance. This reflects the root’s theme of rebellion and obstinacy, emphasizing a continual state of defiance against what is righteous or just.",
  "3302": "مَرَدٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د, with the root verb رَدَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" مَرَدٌّ means \"place of return\" or \"destination.\" The connection lies in the concept of a point or place to which one returns, embodying the root's essence of returning. It may also symbolize the ultimate return to Allah (ﷻ) or the final abode in the hereafter, emphasizing accountability and the cyclical nature of life.",
  "3303": "مَرَضٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ض, with the root verb مَرِضَ meaning \"he was ill\" or \"he became sick.\" مَرَضٌ means \"sickness,\" \"illness,\" or \"disease.\" The connection is direct, representing the state of being unwell and capturing the essence of physical or metaphorical ailments. This reflects the root's core idea of weakness in health, highlighting human vulnerability and the impact of illness on one's well-being.",
  "3304": "مَرِضْتُ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ض, with the root verb مَرِضَ meaning \"he was ill\" or \"he became sick.\" مَرِضْتُ translates to \"I became ill\" or \"I fell sick.\" The root encompasses concepts of sickness, weakness, and deviation from a state of health, extending beyond physical illness to include moral or spiritual ailments, such as مَرَضُ القَلْبِ (disease of the heart), symbolizing corruption or deficiency in faith or character. It highlights a state of vulnerability—physical, emotional, or spiritual—reflecting the comprehensive understanding of health and illness in classical Arabic.",
  "3305": "مَرِيئًا and related words stem from the root م-ر-أ, with the root verb مَرَأَ meaning \"he digested (food).\" مَرِيئًا means \"wholesome,\" \"pleasant,\" or \"easy to digest.\" The connection lies in the agreeable quality of food that nourishes and sustains well-being. It directly ties to the root’s focus on digestion, emphasizing nourishment that is smooth, beneficial, and harmonious, promoting health and balance within the body.",
  "3306": "مَرِيجٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ج, with the root verb مَرَجَ meaning \"he mingled,\" \"he mixed,\" or \"he became confused.\" مَرِيجٌ means \"confused,\" \"turbulent,\" or \"in disarray.\" The connection lies in the chaos arising from uncontrolled or excessive mixing, reflecting the root's concept of disorder through intermingling. It conveys the instability and lack of clarity that result from elements blending in a way that disrupts harmony or coherence.",
  "3307": "مَرِيدٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-د, with the root verb مَرَدَ meaning \"he was rebellious,\" \"he became stubborn,\" or \"it was bare.\" مَرِيدٌ is an intensive form meaning \"extremely rebellious\" or \"defiantly disobedient.\" It represents a heightened state of defiance, describing someone deeply entrenched in rebellion and stripped entirely of moral restraint. Unlike مارِدٌ, which indicates general rebellion, مَرِيدٌ reflects persistent defiance and a complete severance from submission and virtue. This term often describes beings like rebellious devils, emphasizing their extreme stubbornness and evil intent.",
  "3308": "مَرِيضٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ض, with the root verb مَرِضَ meaning \"he was ill\" or \"he became sick.\" مَرِيضٌ means \"sick person\" or \"one who is ill.\" The connection lies in embodying the state of illness, representing an individual experiencing weakness or disease. This directly reflects the root's core idea of sickness, highlighting the personal impact of ailments on a person's physical and emotional state.",
  "3309": "مَرٌّ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ر, with the root verb مَرَّ meaning \"he passed by\" or \"he was or became bitter.\" مَرٌّ means \"passing,\" \"passage,\" or \"bitterness.\" The root conveys dual concepts of transience and harshness. \"Passing\" reflects the fleeting nature of time or events, while \"bitterness\" symbolizes challenges, struggles, or unpleasant experiences. The connection highlights how the passage of time can bring both temporary relief and enduring difficulty, reflecting the root's broader themes of impermanence, resilience, and the emotional intensity of life's trials.",
  "3310": "مَرَّ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ر, and as the root verb, it means \"he passed by,\" \"he went along,\" or \"he was or became bitter.\" مَرَّ captures both the physical act of moving past something and the emotional experience of bitterness. The root also encompasses ideas of progression, endurance, and sharpness, illustrating how life's transience can be both fleeting and impactful. This connection reflects the duality of moving forward while carrying the emotional residue of difficult moments, emphasizing the interplay between change, hardship, and resilience.",
  "3311": "مَرَّةٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ر, with the root verb مَرَّ meaning \"he passed by\" or \"he became bitter.\" مَرَّةٌ means \"an instance,\" \"a time,\" or \"an occasion.\" The root conveys ideas of singularity, transience, and movement, with مَرَّةٌ representing distinct moments or occurrences that \"pass\" in time. This reflects the fleeting nature of life's events, where each moment, though temporary, carries unique significance. The root’s emphasis on passage and impermanence highlights how every \"instance\" contributes to the larger journey of life.",
  "3312": "مَرْءٌ stems from the root م-ر-أ, with the root verb مَرَأَ meaning \"he digested (food).\" مَرْءٌ means \"man\" or \"person.\" The connection to the root lies in the human reliance on digestion as a metaphor for vitality and sustenance. It represents the individual as a participant in the cycles of life, consuming resources to maintain health and contributing to the processes that sustain others. It highlights human resilience and the importance of health and well-being in sustaining one’s role within life’s greater system.",
  "3313": "مَرْجَانٌ and related words stem from the root م-ر-ج, with the root verb مَرَجَ meaning \"he mingled,\" \"he mixed,\" or \"he let loose.\" مَرْجَانٌ primarily refers to \"coral\" and, in some contexts, to \"small pearls.\" The connection lies in coral’s intricate, interwoven structures, reflecting the root's concept of mingling and interconnection. Coral forms through the harmonious growth of individual polyps into a unified ecosystem, while the occasional reference to small pearls highlights their resemblance to coral in their smooth, clustered forms. Both emphasize natural beauty arising from interdependence, balance, and complexity.",
  "3314": "مَرْجُومٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-م, with the root verb رَجَمَ meaning \"he stoned\" or \"he cursed.\" مَرْجُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"stoned\" or \"accursed.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of stoning or cursing, reflecting the root's emphasis on punishment. This term denotes someone condemned or expelled, highlighting the severe consequences of wrongdoing and societal rejection.",
  "3315": "مَرْجُوٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-و, with the root verb رَجَا meaning \"he hoped\" or \"he expected.\" مَرْجُوٌّ is a passive form meaning \"hoped for\" or \"expected.\" The connection lies in being the object of hope, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on desire. This term highlights something awaited with anticipation, emphasizing the importance of future aspirations and trust.",
  "3316": "مَرْجِعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ج-ع, with the root verb رَجَعَ meaning \"he returned\" or \"he went back.\" مَرْجِعٌ means \"place of return\" or \"resort.\" The connection lies in denoting the destination to which one returns, directly reflecting the root's emphasis on going back. This term highlights the concept of an ultimate destination or source, often used to signify returning to Allah (ﷻ) or a foundational truth.",
  "3317": "مَرْحَبٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-ب, with the root verb رَحَبَ meaning \"he was wide\" or \"he was spacious.\" مَرْحَبٌ means \"a wide space\" or \"welcome.\" The connection lies in the concept of spaciousness, reflecting the root's emphasis on breadth. This term symbolizes openness and generosity, often used to express welcome and hospitality.",
  "3318": "مَرْحَمَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ح-م, with the root verb رَحِمَ meaning \"he showed mercy\" or \"he had compassion.\" مَرْحَمَةٌ means \"act of mercy\" or \"compassionate deed.\" The connection lies in translating mercy into tangible actions that alleviate suffering and promote well-being. The root emphasizes the practical application of compassion, inspiring individuals to embody mercy through acts of kindness, care, and support for others in need.",
  "3319": "مَرْدُودٌ and related words stem from the root ر-د-د, with the root verb رَدَّ meaning \"he returned,\" \"he repelled,\" or \"he rejected.\" مَرْدُودٌ is a passive form meaning \"returned,\" \"rejected,\" or \"refused.\" The connection reflects the state of something that has been sent back or not accepted, embodying the root's essence of rejection or return. It highlights the consequences of actions or offerings that are not accepted, emphasizing the importance of sincerity and acceptability.",
  "3320": "مَرْصَدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ص-د, with the root verb رَصَدَ meaning \"he watched,\" \"he observed,\" or \"he lay in wait.\" مَرْصَدٌ means \"a watch-post,\" \"an ambush,\" or \"a place of observation.\" The connection lies in the physical location designated for vigilant watching or guarding, embodying the root's emphasis on observation and readiness. This term captures the idea of a strategic position from which one can observe or await events, reflecting the root's focus on deliberate and purposeful watchfulness.",
  "3321": "مَرْصُوصٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ص-ص, with the root verb رَصَّ meaning \"he pressed together,\" \"he compacted,\" or \"he consolidated.\" مَرْصُوصٌ means \"solidified,\" \"compacted,\" or \"joined firmly together.\" The connection lies in the idea of elements being closely united to form a strong, unbreakable whole, embodying the root's emphasis on cohesion and solidarity. In the Qur'anic context, believers are likened to a \"بُنْيَانٌ مَرْصُوصٌ,\" a solid structure, highlighting the moral lesson of unity and steadfastness in faith and action.",
  "3322": "مَرْضَاتٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" مَرْضَاتٌ means \"that which pleases\" or \"object of satisfaction.\" The connection lies in something that causes pleasure or earns approval, embodying the root's emphasis on contentment. This term reflects actions or qualities that lead to being pleasing to Allah (ﷻ), highlighting the moral significance of seeking divine approval through righteous deeds.",
  "3323": "مَرْضِيٌّ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" مَرْضِيٌّ means \"approved\" or \"accepted,\" referring to someone or something that has attained favor or satisfaction. The root encompasses themes of contentment, harmony, and divine approval, emphasizing the mutual satisfaction between the one who is approved and the one granting approval. The connection highlights the spiritual achievement of earning Allah's (ﷻ) acceptance, where one's deeds and character align with what is pleasing to Him, reflecting the ultimate fulfillment of divine favor.",
  "3324": "مَرْضِيَّةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ض-و, with the root verb رَضِيَ meaning \"he was pleased\" or \"he was content.\" مَرْضِيَّةٌ means \"pleasing\" or \"accepted,\" describing something or someone in a state of being favored or approved. The root conveys themes of satisfaction, harmony, and acceptance, emphasizing both inner contentment and external approval. The connection lies in the soul’s attainment of Allah's (ﷻ) acceptance, reflecting the ultimate spiritual fulfillment where one's deeds and state are fully aligned with divine pleasure. This term highlights the honor and grace of being deemed worthy and approved in the sight of Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3325": "مَرْعًى and related words stem from the root ر-ع-ي, with the root verb رَعَىٰ meaning \"he tended\" or \"he cared for.\" مَرْعًى means \"pasture\" or \"grazing land.\" The connection lies in the place where livestock feed and are tended, embodying the root's emphasis on nurturing and provision. This term symbolizes sustenance and abundance provided by the earth, reflecting the blessings of natural resources.",
  "3326": "مَرْفُودٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-د, with the root verb رَفَدَ meaning \"he assisted\" or \"he supported.\" مَرْفُودٌ means \"supported\" or \"aided.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of assistance or support, embodying the root's emphasis on help and backing. This term highlights the state of being strengthened or upheld by others, reflecting themes of reliance and communal support.",
  "3327": "مَرْفُوعٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ع, with the root verb رَفَعَ meaning \"he raised\" or \"he lifted.\" مَرْفُوعٌ means \"raised\" or \"elevated.\" The connection lies in the state of being lifted up, embodying the root's emphasis on elevation. This term can refer to objects, ranks, or statuses that have been elevated, highlighting themes of honor and distinction.",
  "3328": "مَرْفُوعَةٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ف-ع, with the root verb رَفَعَ meaning \"he raised\" or \"he lifted.\" مَرْفُوعَةٌ means \"raised\" or \"elevated.\" The connection is similar, emphasizing the state of being lifted up, directly reflecting the root's emphasis. This term can describe elevated furnishings in paradise or statuses, highlighting beauty and honor.",
  "3329": "مَرْقَدٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-د, with the root verb رَقَدَ meaning \"he slept\" or \"he lay down.\" مَرْقَدٌ refers to \"a place of sleep\" or \"resting place,\" such as a bed or even a grave. The connection lies in the physical location where one lies down to rest, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'anic context, مَرْقَدُنَا (\"our place of rest\") is used to denote the grave or the place from which people are awakened on the Day of Resurrection, highlighting the transition from a state of rest to awakening.",
  "3330": "مَرْقُومٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ق-م, with the root verb رَقَمَ meaning \"he wrote\" or \"he inscribed.\" مَرْقُومٌ means \"written\" or \"inscribed,\" emphasizing something that has been meticulously recorded. The connection lies in the object bearing writing or inscription, directly relating to the root's meaning. In the Qur'an, it refers to scrolls or records that are precisely inscribed, highlighting the permanence and exactness of divine decrees.",
  "3331": "مَرْكُومٌ and related words stem from the root ر-ك-م, with the root verb رَكَمَ meaning \"he heaped up\" or \"he piled.\" مَرْكُومٌ is a passive form meaning \"heaped up\" or \"piled up.\" The connection lies in the state of being accumulated, directly relating to the root's meaning. It often describes clouds or layers densely stacked, highlighting the overwhelming nature of accumulated entities.",
  "3332": "الْمَرْوَةَ and related words stem from the root م-ر-و, with the root verb مَرَىٰ meaning \"he sharpened\" or \"he rubbed.\" مَرْوَةٌ refers to a \"hard, white stone\" or \"flint,\" symbolizing strength and resilience. الْمَرْوَةَ refers to the sacred hill Al-Marwa in Mecca, deeply tied to the story of Hagar (ﷺ), who displayed unwavering strength as she ran between Safa and Marwa seeking water for her son, Prophet Ishmael (ﷺ). Her perseverance symbolizes endurance and reliance on Allah (ﷻ), qualities reflected in the Sa’i performed by pilgrims. The connection to the root highlights steadfastness and endurance, aligning the resilience of the white stone with the spiritual strength of faith.",
  "3333": "مَرْيَمُ refers to Mary (عَلَيْهَا الصَّلَاةُ وَالسَّلَامُ), the mother of Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ). The name مَرْيَمُ is of Hebrew origin and lacks a definitive root in Arabic. Despite this, Mary (عَلَيْهَا الصَّلَاةُ وَالسَّلَامُ) symbolizes purity, devotion, and unwavering faith. Her story represents chastity and spiritual dedication, inspiring believers to emulate her exemplary character. In the Qur'an, Mary (عَلَيْهَا الصَّلَاةُ وَالسَّلَامُ) is honored above all women, her story emphasizing the miraculous power of Allah (ﷻ), serving as a testament to His ability to bring forth life and His support for the righteous.",
  "3334": "مَزِيدٌ and related words also stem from the root ز-ي-د, with the root verb زَادَ meaning \"he increased,\" \"he grew,\" or \"he exceeded.\" مَزِيدٌ means \"more,\" \"additional,\" or \"extra,\" describing an abundance or surplus beyond what is expected or required. The root's dimensions extend to the idea of boundless generosity and continuous improvement.",
  "3335": "مَسَاقٌ and related words stem from the root س-و-ق, with the root verb ساقَ meaning \"he drove,\" \"he led,\" or \"he propelled.\" مَسَاقٌ means \"driving,\" \"leading,\" or \"the act of being driven.\" The connection lies in encapsulating the process or journey of movement towards a goal, reflecting the root's emphasis on propulsion and guidance. It can symbolize the path or course one takes, often implying an inevitable movement towards a particular end.",
  "3336": "مَسَخْنَا and related words stem from the root م-س-خ, with the root verb مَسَخَ meaning \"he transformed\" or \"he changed into another form.\" مَسَخْنَا refers to \"We transformed\" or \"We altered,\" capturing the act of changing something's essential nature, often in a negative or degrading sense. The root reflects the concept of distortion or metamorphosis, emphasizing a transformation that results in the loss of original identity or integrity. It symbolizes consequences tied to moral corruption or misdeeds, where the transformation reflects inner flaws or failings, highlighting themes of alteration, loss, and degradation.",
  "3337": "مَسَدٌ and related words stem from the root م-س-د, with the root verb مَسَدَ meaning \"he twisted\" or \"he plaited.\" مَسَدٌ refers to \"twisted fibers,\" \"palm-fiber,\" or a \"rope made from such fibers.\" The term reflects the act of twisting strands together to create a strong, cohesive rope, emphasizing the root's concept of twisting and binding. In classical Arabic, مَسَدٌ often denotes ropes crafted from palm fibers, flax, or leather, symbolizing strength, resilience, and the unity of individual elements combining to form something durable.",
  "3338": "الْمَسِيحُ and related words stem from the root م-س-ح, with the root verb مَسَحَ meaning \"he wiped\" or \"he anointed.\" الْمَسِيحُ means \"the anointed one\" or \"Messiah,\" a title attributed to Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ), signifying someone chosen and consecrated for a divine mission. The root’s concept of wiping or anointing reflects the ritual act of sanctification, symbolizing honor, divine selection, and purity. In the Qur'an, the stories of Prophet Yeshua (ﷺ) resonate deeply with this root, such as his ability by Allah’s (ﷻ) will to heal the blind and leper with a touch. مَسِيحُ can also metaphorically describe a traveler who traverses great distances, reflecting his physical journey and role in spreading divine guidance.",
  "3339": "مَسٌّ and related words stem from the root م-س-س, with the root verb مَسَّ meaning \"he touched\" or \"he felt.\" مَسٌّ means \"touch\" or \"contact,\" emphasizing the physical act of coming into contact. This form conveys a more general or abstract sense of touch, focusing on the act itself without necessarily implying its duration or mutuality. It highlights the significance of touch in human experience as a means of connection, influence, or even affliction, reflecting the root's central concept of contact.",
  "3340": "مَسَّ and related words stem from the root م-س-س, with the root verb مَسَّ meaning \"he touched,\" \"he felt,\" or \"he afflicted.\" مَسَّ captures the direct action of coming into physical contact. It extends beyond simple touch to include emotional or physical effects, such as experiencing hardship or affliction. This nuance highlights the dynamic nature of touch, where the act of contact can symbolize anything from gentle interaction to the onset of significant impact or difficulty, highlighting the transformative power of touch.",
  "3341": "مَسْئُولٌ and related words stem from the root س-أ-ل, with the root verb سَأَلَ meaning \"he asked.\" مَسْئُولٌ means \"one who is questioned\" or \"responsible.\" The connection lies in being accountable or subject to inquiry, embodying the root's concept of asking. مَسْئُولٌ emphasizes the concept of responsibility and that individuals will be questioned about their actions, highlighting the importance of accountability.",
  "3342": "مَسْبُوقٌ and related words stem from the root س-ب-ق, with the root verb سَبَقَ meaning \"he preceded\" or \"he surpassed.\" مَسْبُوقٌ is a passive form meaning \"one who is surpassed\" or \"one who is overtaken.\" It conveys the state of being left behind or outpaced by others, directly relating to the root's focus on precedence. This term highlights the dynamics of competition and progression.",
  "3343": "مَسْتُورٌ and related words stem from the root س-ت-ر, with the root verb سَتَرَ meaning \"he concealed\" or \"he covered.\" مَسْتُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"concealed\" or \"hidden.\" It describes something that is covered or kept out of sight, directly connecting to the root's concept of concealment. This term emphasizes being hidden or protected from exposure.",
  "3344": "مَسْجُورٌ and related words stem from the root س-ج-ر, with the root verb سَجَرَ meaning \"he kindled,\" \"he ignited,\" or \"he filled.\" مَسْجُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"filled\" or \"set ablaze,\" describing something that has been ignited or made full, often in a powerful or overwhelming manner. The root conveys themes of filling, overflowing, or igniting, whether with fire, water, or other elements. مَسْجُورٌ is often used to describe a state of intensity or fullness, such as the filling of seas or the kindling of fire, highlighting both the destructive and transformative potential of being completely consumed or filled.",
  "3345": "مَسْجُونٌ and related words stem from the root س-ج-ن, with the root verb سَجَنَ meaning \"he imprisoned\" or \"he detained.\" مَسْجُونٌ is a passive form meaning \"imprisoned\" or \"detained,\" describing someone subjected to confinement. The root connects to the idea of being bound by external authority or consequence, reinforcing the notion of punishment and accountability.",
  "3346": "مَسْجِدٌ and related words stem from the root س-ج-د, with the root verb سَجَدَ meaning \"he prostrated\" or \"he bowed down.\" مَسْجِدٌ refers to a \"mosque\" or \"place of prostration,\" a sacred space for worship and submission to Allah (ﷻ). This term includes three of Islam's most significant mosques: Al-Masjid Al-Haram, the Sacred Mosque in Makkah, which houses the Kaaba; Al-Masjid Al-Aqsa, the Furthest Mosque in Jerusalem, the first Qibla; and Al-Masjid An-Nabawi, the Prophet Muhammad’s (ﷺ) Mosque in Medina. All three hold profound spiritual significance and a special place in the hearts of the Muslim nation, symbolizing communal worship, reverence, and submission to Allah (ﷻ).",
  "3347": "مَسْحٌ and related words stem from the root م-س-ح, with the root verb مَسَحَ meaning \"he wiped,\" \"he rubbed,\" or \"he anointed.\" مَسْحٌ refers to \"wiping\" or \"stroking,\" emphasizing the act of passing one’s hand over a surface. This reflects the root's fundamental concept of gentle, deliberate contact. In classical Arabic, مَسْحٌ holds importance in physical and spiritual contexts, such as wiping during ablution to symbolize purification. The term also describes acts of care and inspection, illustrating the role of touch in communication, cleanliness, and ritual practices, connecting the physical act with symbolic renewal and devotion.",
  "3348": "مَسْحُورٌ and related words stem from the root س-ح-ر, with the root verb سَحَرَ meaning \"he bewitched.\" مَسْحُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"bewitched\" or \"enchanted.\" It describes someone affected by magic, directly connecting to the root's concept. This term emphasizes vulnerability to deceptive practices.",
  "3349": "مَسْرُورٌ and related words stem from the root س-ر-ر, with the root verb سَرَّ meaning \"he rejoiced\" or \"he made happy.\" مَسْرُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"made happy,\" \"delighted,\" or \"pleased.\" The connection lies in being the recipient of joy or happiness, reflecting the root's emphasis on delight. This term describes someone filled with joy, highlighting the effect of positive experiences or blessings.",
  "3350": "مَسْطُورٌ and related words stem from the root س-ط-ر, with the root verb سَطَرَ meaning \"he wrote,\" \"he lined,\" or \"he set in order.\" مَسْطُورٌ is a passive form meaning \"written,\" \"inscribed,\" or \"recorded.\" The connection lies in the state of being written down, reflecting the root's emphasis on inscribing and arranging text. This term signifies that something has been documented, emphasizing the permanence of the written word.",
  "3351": "مَسْغَبَةٌ and related words stem from the root س-غ-ب, with the root verb سَغِبَ meaning \"he was hungry\" or \"he suffered hunger.\" مَسْغَبَةٌ means \"famine\" or \"severe hunger,\" describing a state of extreme deprivation and scarcity of food. The root also carries connotations of weariness, fatigue, and weakness resulting from prolonged hunger, reflecting not just physical deprivation but also the exhaustion that accompanies it. This term highlights the depth of suffering caused by hunger, highlighting themes of vulnerability, hardship, and the importance of compassion toward those enduring such states of need.",
  "3352": "مَسْفُوحٌ and related words stem from the root س-ف-ح, with the root verb سَفَحَ meaning \"he poured forth\" or \"he shed.\" مَسْفُوحٌ means \"poured out\" or \"shed,\" and is often used in reference to blood. The root emphasizes uncontrolled spilling or shedding, reflecting the prohibition against consuming blood that has been deliberately drained. This highlights the emphasis on purity and restraint in dietary practices, ensuring physical health and spiritual cleanliness.",
  "3353": "مَسْكَنٌ and related words stem from the root س-ك-ن, with the root verb سَكَنَ meaning \"he dwelt,\" \"he resided,\" or \"he became still.\" مَسْكَنٌ means \"dwelling,\" \"residence,\" or \"abode.\" The term embodies the place where one finds rest and stillness, directly connecting to the root's concept of habitation and tranquility. It highlights the importance of a stable and peaceful home as a foundation for personal and familial well-being, reflecting the human need for a secure place to settle and find comfort."
};
